e=\"Stranger iOS Out Now\" /> Android (2014),<ref name=\"Stranger Android Out Now\" /> Mac (2015),<ref name=\"Stranger HD Mac\" /> Apple TV (2017)<ref name=\"Strange Apple TV\" />|| Oddworld Inhabitants (Xbox port), <br> Square One Games (Apple and Android ports)|| [[Electronic Arts]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2005/01/24/oddworld-strangers-wrath-3 |title= Oddworld Stranger's Wrath |publisher=IGN |date=2005-01-24 |accessdate=2013-02-07}}</ref> (Xbox port) <br> Oddworld Inhabitants (Apple and Android ports)|| First-person shooter/third-person platformer.\n|-\n| ''[[Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath|Stranger's Wrath HD]]'' || [[2010 in video gaming|2010]] || PC, Steam (2010), PS3 (2011), PS Vita (2012),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oddworldlibrary.net/blog/2011/06/oddworld-on-playstation-vita/ |title=Oddworld on PlayStation Vita|publisher=Oddblog |date=2011-06-07 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> [[Wii U]] (TBA) || [[Just Add Water (company)|Just Add Water Ltd.]] || Oddworld Inhabitants <br> || High definition remaster. Digital only.\n|-\n| ''[[Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee|Munch's Oddysee HD]]'' || [[2012 in video gaming|2012]] || PS3 (2012), [[PlayStation Vita|PS Vita]] (2014),<ref name=\"Munch on Vita This Week\" /> Mac (2016)<ref name=\"Munch Mac Release\" /> || Just Add Water Ltd. || Oddworld Inhabitants || High definition remaster. Digital only.\n|-\n| ''[[Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty!|New 'n' Tasty!]]'' || [[2014 in video gaming|2014]]<ref name=\"Sony 'Tasty' Press Release\" /> || PS4 (2014),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/06/10/oddworld-abes-oddysee-remake-new-n-tasty-coming-to-ps4/ |title=Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee remake 'New 'n' Tasty' coming to PS4 |publisher=Joystiq |date=2013-06-10 |accessdate=2013-06-11}}</ref> PS3, [[Xbox One]], Windows, OS X, Linux (2015),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2015/01/oddworld-new-n-tasty-release-dates-steam-ps3-xbox-one/ |title=Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty Release Dates For Steam, PS3 & Xbox One |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2015-01-15 |accessdate=2015-01-16}}</ref> PS Vita,<ref name=\"Tasty! Vita Release\" /> Wii U<ref name=\"Tasty! Wii Date\" /> (2016), iOS, Android, [[Nvidia Shield (set-top box)|Shield]] (2017),<ref name=\"iOS Android Shield\" /> || Oddworld Inhabitants, |Just Add Water Ltd.|| Oddworld Inhabitants || New version of ''Abe's Oddysee''. Digital only.\n|-\n| ''Soulstorm'' || 2020<ref name=\"Lanning Greggy 2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fAMWwrHFo2c |title=Is Competition Good? \u2013 The GameOverGreggy Show Ep. 177 (Pt. 4) |publisher=YouTube |date=2017-04-27 |accessdate=2017-05-11}}</ref> || || Oddworld Inhabitants, [[Frima Studio]], Fat Kraken Studios, Sabotage Studio || Oddworld Inhabitants || Retelling of ''Abe's Exoddus''.  \n|}\n\n===''Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee''===\n{{Main|Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee}}\n\nThe first game developed by Oddworld Inhabitants is 1997's ''Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee''. Published by [[GT Interactive]] for [[PlayStation]], [[DOS]] and [[Windows]] platforms, it is the first in their planned five-game Quintology of games set on the fictional planet of Oddworld. The game tells the story of Abe, a happy, ignorant factory worker and the destined savior of his mudokon race.<ref name=Schott>Carr, Diane, David Buckingham, Andrew Burn, Gareth Schott, 2006, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WSp7uW75TrYC Computer Games: Text, Narrative and Play], Polity</ref> Abe is a lowly floor waxer at RuptureFarms, a meat processing plant run by the evil glukkons on Oddworld's largest continent of Mudos. The plant makes sweet and savory treats by farming and slaughtering the wildlife that roam the rural areas surrounding the plant, and exploits 100 mudokons for slave labor to run their factory. When Abe discovers the glukkons' plan to increase their dwindling profits by using the mudokons in their new tasty treat, he vows to escape the plant and save his 99 friends. Along the way, he meets a spiritual guide that opens his mind to the mudokons' bond with nature and Abe's personal destiny to awaken the powerful mudokon gods and become the prophesied savior who would return his race to their sacred holy lands. The game is a side-scrolling 2D [[platformer]] with lifelike animation on top of photo-realistic backgrounds. Its revolutionary features included the ability to \"chant\" in order to possess and remotely control the bodies of Slig guards to solve puzzles or allow Abe to advance safely; and a feature called gamespeak, the ability for the player to engage in conversation with other mudokons to navigate them to safety. The game was later ported to Gameboy by Saffire under the title ''Oddworld Adventures''.\n\n===''Oddworld: Abe's Exoddus''===\n{{Main|Oddworld: Abe's Exoddus}}\n\nFollowing the success of ''Abe's Oddysee'', Oddworld temporarily shelved plans for the next game in their Quintology to produce an instant follow up that could capitalize on the popularity of the first game. The resultant spinoff game, ''Oddworld: Abe's Exoddus'' was released the following year in 1998, again published by GT Interactive for PlayStation and Windows platforms. A direct sequel to ''Oddysee'', ''Exoddus'' begins immediately after Abe returns from RuptureFarms with his fellow mudokons, receiving a vision from the spirits of his ancestors. They plead for his help in stopping the glukkons from digging up mudokon bones to make the addictive Soulstorm Brew.<ref name=bio>[http://www.oddworld.com/firsttenyears/universe/native/characters/mudokons/ow_abe_bio.html Abe biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060720104338/http://oddworld.com/firsttenyears/universe/native/characters/mudokons/ow_abe_bio.html |date=20 July 2006 }}, Official Oddworld Website.</ref> Along the way, Abe rescues more of his mudokon race and learns more about their sacred history, living in harmony with nature and the wildlife.<ref name=\"Robinson, John\">[http://www.cnn.com/TECH/computing/9902/04/oddworld/index.html Something strange is brewing in 'Oddworld: Abe's Exoddus'], CNN.</ref> Coming so quickly after the previous game, ''Exoddus'' used ''Oddysee'''s game engine, remaining a 2D side-scrolling platformer, albeit adding more, longer levels and extra features. Abe's abilities were expanded upon to include more communication options and wider chant abilities allowing the possession of other species.<ref name=Thomas>Thomas, Maureen, Fran\u00e7ois Penz, 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=_UozK9smjVcC Architectures of Illusion: From Motion Pictures to Navigable Interactive Environments], Intellect Books</ref> Mudokons were also further developed, now having moods that affect Abe's ability to communicate with them and enlist their co-operation.\n\n===''Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee''===\n{{Main|Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee}}\n\nOddworld Inhabitants' third game, ''Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee'' was the second of their planned five-game Quintology series. Released in 2001 as a direct sequel to their two previous entries, the game was published by [[Microsoft Game Studios]] exclusively for the Xbox. Abe returns, but the game introduces a new protagonist in Munch, the last living remnant of the near-extinct, amphibious gabbit creatures. The story again involves Abe embarking on a quest to free the weak from the tyranny of the powerful capitalist creatures that exploit them for their own gain. Players assume the dual roles of Abe and Munch as they team up to escape the vicious Vykkers who harvested the gabbits in order to profit from their eggs\u2014a delicacy on Oddworld\u2014and ultimately destroy the Vykker's Labs. The game marks the series' introduction into 3D environments, though retaining its roots as a platformer. It is also the first game to introduce a second protagonist, allowing the player to switch between Abe and Munch to take advantage of abilities exclusive to each character. Also pivotal was the expansion of elements that were only touched on in their two previous games, such as the ability to \"create characters and use them as allies to attack, defend and solve work problems in the world.\"<ref name=\"Xbox Interview Lanning\" /> Other changes include new chanting features, the ability for Abe to pick up objects or people, and power ups that affect gameplay.\n\n===''Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath''===\n{{Main|Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath}}\n\nVeering away from the Quintology a second time, Oddworld Inhabitants' fourth game was ''Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath'', published for the Xbox in 2005 by [[Electronic Arts]]. The first Oddworld game to be entirely independent of the Abe series, ''Stranger's Wrath'' is set in the Wild West of Oddworld and follows a bounty hunter known only as the Stranger, one of the last remaining \"steef\" on Oddworld, as he collects bounties for capturing outlaws in order to save enough \"moolah\" for a life-saving operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxm.co.uk/60957/features/oddworld-strangers-wrath-why-oddworlds-only-fps-deserves-a-second-chance/ |title=Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath \u2013 why Oddworld's only FPS deserves a second chance |publisher=Xbox Magazine |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> The game continues the 3D gameplay introduced by ''Munch's Oddysee'' and switches between first person perspective for shooting, and third person perspective for long range running, platform jumping and melee combat.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/17/technology/circuits/17game.html?_r=1&ex=1109307600&en=c4214af930777332&ei=5070&oref=slogin Underneath It All, Substance Sells,] ''New York Times''.</ref> It also moves away from Oddworld's reliance on puzzles in favor of an action-adventure style with elements of role playing. Its prominent new features included \"live ammunition\", where the player can use various in-game creatures and projectiles for differing effects; and the ability to use the game's money system to purchase various items and weapon upgrades.\n\n===''Oddboxx''===\nIn 2009, Lorne Lanning announced plans to make an Oddworld [[Online distribution|digital download]] package exclusively for PC to contain ''Abe's Oddysee'', ''Abe's Exoddus'', and for the first time on the platform, ''Munch's Oddysee'' and ''Stranger's Wrath''. When Oddworld Inhabitants unveiled their re-designed website on 4 November 2010, they declared the then in-development package would be titled ''Oddboxx''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/?p=249 |title=The Oddboxx &#124; Oddworld Inhabitants |publisher=Oddworld.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref> The European and U.S. prices of the ''Oddboxx'' were revealed on 14 December<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/?p=271 |title=Oddboxx \u2013 Euro and U.S. Prices. Also online retail partners announced! &#124; Oddworld Inhabitants |publisher=Oddworld.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref> and on 20 December 2010, it was released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/objects/037/037836.html |title=IGN: The Oddboxx |publisher=Pc.ign.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref> 30 [[Achievement (video gaming)|Achievements]] were added to ''Munch's Oddysee'', while ''Stranger's Wrath'' gained 20.\n\nOn 29 April 2011, Stewart Gilray announced at GameCityNights that they were planning an ''Oddboxx'' release for the PlayStation Network with the ''Stranger'' portion of the package to be the remastered edition they had been working on, though the release had been delayed to fix some bugs and add additional features like [[PlayStation Move]] and [[3DTV]] support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oddworldlibrary.net/blog/2011/04/oddworld-announcements-at-gamecitynights/ |title=Oddworld announcements at GameCityNights|publisher=Oddblog |date=2011-04-29 |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref> The ''Oddboxx'' finally saw release on 6 November 2013 for the PlayStation 3 in the European and Australian markets, which included the HD remakes of ''Munch'' and ''Stranger'' along with original versions of ''Abe's Oddysee'' and ''Exoddus''.<ref name=\"What Is Oddboxx\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/11/what-is-oddboxx/ |title=What Is \"Oddboxx\"? |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-11-06 |accessdate=2013-11-26}}</ref> But the studio is unable to release it to the North American market due to \"technicalities regarding the product publisher code... on two of the titles\" in the collection of four.<ref name=\"Oddboxx not in North America\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-11-06-four-oddworld-games-come-to-europe-tomorrow-in-the-oddboxx |title=Four Oddworld games come to Europe tomorrow in the Oddboxx |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2013-11-06 |accessdate=2013-11-26}}</ref>\n\n===''Abeboxx''===\nTo make up for ''Oddboxx'' not being released on the PlayStation 3 in the North American market, Oddworld Inhabitants released a mini collection entitled the ''Abeboxx'', composed of original versions of ''Abe's Oddysee'' and ''Abe's Exoddus'', to the PSN on 26 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/11/abeboxx-releases-on-playstation-in-the-us-today/ |title=Abeboxx Launches On PlayStation in America Tomorrow |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-11-25 |accessdate=2013-11-26}}</ref> It was subsequently released in Europe for PS3, PSP and PS Vita on 22 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2014/01/abeboxx-released-europe-ps3-psp-ps-vita/ |title=Abeboxx Released In Europe For PS3, PSP And PS VITA |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2014-01-22 |accessdate=2014-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===''Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty!''===\nThe first game solely developed by Just Add Water and published by Oddworld Inhabitants, ''New 'n' Tasty!'' is a retelling of ''Abe's Oddysee'' with 2.5D visuals. The game remained a side-scrolling platformer, but has done away with the original's flip screen presentation in favour of smooth continuous scrolling and a dynamic camera for zooming in and out based on the movements of the player and the scenery. The story is completely identical to ''Oddysee'' and new FMV sequences have been added to recreations of the originals to further illustrate the plot. The soundtrack too has been recreated from scratch, with additional pieces added. ''New 'n' Tasty!'' debuted on PS4 in July 2014, as part of an exclusive release with Sony in exchange for giving Oddworld Inhabitants their own booth at E3 in 2013, and centre stage at Sony's 2013 E3 presentation.<ref name=\"Venture Beat Bet\" /> Versions for Linux, Microsoft Windows and OS X were released on February 25, 2015 while the Xbox One version was released on March 27, 2015. The PlayStation 3 version was released on April 21, 2015 and the PlayStation Vita version was released on January 19, 2016.<ref>Oddworld Inhabitants (January 15, 2016) https://twitter.com/OddworldInc/status/688152263747977216 ''Twitter.com''</ref> The Wii U version was released on February 11.<ref name=\"Tasty! Wii Released\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2016/02/oddworld-new-n-tasty-out-now-for-wii-u/ |title=Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty Out Now for Wii U |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2016-02-11 |accessdate=2016-02-15}}</ref> The same day the Vita version was released, Oddworld Inhabitants and publisher Limited Run Games announced they would run a series of limited edition physical copies of ''New 'n' Tasty!'' for the Vita, marking the first physical copies of an Oddworld Inhabitants game since ''Stranger's Wrath'' released to the original Xbox in 2005.<ref name=\"Vita Lounge Physical\">{{cite web|url=http://thevitalounge.net/2016/01/18/oddworld-new-n-tasty-getting-a-physical-release/ |title=Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty getting a physical release |publisher=The Vita Lounge |date=2016-01-18 |accessdate=2016-01-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Limited Run Physical\">Limited Run Games (January 18, 2016) [https://twitter.com/LimitedRunGames/status/689217962860003330 \"We've officially hit 3,000 followers! Oddworld: New N' Tasty is coming to physical media. Await further details from @OddworldInc!\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> On 29 March 2016, Limited Run Games revealed there will also be a limited edition physical version for the PS4.<ref name=\"Limited Run PS4\">Limited Run Games (March 29, 2016) [https://twitter.com/LimitedRunGames/status/714900956593389569 \"RT and follow @OddworldInc + @LimitedRunGames for a chance to win a signed PS4 copy of Oddworld: New N' Tasty!\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> On December 14, 2017, ''New 'n' Tasty!'' was released on iOS, Android and NVIDIA Shield.<ref name=\"iOS Android Shield\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2017/12/oddworld-new-n-tasty-releases-ios-android-shield/ |title=Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty Releases On iOS, Android and Shield |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2017-12-14 |accessdate=2017-12-27}}</ref>\n\n===HD remasters===\nOn 3 September 2010, Just Add Water announced on their website that they had been working for nine months to bring a high definition remaster of ''Stranger's Wrath'' to the [[PlayStation Network]] as the beginning of an Oddworld revival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jawltd.com/2010/09/do-be-a-stranger-%E2%80%93-oddworld-returns/ |title=Do be a Stranger \u2013 Oddworld returns!|publisher=Just Add Water |date=2010-09-03 |accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> Talks with Microsoft in regards to an Xbox Live Arcade release were ongoing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-06-22-jaw-in-talks-with-us-publishers-over-strangers-wrath-hd-on-xbox-360 |title= JAW in talks with US publishers over Stranger's Wrath HD on Xbox 360 |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> The HD version of ''Stranger's Wrath'' was released to PS3 on 27 December 2011 and Steam on 9 September 2012 with upgraded features including 720p visuals, new character models and hidden unlockables.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oddworld.com/games-new-parent/game-strangers-wrath-hd/ |title=Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath HD |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |year=2011 |accessdate=2013-02-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201133402/http://www.oddworld.com/games-new-parent/game-strangers-wrath-hd/ |archivedate=1 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The game reached the top ten for the month of December 2011, despite only being released on 27 December.<ref name=\"Gilray Expansive DLC\">{{cite web|url=http://expansivedlc.com/interview-stewart-gilray-ceo-of-jaw-ltd/ |title=Interview: Stewart Gilray, CEO of JAW Ltd|publisher=Expansive DLC |date=2013-02-06 |accessdate=2013-02-08}}</ref> While the Xbox version was planned, it was officially cancelled on 21 June 2012,<ref name=\"eurogamer.net\"/> which Gilray then reiterated on 23 February 2013 when ''Stranger HD'' was finally completed.<ref name=\"Oddworld vs. PS Vita\" /> An update was released for the PS3 version in the European and Australian markets on 6 November 2013, which gave the game Leaderboards, 3D Stereoscopic TV and PlayStation Move support, along with reducing the file size by half.<ref name=\"Stranger Update Europe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/11/strangers-wrath-hd-gets-major-ps3-update/ |title=Stranger's Wrath HD Gets Major PS3 Update |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-11-06 |accessdate=2014-02-14}}</ref> That update was also provided to the American territory on 12 February 2014, the same day that a ''Stranger's Wrath HD'' Demo was made available for the PS3 in all territories.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2014/02/strangers-wrath-hd-ps3-demo-now-available-plus-update-news/ |title=Stranger's Wrath HD PS3 Demo Now Available! (Plus Update News) |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2014-02-12 |accessdate=2014-02-14}}</ref> On 11 August 2017, Oddworld Inhabitants released ''Stranger's Wrath'' for the Apple TV.<ref name=\"Strange Apple TV\">Oddworld Inhabitants (August 11, 2017) [OddworldInc: Surprise! Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath is out now for Apple TV! itunes.apple.com/us/app/oddworl\u2026 #AppleTV pic.twitter.com/ZgSjMqjWVn ] ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nThe PlayStation Vita port of ''Stranger'' was released on 18 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2011/11/22/ps-vita-launch-line-up-new-exclusive-games-and-more-revealed/ |title=PS Vita Launch Line-up, New Exclusive Games And More Revealed \u2013 PlayStation.Blog.Europe |publisher=Blog.eu.playstation.com |date=2011-11-22 |accessdate=2012-03-03}}</ref> It reached the top of the sales charts in Europe for December and second in the US despite being released in the middle of the month.<ref name=\"Gilray Expansive DLC\" />\n\nThe HD remaster of ''Munch's Oddysee'' was announced at GameCityNights on 29 April 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-04-29-oddworld-munchs-oddysee-hd-announced |title= Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee HD announced  |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2011-04-29 |accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> and released to PlayStation 3 on 19 December 2012 with upgrades similar to ''Stranger HD''{{'s}} and 45 trophies. Improvements were made to [[Graphical user interface|GUI]] and [[Front end processor|front end]].<ref name=\"Gilray Expansive DLC\" /> The Vita version of ''Munch HD'' was expected in the second quarter of 2013, but was halted during the final weeks of FQA testing when they discovered foreign language assets were missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/11/munchs-oddysee-hd-update/ |title= Munch's Oddysee HD Update  |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-11-20 |accessdate=2016-01-21}}</ref> Stewart Gilray later explained that the missing foreign language assets delayed an update to trophies and graphical errors<ref name=\"Joypad Podcast\" /> on the PS3 version, which needed to be released to all territories so that it could be applied to the Vita version.<ref name=\"Put An Intern\">{{cite podcast |host=Glenn Percival |title=Put An Intern On It |website=www.psnation.com |publisher=PS Nation |date=2013-12-23 |url=http://www.psnation.com/2013/12/23/episode-351-put-an-intern-on-it/ |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> The game is now being translated in full to make up for the missing foreign dialogue.<ref name=\"Joypad Podcast\" /> The game was released on December 17, 2014.<ref name=\"Munch on Vita This Week\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2014/12/17/new-playstation-store-resogun-oddword-munchs-oddysee-switch-galaxy-ultra/?adbid=545296187310346242&adbpl=tw&adbpr=36969785&emcid=social_20141217_37460677 |title=New on PlayStation Store: Resogun, Oddword: Munch's Oddysee, Switch Galaxy Ultra, more |publisher=PlayStation Blog |date=2014-12-17 |accessdate=2014-12-18}}</ref> It was also released for Mac through the App Store on January 6, 2016.<ref name=\"Munch Mac Release\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/oddworld-munchs-oddysee/id1001249388?ls=1&mt=12 |title=Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee |publisher=Apple |date=2016-01-06 |accessdate=2016-01-07}}</ref> A PC port is not in the works, but in discussions.<ref name=\"A Munch HD Update\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/10/an-update-on-munchs-oddysee-hd/ |title=An Update On Munch's Oddysee HD |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-10-18 |accessdate=2013-12-16}}</ref> However, on February 25, 2016, Oddworld Inhabitants revealed they are working with Square One Games on an updated port of ''Munch's Oddysee'' for the Steam platform that includes HD environment assets, though they stopped short of saying the entire game will be an HD remaster.<ref name=\"New Munch Port Steam\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2016/02/munchs-oddysee-2016-beta-released-on-steam/ |title=Munch's Oddysee 2016 Beta Released On Steam |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2016-02-25 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nThe HD remasters of ''Munch'' and ''Stranger'' were included with original versions of ''Abe's Oddysee'' and ''Exoddus'' in the PlayStation release of the ''Oddboxx'' on 6 November 2013 for European and Australian markets.<ref name=\"What Is Oddboxx\"/>\n\nA PlayStation 4 version of ''Stranger HD'' with \"new dynamics\" has been mentioned, contingent on discussions about budget and schedules.<ref name=\"Stranger PS4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-03-18-lorne-lanning-is-planning-to-bring-oddworld-strangers-wrath-to-ps4 |title=Lorne Lanning hopes to bring Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath to PS4 |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2014-03-20 |accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2016, Oddworld Inhabitants announced they have teamed with Limited Run Games to bring ''Stranger's Wrath HD'' to the PS Vita on a physical disc, their second such partnership with Limited Run Games, and only the second time they have published a game on disc since they became a self-publisher.<ref name=\"Stranger disc announce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2016/10/oddworld-announces-physical-collectors-edition-strangers-wrath-hd-ps-vita/ |title=Oddworld Announces Physical Collectors Edition of Stranger's Wrath HD For PS Vita |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2016-10-24 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> The limited edition is set for release on December 9, 2016,<ref name=\"Stranger HD Limited Date\">Oddworld Inhabitants (November 20, 2016) [https://twitter.com/oddworldinc/status/800243949491331072 \"Bookmark this page! Limited Edition PS Vita Stranger's Wrath goes live on December 9th. limitedrungames.com/products/limit\u2026 (inc map and poker cards)\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> and will come with a reversible cover, ''Stranger's Wrath''-themed poker cards and a map of the in-game Mongo River.<ref name=\"Stranger disc announce\" />\n\nOn February 9, 2018, Oddworld Inhabitants revealed that ''Munch's Oddysee HD'' would be the third game they publish on disc since their turn into independent developing, and the third instance in their partnership with Limited Run Games.<ref name=\"Munch HD Limited Announce\">Oddworld Inhabitants (February 9, 2018) [https://twitter.com/oddworldinc/status/961910953783824384 \"Power-ups to the People! Announcing Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee HD for PS Vita via @LimitedRunGames \u2013 out 23 February 2018. More details to follow!\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> The game will be released for the PS Vita on February 23, 2018 in a single disc format<ref name=\"Limited Munch Vita\">Oddworld Inhabitants (February 23, 2018) [https://twitter.com/oddworldinc/status/961910953783824384 \"6 hours to go! If you've not bought from @LimitedRunGames before, their buying guide might be useful \u2013 limitedrungames.com/pages/buying-g\u2026\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> and a collector's edition.<ref name=\"Limited Munch Collector\">Oddworld Inhabitants (February 23, 2018) [https://twitter.com/oddworldinc/status/966892085323288578 \"Soon! Are you ready? @LimitedRunGames\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\n===Other ports===\nOddworld Inhabitants announced that ''Stranger's Wrath HD'' would be coming to mobile devices iOS and Android.<ref name=\"Stranger on Mobile\" /> Developed by Square One Games, the port consists mostly of the original Xbox version's assets, but will use some aspects from the recent HD updates as well.<ref name=\"Expansive DLC Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://expansivedlc.com/interview-jaw-ltd/ |title=Interview: JAW Ltd |publisher=Expansive DLC |date=2013-06-24 |accessdate=2013-06-24}}</ref> The iOS version was released on November 27, 2014, coming with fully configurable controls and brand new graphical features.<ref name=\"Stranger iOS Out Now\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2014/11/strangers-wrath-out-now-for-ios-soon-for-android/ |title=Stranger's Wrath Out Now For iOS, Soon For Android |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2014-11-27 |accessdate=2014-11-29}}</ref> The Android version was released on December 8, 2014.<ref name=\"Stranger Android Out Now\">{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2014/12/08/console-classic-oddworld-strangers-wrath-comes-to-android-as-an-amazon-exclusive-for-now/ |title=[Update: Now On The Play Store!] Console Classic Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath Comes To Android As An Amazon Exclusive (For Now) |publisher=Android Police |date=2014-12-08 |accessdate=2014-12-08}}</ref>\n\n''Stranger's Wrath'' was released for Mac on February 9, 2015 through the App Store, including native Mac resolution (including 5K), iCloud integration to allow users to play and continue on their iOS-portable devices, fully remappable keyboard and mouse controls and gamepad support, Game Center achievements and leaderboards.<ref name=\"Stranger HD Mac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2015/03/strangers-wrath-now-available-on-the-app-store-for-mac/ |title=Stranger's Wrath Now Available On The App Store For Mac |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2015-03-09 |accessdate=2015-03-13}}</ref>\n\nStewart Gilray has hinted at porting ''Stranger's Wrath'' to PlayStation 4.<ref>Gilray, S. (23 March 2013) [https://twitter.com/stewartgilray/status/315552958777528320 \"Keep thinking about porting Stranger to PS4, just because we could\u2026\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nOn November 12, 2015, Oddworld Inhabitants released ''Munch's Oddysee'' to iOS,<ref name=\"Munch Out Now iOS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2015/11/munchs-oddysee-coming-to-ios-and-android/ |title=Munch's Oddysee Coming To iOS And Android |date=2015-11-11 |accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref> with the Android release following on November 28, 2015.<ref name=\"Munch on Android\">Oddworld Inhabitants (November 18, 2015) [https://twitter.com/OddworldInc/status/666645350300651521 \"Munch. Android. https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.oddworld.Munch \u2026 \" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2017 and September 29, 2017, ''Stranger's Wrath'' and ''Munch's Oddysee'' were released to the Apple TV.<ref name=\"Strange Apple TV\" /><ref name=\"Munch Apple TV\">Oddworld Inhabitants (September 29, 2017) [OddworldInc: Surprise (again!) \u2013 available now on Apple TV -> Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee! itunes.apple.com/us/app/oddworl\u2026 pic.twitter.com/YCE3S9UV5N ] ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nA Wii U version of ''Stranger's Wrath'' will be released, but the developers want to release ''New 'n' Tasty!'' on the platform first because Abe is a more Nintendo-friendly character and they expect ''Stranger's Wrath'' will alienate Nintendo gamers from the Oddworld universe if that is their first introduction to the franchise.<ref name=\"Moonhawk Gilray\" />\n\n==Upcoming titles==\n\n===Oddworld: Soulstorm===\n\nOn April 14, 2015, it was announced by Lanning that ''Abe's Exoddus'' would be getting a remake. Lanning said that Exoddus's success would contribute significantly to future ''Oddworld'' titles, and would be marketed more broadly than ''[[Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty!]]''.'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/04/14/oddworld-abes-exoddus-remake-in-the-works/|title=Oddworld: Abe's Exoddus remake in the works|author=Brenna Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=April 14, 2015|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2016 in an interview with Lorne Lanning, he told NintendoLife that the remake is about to go into production.<ref name=\"lanninginterview\">{{cite web|title=Alex Interviews Lorne Lanning \u2013 Create of Oddworld|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OHHlomOckXI|website=Youtube|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, it has been confirmed that ''Oddworld: Soulstorm'' would be the Abe's Exoddus remake. The game will be developed and published by Oddworld Inhabitants, [[Frima Studio]] and Fat Kraken Studios. The game is being developed on the [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] engine.\n\nIn an April 2016 interview with [[Game Informer]], Lanning said that because ''Abe's Exoddus'' took only nine months to make, its script wasn't perfect for this remake. He explained that ''Exoddus'' is going to be the spine for ''Oddworld: Soulstorm'' which will be about Soulstorm Brewery and the brew, hoping the game would be finished for a late 2017 release.<ref name=\"lanningexoddus\">{{cite web|title=Oddworld: Lorne Lanning on Soulstorm, VR Fraud and Hollywood|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AcqKAKpuyjw|website=YouTube|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016 in an podcast by Lorne Lanning, he said that the development of the game was going strong and a further announcement was due in the Fall of 2016. He said that the game is on target to be released in 2017 and it's going to be a platform-based game like ''New 'n' Tasty'' is. He also said that some Youtubers and their composer, Michael Bross will be doing some voice-over work for the game.\n\nIn September 2016 at the [[EGX (expo)|EGX Expo]], Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty's designer Matt Glanville said that Oddworld: Soulstorm is going to be a bigger version of Abe's Exoddus. There will be some areas and game mechanics that were from Exoddus and some new areas from Oddworld. The Quarma system from Munch's Oddysee will return and the path that the player takes will depend on the storyline. He also stated that Oddworld: Soulstorm is a sequel to New 'n' Tasty.<ref>{{Citation|last=EGX|title=EGX 2016: The Evolution Of Oddworld Game Design|date=2016-09-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U2AcGZd8P5Q|accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April 2017, Lanning revealed the release date of the game had been revised to 2018.<ref name=\"Lanning Greggy 2017\" />\n\n===''The Brutal Ballad of Fangus Klot''===\n\n[[File:The Brutal Ballad of Fangus Klot Artwork.jpg|thumbnail|right|The original artwork for ''Fangus Klot'' created by Oddworld Inhabitants.]]\n\nOriginally coming from discussions about a sequel to ''Stranger's Wrath'',<ref name=\"Reddit\" /> ''The Brutal Ballad of Fangus Klot'' is a standalone game, independent of the Oddworld Quintology, originally announced in an April 2005 issue of [[Game Informer]]. The story is set in a rural land resembling [[Afghanistan]]<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> far from the continent of Mudos where the first four Oddworld games were based, inspired by the \"United States propaganda approach\" of pretending to free the region, but really wanting to \"rob it and slaughter it and leave it as rubble\".<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> The invaders are a foreign species resembling an Eastern European<ref name=\"Odd Odd World\" /> or \"Russian mafia\"<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> whose genetics include traces of feline DNA. Fangus' history reveals canine DNA, allowing for Lanning's desire to \"play off of that dog versus cat theme\" that he's always wanted to visit\u2014\"one of those dynamic, eternal battles... myths that lie deep in our history of civilization... like good versus evil.\"<ref name=\"Odd Odd World\" /> The invaders have turned this \"beautiful landscape into meth labs,\"<ref name=\"Odd Odd World\" /> \"whilst the dogs find themselves fighting for scraps in a war-torn region.\"<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> Fangus is a shepherd who is directly affected by the invasion, \"finding out he's only got so long, and the circumstances that have [led] him to this position means he's going to have to fight,<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> following a similar journey to that of the [[Maximus Decimus Meridius|Roman general]] in [[Gladiator (2000 film)|''Gladiator'']].<ref name=\"Odd Odd World\" />\n\nOddworld Inhabitants delayed reacting to a rumor about the game which caused many to consider the development the playing of an [[April Fools' Day|April Fools' Day prank]]. In a June 2009 issue of Game Informer, Lorne Lanning officially spoke about the game, revealing concept art and story details, and plans to distribute the game digitally. A Mature rating by the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board|ESRB]] was expected due to dark tones and themes throughout the game. [[Majesco Entertainment]] was expected to publish the game for the Xbox before it was canceled when they failed to come to agreements with Sherry McKenna and Lorne Lanning. In a 9 May 2011 FAQ, an Oddworld Inhabitants representative confirmed ''Fangus Klot'' will be in future plans following ''The Hand Of Odd'' and ''Oddworld: New 'n' Tasty!''<ref name=\"Oddworld Inhabitants\"/> and Lanning further expressed his desire to make the game, though financing it is the obstacle.<ref name=\"Tell it like it is\" /><ref>Lanning, L. (15 August 2013) [https://twitter.com/lorne_lanning/status/367859629818007552 \"Cant... stop... thinking... Fangus.  He's a black hole relentlessly tugging my mind. dark, brutal, heart break.  Dammit. Just doesn't stop.\"] ''Twitter.com''</ref> The reluctance comes from it being an entirely untried IP that Lanning envisions costing $10M, which he says is not smart for an independent developer to take on at this stage of their success.<ref name=\"Odd Odd World\" /> Stewart Gilray has seen \"an original Xbox build\" of ''Fangus'', which does run,<ref name=\"What's Next\" /> but his company is no longer producing games for Oddworld Inhabitants. In March 2014, Lanning revealed he has been designing the game himself for a year and a half and that if ''New 'n' Tasty!'' sells 500,000 units, Oddworld Inhabitants would finance ''Fangus''<ref name=\"500K Funds New Game\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-03-18-new-n-tasty-needs-to-sell-500k-to-fund-an-original-new-oddworld-game |title= New 'n' Tasty needs to sell 500K to fund an original new Oddworld game |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2014-03-18 |accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref> because he expects it to cost between 5\u20136 million dollars.<ref name=\"Venture Beat Bet\" /> On August 12, 2015, Lanning said that if there's any indication that a remake of ''Exoddus'' will garner the same returns as ''New 'n' Tasty!'' has, then a new IP would be made.<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" />\n\n===''Oddworld: Hand of Odd''===\n{{Main|Oddworld: Hand of Odd}}\n\nHand of Odd was conceived as an online, [[open world]], [[real-time strategy]] game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-04-29-jaw-revives-oddword-hand-of-odd |title= JAW revives Oddworld: Hand of Odd |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> during the production of ''Munch's Oddysee''.<ref name=\"Lost Oddworld Projects\" /> Early information revealed its multiplayer aspects and its ability to be played from the perspective of Oddworld's peaceful mudokons or its greedy, corporate overlords, changing the aim and experiences of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.depthsofoddworld.net/games-handofodd.html |title=Hand of Odd|publisher=Depths of Oddworld |year=2005 |accessdate=2013-01-26}}</ref> Lanning wanted to create an RTS game that changed the previous model of two warring factions with the same goal of deforestation in order to build a militarised complex to overtake an opposition army.<ref name=\"Lost Oddworld Projects\" /> Instead, he wanted one of the two warring entities to be a native, shamanistic class \"focused on life-force [that] gain power by growing back trees and restoring the environment,\" in keeping with his video game development MO of \"the indigenous versus the industrial\" to help people \"understand real world problems in a world that (for everything other than its appearance) is very similar to ours.\"<ref name =\"New Era Oddworld\" /> But with the release of sub-par RTS games, the market began losing faith in the genre. Soon after, Oddworld Inhabitants' publisher was acquired by a company known for risk-averse decisions, so Lanning decided to shelve the game after just preliminary design and development, because the odds were stacked against them, not because of the quality of the game he wanted to make.<ref name=\"Lost Oddworld Projects\" /> However, the work made on the pre-production of the game helped flesh out details of Oddworld that have helped them understand their universe for future games, and the early footage excited Gilray at the time.<ref name=\"The Future's Odd\" /> Ongoing downloadable content was being considered before the game was halted when the studio redirected its goals towards multimedia development. The game was thought to have been revived when Just Add Water announced plans for its development<ref>{{cite web|title=Oddworld: The Hand of Odd revived, Stranger's Wrath HD delayed|url=http://www.neoseeker.com/news/16331-oddworld-the-hand-of-odd-revived-strangers-wrath-hd-delayed/|work=Daily Gaming News|publisher=Neoseeker|accessdate=2 May 2011|authorlink=Oddworld: The Hand of Odd revived, Stranger's Wrath HD delayed}}</ref> including launching a website with the original logo designed by Oddworld Inhabitants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.handofodd.com/ |title=Oddworld: Hand of Odd|publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |accessdate=2013-01-26}}</ref> Gilray said computers and tablets were the likely platform choices because strategy games and consoles don't mix,<ref name=\"The Future's Odd\" /> and because \"it works well with touchscreen interface or mouse control\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-04-29-jaw-revives-oddword-hand-of-odd |title= JAW revives Oddworld: Hand of Odd |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2013-01-26}}</ref> Just Add Water has seen \"the original bound ''Hand of Odd'' design document\"<ref name=\"What's Next\" /> which is four inches thick and was originally made in the late 1990s. However, plans for the game are not known, as Just Add Water ended their partnership with Oddworld Inhabitants at the end of 2015.<ref name=\"JAW Oddworld End\" />\n\n==Future==\nGiven that Oddworld Inhabitants now owns every single element of the Oddworld franchise,<ref name=\"What's Next\" /> and has provided Just Add Water with the full 15[[Terrabyte|TB]] archive of original assets from Oddworld's time in game development,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-the-making-of-oddworld-strangers-wrath-hd |title=The Making of Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath HD |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2012-01-28 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> the team at Just Add Water have a backlog of games to make.<ref name=\"Expansive DLC Interview\" /> It is Gilray's objective to focus on ''[[#Oddworld: Hand of Odd|Hand of Odd]]'', ''[[#Rumored games|Squeek's Oddysee]]'' and then continue with more of the Oddworld universe<ref name=\"Gamefreak Gilray Interview\" /> in \"rebuilding the Oddworld brand\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spong.com/feature/10110915/Feature-2013-Industry-Insights-with-Stewart-Gilray-Just-Add-Water |title=Features// 2013 Industry Insights with Stewart Gilray, Just Add Water |publisher=Spong |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-02-08}}</ref> According to the Oddworld timeline document Lanning gave to Gilray, the Oddworld planet's history has spanned two to three thousands years, while \"the games so far have covered two, maybe three hundred years... so right now there is no end in sight. Our limit is what we do and when we do it.\"<ref name=\"Gamefreak Gilray Interview\" /> There are also many unseen creatures integral to future Oddworld stories that originally came from designs cut from previous games and are waiting to be revealed as Abe ventures closer to the center of the planet's consumerism.<ref name=\"In Odd We Trust\" /> Gilray is also aware of a 'time encyclopaedia' written by Lanning that details a thousand years of the Oddworld planet's history, including other continents, species and civilisations only hinted at in previous games.<ref name=\"Joypad Podcast\" /> Gilray said the next logical game to build would be a remake of ''Abe's Exoddus'' because it would use the same engine as ''New 'n' Tasty!'' and be quicker to produce than an entirely new game, though they are open to continuing with a new game because \"Lanning's mind is already full of ideas.\"<ref name=\"What's Next\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/03/12/whats-next-for-oddworld-just-add-water-speaks/ |title=What's next for Oddworld? Just Add Water speaks |publisher=VG24/7 |date=2013-03-12 |accessdate=2013-03-12}}</ref> Lanning said in October that if they choose to focus on new content, that there are two possibilities on the table, stopping short of specifying what those games are because he does not want to make a promise and then fail to deliver, as he has done in the past.<ref name=\"Two Different Possibilities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/10/03/two-different-possibilities-for-brand-new-oddworld-content-sa/ |title='Two different possibilities' for brand new Oddworld content, says Lanning| publisher=Joystiq |date=2013-10-03 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\nOf his relationship to Just Add Water, Lanning said it is best \"to empower people with a sense of responsibility and trust [but] when we get on to new content, there's a whole other level of discretion that will go beyond that and then we'll see if they like working with me.\"<ref name=\"Nathan Interviews Lorne\" /> Lanning has explained that his role is not down in the trenches with the developers anymore because the templates and mechanics of the gameplay are done, and he trusts the developers at Just Add Water to use them in the construction of the game, but his input increases when new gameplay mechanics are developed, such as Stranger's Wrath's live ammo, or when they get close to shipping and he needs to inspect game controls.<ref name=\"Core Elements Lanning\" /> When he compares the relationship with Just Add Water to those his company had with publishers in the past, he feels their development team has a culture that can be nurtured better because the pressure to succeed is only coming from themselves, not an outside force they can't control, such as a publisher's demands and the risk of blowing a huge budget on lukewarm sales returns.<ref name=\"Properties Apocalypse\" /> Gilray says Lanning and Sherry McKenna are in constant communication with him, which assures him they still care about their brand.<ref name=\"The Future's Odd\" /> Though ultimately, they would all be waiting to see how well ''New 'n' Tasty!'' performs before making a decision.<ref name=\"Gamercast Tasty! Preview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamercast.net/e3-2013-oddworld-new-n |title=E3 2013: Oddworld New 'n' Tasty preview! |publisher=Gamercast |date=2013-07-01 |accessdate=2013-07-08}}</ref> Lanning revealed they require 500,000 units of ''New 'n' Tasty!'' to sell in order to fund a new game, but only 250,000 had been sold to fund a new version of ''Exoddus'',<ref name=\"Polygon 500K Units\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/3/18/5521318/new-n-tasty-sales-will-ensure-abes-exoddus-remake-and-new-oddworld |title= New 'n Tasty sales of more than 500K will ensure Abe's Exoddus remake and new Oddworld game |publisher=Polygon |date=2014-03-18 |accessdate=2014-03-31}}</ref> because he believes more money is spent on the research and development period in order to produce \"new mechanics, getting something creative that's different,\" whereas a new version of ''Exoddus'' would use the mechanics and assets already created in the original game to use as a blueprint.<ref name=\"Venture Beat Bet\" /> Gilray said a committee begun working on the next game in the middle of summer, 2013.<ref name=\"Kinder Gentler Stewart\" />\n\nIn February 2013, Stewart Gilray said the Just Add Water team had expanded to include 22 staff, of which \"a few\" are from the original Oddworld Inhabitants development team headed by Lanning between 1997 and 2005.<ref name=\"Oddworld vs. PS Vita\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-oddworld-vs-playstation-vita |title=Oddworld vs. PlayStation Vita |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2013-02-23 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref> Just Add Water has a \"rough plan for the next couple of years\",<ref name=\"What's Next\" /> and now that their team has expanded with their budgets increased due to the success of their games, it is Gilray's intention to \"bridge that gap between the traditional definition of \"indie\" and \"AAA\" projects\".<ref name=\"Oddworld vs. PS Vita\" /> Lanning says he has not been this excited about gaming in over a decade because of the combination of exciting Triple-A titles on next-gen consoles, the wider, creative innovations on the indie front, and the revisiting of old genres like 2D platforming that were lost many years earlier getting a fresh look with newer technology.<ref name=\"Hit List Q&A\" /> He firmly believes that Oddworld must define creativity, and \"the day that it's not defining that for the public, I think we've got major issues... we have to see that we're getting stale before our audience does.\"<ref name=\"Icons Part 2\" /> They are humbly building the risks and the scale of their games to get the company back onto that Triple-A playing field, the only difference being that they are self-financing the development instead of relying on a publisher to fund it, which creates an environment for the developers down in the trenches that doesn't leave them burning out with hard work and the stress of failure threatening their livelihoods.<ref name=\"PSNation Interview Gilray Lanning\" /> They are being careful with their business decisions to ensure that the brand is maintained.<ref name=\"Oddworld Q&A\" /> Lanning has considered \"crowdfunding\" options like Kickstarter to produce his game, but would prefer to fund them solely with the money made from his games,<ref name=\"Two Different Possibilities\" /> with a future goal to be producing Triple-A titles entirely self-funded.<ref name=\"Triple-A to Indie 3\" />\n\nOddworld Inhabitants said that Munch will feature in all future Quintology games,<ref>Oddworld Inhabitants (17 April 2013) [https://twitter.com/OddworldInc/status/324829818573185024 \"@gravy__ He will be in all future Quintology games.\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> and that while they are not planning on a new game centred on Abe, he will feature in a future game.<ref name=\"Oddworld Q&A\" /> The team is developing three more titles under the Unity engine.<ref name=\"Game Informer Screenshots\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/oddworld_abes_oddysee_new_n_tasty/b/playstation4/archive/2014/02/21/abe-s-oddysee-remake-is-looking-great-in-exclusive-screenshots.aspx |title=Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee New N' Tasty! |publisher=Game Informer |date=2014-02-21 |accessdate=2014-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Possible games==\n\n* '''''SligStorm''''': Originally discussed during the development of ''Munch's Oddysee'', this 2D platforming bonus game, in the same vein as ''Abe's Exoddus'', was shelved due to the move from 2D platforming into 3D games.<ref name=\"Oddworld Q&A\" /> The player would assume the role of an albino slig<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pressstarttodrink.blogspot.com.au/2010/04/new-oddworld-project-confirmed-for-xbla.html |title=New Oddworld Project Confirmed for XBLA |publisher=Blogspot |date=2010-04-02 |accessdate=2013-02-25}}</ref> living in Rupture Farms and being picked on by other sligs for being different, until he decides to turn against his kind and work on the inside to assist the escape of the mudokons by shooting other sligs.<ref name=\"Joypad Podcast\" /> On 9 May 2011, an Oddworld Inhabitants representative released a list of FAQ answers in relation to future games, confirming ''Sligstorm'' will be worked on after \"Abe HD\" and \"The Hand of Odd,\"<ref name=\"Oddworld Inhabitants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/about/faq/ |title=FAQ|publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2011-05-09 |accessdate=2012-02-01}}</ref> which was echoed in July 2011 by a representative on the Oddworld Inhabitants Facebook page.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=219253608111652&set=a.176207019082978.28797.165852613451752&type=1&theater |title=Stranger's Wrath HD |publisher=Facebook |date=2011-07-15 |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> Lanning believes the difficulty lies in making players sympathize with a slig as the hero of a game.<ref name=\"Reddit\" />\n* '''''Oddworld: Squeek's Oddysee''''': The third game in the original Quintology following the first two entries ''Abe's Oddysee'' and ''Munch's Oddysee''. In the 9 May 2011 FAQ, an Oddworld Inhabitants representative confirmed ''Squeek's Oddysee'' is on the cards after ''The Hand of Odd'', ''Abe HD'', ''The Brutal Ballad of Fangus Klot'' and ''Sligstorm'' are released.<ref name=\"Oddworld Inhabitants\"/> Lanning indicated it had a \"messed up story\" and would take a lot of time and money.<ref name=\"Reddit\" />\n* '''''Oddworld: Munch's Exoddus''''': Expected to be a bonus game based on ''Munch's Oddysee'' outside of the original pentalogy, in the same way that ''Abe's Exoddus'' was to ''Abe's Oddysee'', plans for ''Munch's Exoddus'' evolved to become ''Stranger's Wrath''.<ref name=\"Munch II Became Stranger\" /> It would have featured Munch traveling to a land named \"Ma'Spa\" to hatch the Gabbit eggs acquired from the original game. Oddworld Inhabitants confirmed the game is not currently in the works, but may be a possibility.<ref name=\"Dear Alf April\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/04/dear-alf-april-2013/ |title=Dear Alf April 2013 |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-04-02 |accessdate=2013-04-03}}</ref>\n* '''''Oddworld: Slave Circus''''': Lorne Lanning has revealed plans for a game entitled ''Oddworld: Slave Circus''. \"It is seriously whack. You start the game by buying a slave. Think Gladiators on Oddworld. Have done a tremendous amount of work on this and have never mentioned it. But it is in the coffer and there may be some light for it down the road. But has some other contingencies depending on it... It's insane. Hopefully not so insane it won't come to life.\"<ref name=\"Reddit\" />\n* '''''Stranger's Wrath 2''''': The first mention of a sequel to ''Stranger's Wrath'' came on 17 January 2013 when Oddworld Inhabitants posted on their a blog asking readers to vote on the preferred next title to be developed by Just Add Water\u2014''Stranger 2'' being one of the options.<ref name=\"Next? Votes\" />\n* '''''Stranger Arena''''': A competitive multiplayer game in the Oddworld universe that utilised the mechanics established in ''Stranger's Wrath''.<ref name=\"Stranger Arena Eurogamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-04-04-lorne-lanning-explains-his-canned-stranger-arena-multiplayer-game |title=Lorne Lanning explains his canned Stranger Arena multiplayer game |publisher=Eurogamer |date=2014-04-04 |accessdate=2016-06-02}}</ref> Players would control multiple \"Strangers\" and battle head to head or in groups in multiplayer modes. Lanning envisioned it being a game changer for the multiplayer genre because players had the ability to shift between third-person and first-person, as in Stranger's Wrath, unlike other shooters like ''Halo'' and ''Call of Duty'', allowing players a more strategic method of switching between third-person for melee and evasion abilities, or first-person for shooting. He also intended to include RTS aspects of defensive base building to combat players who focused on speed and accuracy.<ref name=\"Stranger Arena Eurogamer\" /> The game engine was initially built on the original Xbox system, and to port it over to a modern system like Unity would involve \"re-architecting\" that the developers cannot afford to risk time and money on at this stage.<ref name=\"Stranger Arena Eurogamer\" />\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=November 2012}}\n\nAdventure Classic Gaming called Lanning \"a legend in both the game and the film industries.\"<ref name=\"Lanning Bio\" />\n\nThe ''Oddworld'' games have received more than 100 industry awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/10/24/bizbuzz/sony_odd/ |title= Microsoft takes Oddworld |publisher=CNN Money |date=2000-10-24 |accessdate=2013-02-08}}</ref> ''Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee'' received more than 24 awards and three nominations from the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] over 1997 and 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/editorials/op-ed/5255-This-Week-in-Gaming-History |title= This Week in Gaming History |publisher=The Escapist |date=2008-09-15 |accessdate=2013-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Oddworld Inhabitants combined the [[Full motion video|FMV]] [[cutscene]]s from ''Exoddus'' and submitted them to the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] as ''Abe's Exoddus: The Movie'' for Oscar consideration in the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Animated Short]] category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/1998/10/14/abe-reaches-for-an-oscar |title= Abe Reaches for an Oscar |publisher=IGN |date=1998-10-13 |accessdate=2013-02-08}}</ref> The short did not win the Oscar.<ref name=\"Icons Part 2\" />\n\nIn 1998, footage from ''Abe's Oddysee'' and ''Abe's Exoddus'' was used in the music video for Get Freaky by German electro-dance music project [[Music Instructor]]. Footage from ''Munch's Oddysee'' along with new CG animations of Abe and Munch were used in the music video for a European song called 'Use Yur Imagination' in 2002.<ref name=\"Munch Music Video\">Ballistic Publishing, ''The Art of Oddworld: The First Ten Years 1994\u20132004'', page 233</ref>\n\nIn 2010, ''[[Game Informer]]'' included Oddworld on the list of ten gaming franchises that should be revived, specifically counting for the return of Abe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2010/06/30/ten-franchises-that-deserve-a-revival.aspx?PostPageIndex=2 |title=Ten Franchises That Deserve A Revival |publisher=Gameinformer |date=2010-06-30 |accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref>\n\nOddworld's mascot Abe was planned as DLC for the PlayStation 3's All-Stars Battle Royale, but was later cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screwattack.com/news/dart-cancelled-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-dlc-character |title=Dart Cancelled As PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale DLC Character |publisher=Screw Attack |date=2013-06-30 |accessdate=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105053424/http://www.screwattack.com/news/dart-cancelled-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-dlc-character |archivedate=5 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDue to Stewart Gilray's [[Crowdfunding in video games|crowdfunding]] support during the development of ''[[Thomas Was Alone]]'', the creator named a game character after Abe from the Oddworld franchise.<ref name=\"Kinder Gentler Stewart\">{{cite podcast |host=Glenn Percival |title=A Kinder, Gentler Stewart |website=www.psnation.com |publisher=PS Nation |date=2013-05-07 |url=http://www.psnation.com/2013/05/07/episode-318-a-kinder-gentler-stewart/ |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\n\nLanning hinted at plans to release a game that involved action figures from the Oddworld universe in a pamphlet released at E3 in 1999.<ref name=\"Nathan Interviews Lorne\" /> Called ''Oddwars'', Lanning still has all the material he created for the game and may release it in the future.\n\nOn 30 July 2007, the composer of ''Stranger's Wrath'', Michael Bross, released a soundtrack of music from the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Michael+Bross/Music+From+Oddworld:+Stranger%27s+Wrath+Vol.+1 |title=Music From Oddworld: Stranger's Wrath Vol. 1 |publisher=Last.fm |accessdate=2013-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOddworld Inhabitants, in conjunction with book publisher Ballistic Publishing, released ''The Art of Oddworld Inhabitants: The First Ten Years 1994 \u2013 2004'' in 2008, an art book featuring design concepts, paintings and in-game screenshots made between 1994 and 2004 during the development of ''Abe's Oddysee'', ''Abe's Exoddus'' and ''Munch's Oddysee''.<ref>Ballistic Publishing, ''The Art of Oddworld: The First Ten Years 1994\u20132004''</ref> The book came in four editions: hard cover, soft cover, leather-bound edition (limited to 1000 copies, each individually numbered and with a certificate of authenticity) and folio edition (limited to 100 copies, each individually numbered and with a certificate of authenticity).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballisticpublishing.com/books/oddworld/ |title=The Art of Oddworld Inhabitants |publisher=Ballistic Publishing |accessdate=2013-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2011, to promote the release of ''Stranger's Wrath HD'', a [[List of LittleBigPlanet 2 downloadable content packs|''LittleBigPlanet 2'' costume]] was made available for purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2011/11/littlebigplanet-gets-stranger/ |title=LittleBigPlanet Gets Stranger|publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2011-11-04 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> An XMB Dynamic Theme of ''Stranger's Wrath'' was also released a few weeks later,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2011/11/stranger-dynamic-theme-for-ps3/ |title=Stranger Dynamic Theme for PS3|publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2011-11-21 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> followed by a LittleBigPlanet 2 costume of Munch on 30 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oddworldlibrary.net/blog/2011/11/munch-costume-for-littlebigplanet/ |title=Munch costume for LittleBigPlanet|publisher=Oddblog |date=2011-11-28 |accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2011, clothing company Insert Coin announced they would be selling t-shirts from their website with Stranger's Wrath images to promote the impending release of the remastered game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insertcoinclothing.com/blog/2011/09/its-an-oddworld-after-all/ |title=ITS AN ODDWORLD AFTER ALL|publisher=Insert Coin |date=2011-09-09 |accessdate=2013-03-05}}</ref> Two different designs were manufactured based on locales within the game. Jonny Eveson has also released designs for an Oddworld-themed T-shirt based on ''Abe's Exoddus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/03/you-cried-out-for-a-teeshirt-we-listened/ |title=You cried out for a teeshirt, we listened |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-03-15 |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> The design came in three colors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oddworldlibrary.net/blog/2013/03/an-oddworld-t-shirt-is-coming/ |title=An Oddworld t shirt is coming |publisher=Oddblog |date=2013-03-15 |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> Oddworld Inhabitants uploaded the design to Qwertee seeking votes from the public to have the design accepted and put up for sale<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qwertee.com/product/probrewbly-bad/ |title=Probrewbly Bad By oddworldinc |publisher=Qwertee |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> and on 1 April, the design was successfully added and put on sale for 48 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddworld.com/2013/04/soulstorm-brew-design-available-on-qwertee-later-today/ |title=SoulStorm Brew design available on Qwertee later today! |publisher=Oddworld Inhabitants |date=2013-04-01 |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Oddworld Inhabitants teamed up with publisher Limited Run Games for a one-off special release of ''New 'n' Tasty!'' on physical media if the publisher could reach 3000 followers on Twitter.<ref name=\"Limited 3000 Vita\">Oddworld Inhabitants (January 15, 2016) [https://twitter.com/OddworldInc/status/687765142365450242 \"https://twitter.com/OddworldInc/status/687765142365450242\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> On January 18, Limited Run Games reached that goal and confirmed ''New 'n' Tasty!'' would be released on disc for the PlayStation Vita.<ref name=\"Vita Lounge Physical\" /> On 29 March 2016, Limited Run Games revealed there would also be a limited edition physical version for the PS4.<ref name=\"Limited Run PS4\">Limited Run Games (March 29, 2016) [https://twitter.com/LimitedRunGames/status/714900956593389569 \"RT and follow @OddworldInc + @LimitedRunGames for a chance to win a signed PS4 copy of Oddworld: New N' Tasty!\" ] ''Twitter.com''</ref> On October 24, 2016, Oddworld Inhabitants announced their second partnership with Limited Run Games to bring ''Stranger's Wrath HD'' to disc for the Vita platform only.<ref name=\"Stranger disc announce\" /> The game was released on December 9.<ref name=\"Stranger HD Limited Date\" /> On February 9, 2018, Oddworld Inhabitants announced their third partnership with Limited Run Games to release ''Munch's Oddysee HD'' on disc for the PS Vita.<ref name=\"Munch HD Limited Announce\" /> The game has been released on February 23.<ref name=\"Munch HD Limited Announce\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oddworld.com Official homepage]\n* [http://games.ign.com/objects/026/026309.html IGN OWI overview]\n\n{{Oddworld series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences members]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Luis Obispo County, California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Oddworld]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oddworld_Inhabitants"}
{"title_page": "The Economist", "text_new": "{{about||the profession|Economist|6=other uses|7=The Economist (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|English weekly news and international affairs publication}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Economist\n| logo = The Economist Logo.svg\n| image = 'The Economist' cover (September 8, 2001).png\n| caption = Cover of the 8 September 2001 issue{{#tag:ref|The title and its design are references to the book ''[[No Logo]]'' (1999).|group=\"nb\"}}\n| type = [[Weekly newspaper]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n| format = <!--The Economist is a newspaper printed in magazine format. Leave as \"magazine\" for format, with no hyperlink.-->Magazine\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1843|09}}\n| founder = [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]\n| owners = [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]]\n| ISSN = 0013-0613\n| political = <!--This is not an indiscriminate list, only the big, umbrella political camps The Economist belongs to.-->\n[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eb87e2f4-ffc9-11e9-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Liberalism at Large \u2014 how The Economist gets it right and spectacularly wrong|last=Zevin|first=Alexander|date=December 20, 2019|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Social liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Radical centrism]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-0|work=The Economist|title=Is The Economist left- or right-wing?|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21564556|work=The Economist|title=True Progressivism|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Adelphi, London|1-11 John Adam Street]]<br>[[City of Westminster|Westminster]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| editor = [[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]\n| website = {{url|economist.com}}\n| circulation = 909,476 (print)<br>748,459 (digital)<br>1.6 million (combined)\n| circulation_date = July-December 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=The Economist - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/432 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| logo_size = 135px\n| depeditor = [[Tom Standage]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Economist''''' is an international [[weekly newspaper]] <!--It is a newspaper NOT a magazine. Please see discussion at Talk:The Economist/Archive 2. The latter is \"printing format\" NOT a publication. Do not change wording without another editorial consensus on the talk as per WP:TITLE it is still a newspaper no matter how it is printed.-->printed in [[Magazine|magazine-format]] that focuses on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]], [[world news]], international business, and politics. Based in [[London|London, England]], the newspaper is owned by the [[Economist Group]], with core  editorial offices in major cities in North America, Europe, Asia, and the [[Middle East]]. In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million). In 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million. Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016. The newspaper stresses [[data journalism]] and analysis over original reporting, to both criticism and acclaim.<!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Article uses British English, e.g. \"-ise\" over \"-ize\". See: WP:ISE.--><!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->\n\nFounded in 1843, ''The Economist'' was first circulated by Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] to muster support for abolishing the British [[Corn Laws]] (1815\u201346), a system of [[Tariff|import tariffs]]. Over time, the newspaper's coverage expanded further into [[political economy]] and eventually began running articles on current events, finance, commerce, and British politics. Throughout the mid- to late- 20th century, it greatly expanded its layout and format, adding [[Op-ed|opinion columns]], special reports, [[Political cartoon|political cartoons]], [[Letter to the editor|reader letters]], cover stories, art critique, book reviews, and technology features. The paper is often recognizable by its [[fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] nameplate and illustrated, topical covers. Individual articles are written anonymously, with [[Byline|no byline]], in order for the paper to speak as one collective voice. The paper is supplemented by its sister lifestyle magazine, ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]]'', and a variety of podcasts, films, and books.\n\nThe [[The Economist editorial stance|editorial stance of ''The Economist'']] primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]], [[Social liberalism|social]], and most notably, [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring policies and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper advocates for [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]]. Despite a pronounced editorial stance, it is seen as having little [[reporting bias]], rigorous [[Fact-checking|fact checking]] and strict [[copy editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/when-will-magazines-stop-trying-to-copy-the-economist|title=Why Time and Newsweek Will Never Be The Economist|last=Pressman|first=Matt|date=April 20, 2009|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/|title=10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts|last=Leadership|first=The Berlin School Of Creative|date=February 1, 2017|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Its extensive use of [[Word play|word play]], [[Subscription (finance)|subscription]] prices, and typical depth of coverage has linked the paper with a high-income and educated readership, drawing both positive and negative connotations in the [[Western world|Western World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/01/31/why-the-economist-swapped-its-famous-elitist-marketing-emotional-messaging|title=Why The Economist swapped its famous elitist marketing for emotional messaging|last=Burnell|first=Ian|date=31 January 2019|website=The Drum|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/09/business/media/09economist.html|title=The Economist Tends Its Sophisticate Garden|date=2010-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In line with this, it claims to have influential readership of prominent business leaders and [[Policy|policy-makers]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:James Wilson by Sir John Watson-Gordon.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] founded the newspaper to \"take part in a severe [[Debate|contest between intelligence]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reed.edu/reed-magazine/articles/2017/contest-letter-editor.html|title=The Contest|last=Lydgate|first=Chris|date=March 1, 2017|website=Reed Magazine|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2017}}</ref>|208x208px]]\n''The Economist'' was founded by the British businessman and banker [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] in 1843, to advance the repeal of the [[Corn Laws]], a system of import tariffs.<ref>[http://mitpress.typepad.com/mitpresslog/2007/01/from_corn_laws_.html From the Corn Laws to Your Mailbox], The MIT Press Log, 30 January 2007. Retrieved 11 June 2010.</ref> A [[prospectus (finance)|prospectus]] for the \"newspaper\" from 5 August 1843 enumerated thirteen areas of coverage that its editors wanted the publication to focus on:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=1873493|title=Prospectus|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=5 August 1843}}</ref>\n# Original [[editorial|leading articles]], in which free-trade principles will be most rigidly applied to all the important questions of the day.\n# Articles relating to some practical, commercial, agricultural, or foreign topic of passing interest, such as foreign treaties.\n# An article on the elementary principles of [[political economy]], applied to practical experience, covering the laws related to prices, wages, rent, exchange, revenue and taxes.\n# [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] reports, with particular focus on commerce, agriculture and free trade.\n# Reports and accounts of popular movements advocating free trade.\n# General news from the [[Court of St. James's]], the [[Greater London|Metropolis]], the [[Historic counties of England|Provinces]], Scotland, and Ireland.\n# Commercial topics such as changes in fiscal regulations, the state and prospects of the markets, imports and exports, foreign news, the state of the manufacturing districts, notices of important new mechanical improvements, shipping news, the money market, and the progress of railways and public companies.\n# Agricultural topics, including the application of geology and [[chemistry]]; notices of new and improved [[List of agricultural machinery|implements]], state of crops, markets, prices, foreign markets and prices converted into English money; from time to time, in some detail, the plans pursued in Belgium, Switzerland, and other well-cultivated countries.\n# [[British overseas territories|Colonial]] and foreign topics, including trade, produce, political and fiscal changes, and other matters, including [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9s]] on the evils of restriction and protection, and the advantages of free intercourse and trade.\n# Law reports, confined chiefly to areas important to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture.\n# Books, confined chiefly, but not so exclusively, to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture, and including all treatises on political economy, finance, or taxation.\n# A commercial [[gazette]], with prices and statistics of the week.\n# [[Letter to the editor|Correspondence and inquiries]] from the newspaper's readers.\n\nWilson described it as taking part in \"a severe contest between intelligence, which presses forward, and an unworthy, timid ignorance obstructing our progress\", a phrase which still appears on its masthead as the publication's mission.<ref name=\"opinion\">{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/ |title=Opinion: leaders and letters to the Editor |work=The Economist |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> It has long been respected as \"one of the most competent and subtle Western periodicals on public affairs\".<ref name=\"Leites\">{{cite journal|title=The Politburo Through Western Eyes|pages=159\u2013185|author=Nathan Leites|journal=[[World Politics]]|year=1952|volume=4|issue=2|jstor=2009044|doi=10.2307/2009044}}{{subscription required}}</ref> It was cited by [[Karl Marx]] in his formulation of socialist theory, because Marx felt the publication epitomised the interests of the bourgeoisie <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YauuCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA242&dq=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&pg=PA242#v=onepage&q=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&f=false|title=Karl Marx: His Life and Thought|last=McLellan|first=David|date=1 December 1973|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349155149|language=en}}</ref> He wrote: \"the London ''Economist'', the European organ of the aristocracy of finance, described most strikingly the attitude of this class.\"<ref>Karl Marx, ''The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte'', VI (1852)</ref> In 1915, revolutionary [[Vladimir Lenin]] referred to ''The Economist'' as a \"journal that speaks for British millionaires\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theeconomist/status/955168910852153344?lang=en|author=The Economist|website=twitter.com}}</ref> Additionally Lenin claimed that ''The Economist'' held a \"bourgeois-pacifist\" position and supported peace out of fear of [[revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1915/may/01c.htm|title=Bourgeois Philanthropists and Revolutionary Social-Democracy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:The Economist 2019 1 o.jpg|left|thumb|A panel of journalists and public policy leaders at ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s 2019 India Summit.<nowiki/>]]In 1920, the paper's circulation rose to 6,170.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} In 1934, it underwent its first major redesign. The current [[fire engine red]] nameplate was created by [[Reynolds Stone]] in 1959.<ref name=\"About us\" /> In January 2012, ''The Economist'' launched a new weekly section devoted exclusively to China, the first new country section since the introduction of one on the United States in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economist Launches New China Section|url=http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|work=Asian Media Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201210032/http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|archivedate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 1991, [[James Fallows]] argued in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that ''The Economist'' used editorial lines that contradicted the news stories they purported to highlight.<ref name=\"fallows\" /> In 1999, [[Andrew Sullivan]] complained in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that it uses \"marketing genius\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/london-fog|title=London Fog|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> to make up for deficiencies in original reporting, resulting in \"a kind of ''[[Reader's Digest]]''\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3874750,00.html|title=Not so groovy.|date=14 June 1999|work=The New Republic|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref> for America's corporate elite.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Finkel|first=Rebecca|date=July 1999|title=Nasty barbs fly between New Republic and Economist|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/news1999/july99/news4707.html|magazine=Media Life|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107024913/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news1999/july99/news4707.html|archivedate=7 November 2015|accessdate=27 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"its writers rarely see a political or economic problem that cannot be solved by the trusted three-card trick of privatisation, deregulation and liberalisation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Stern|first=Stefan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/aug/21/pressandpublishing.business1|title=Economist thrives on female intuition|date=21 August 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 January 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' named it the best English-language paper noting its strength in international reporting where it does not feel moved to cover a faraway land only at a time of unmitigated disaster\" and that it kept a wall between its reporting and its more conservative editorial policies.<ref>Entertainment: 50 Best Magazines, Chicago Tribune, 15 June 2006.</ref> In 2008, [[Jon Meacham]], former editor of ''Newsweek'' and a self-described \"fan\", criticised ''The Economist''{{'s}} focus on analysis over original reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/node/39374|title=Jon Meacham Wants Newsweek to Be More Like Hayes' Esquire|work=The New York Observer|accessdate=27 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522125448/http://www.observer.com/node/39374|archive-date=22 May 2008}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Economist'' was [[2012 ICT Skype controversy|accused]] of hacking into the computer of Justice [[Mohammed Nizamul Huq]] of the [[Bangladesh]] Supreme Court, leading to his resignation as the chairman of the [[International Crimes Tribunal (Bangladesh)|International Crimes Tribunal]].<ref name=\"ICTleaks\">{{cite magazine|date=8 December 2012|title=Discrepancy in Dhaka|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/12/bangladesh|magazine=The Economist}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/bangladesh-crimes-tribunal-accuses-the-economist-magazine-of-hacking-judges-computer/2012/12/09/8f248da2-421e-11e2-8c8f-fbebf7ccab4e_story.html|title=Economist accused of hacking ICT judge's computer|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks2\">{{cite news|last=Hossain|first=Farid|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121209/as-bangladesh-war-crimes|title=Economist magazine faces contempt in Bangladesh|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/bangladeshi-war-crimes-tribunal-issues-notice-to-the-economist/1041394|title=Bangladeshi war crimes tribunal issues notice to The Economist|date=6 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-economist-pearson_55cb31f0e4b0923c12beac28?ir=Business&section=business&kvcommref=mostpopular|title=Pearson Unloads $731 Million Stake in the Economist|date=12 August 2015|work=HuffPost|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Shareholders ===\n[[File:Economist building London1.jpg|thumb|The Economist Building, until 2017, in [[London]], England on [[St James's Street]].|alt=]][[Pearson plc]] held a 50% shareholding via [[Financial Times|The Financial Times Limited]] until August 2015. At that time, Pearson sold their share in the Economist. The [[Agnelli family]]'s [[Exor (company)|Exor]] paid \u00a3287m to raise their stake from 4.7% to 43.4% while the Economist paid \u00a3182m for the balance of 5.04m shares which will be distributed to current shareholders.<ref name=\"West\">{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref> Aside from the Agnelli family, smaller shareholders in the company include [[Cadbury family|Cadbury]], [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]] (21%), [[Schroders|Schroder]], [[Baron Layton|Layton]] and other family interests as well as a number of staff and former staff shareholders.<ref name=\"West\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/agnellis-rothschilds-close-in-on-economist-magazine-sale-pearson/|title=Agnellis, Rothschilds close in on Economist|date=11 August 2015|work=POLITICO|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Trustee|board of trustees]] formally appoints the editor, who cannot be removed without its permission. Although ''The Economist'' has a global emphasis and scope, about two-thirds of the 75 staff journalists are based in the London borough of [[City of Westminster|Westminster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/so-whats-the-secret-of-the-economist-347699.html|title=So what's the secret of 'The Economist'?|date=26 February 2006|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Editor ===\n[[File:Zanny Minton Beddoes World Economic Forum 2013 cropped.jpg|thumb|254x254px|[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]] was appointed editor in 2015, first joining as an [[emerging markets]] correspondent in 1994.]]\nThe [[editor-in-chief]], commonly known simply as \"the Editor\", of ''The Economist'' is charged with formulating the paper's editorial policies and overseeing corporate operations. Since its 1843 founding, the editors have been:\n\n*[[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]: 1843\u20131857\n*[[Richard Holt Hutton]]: 1857\u20131861<ref>The ''Concise Dictionary of National Biography'' makes him assistant editor 1858\u20131860</ref>\n*[[Walter Bagehot]]: 1861\u20131877<ref>He was Wilson's son-in-law</ref>\n*[[Daniel Conner Lathbury]]: 1877\u20131881<ref>[[s:The Times/1922/Obituary/Daniel Conner Lathbury|A journalist and biographer]]</ref> (''jointly'')\n*[[Robert Harry Inglis Palgrave]]: 1877\u20131883 (''jointly'')\n* Edward Johnstone: 1883\u20131907<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|title=economist150\u5468\u5e74\uff081993\uff09 \u2013 \u7ecf\u6d4e\u5b66\u4eba\u8d44\u6599\u5e93 \u2013 ECO\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51 \u2013 Powered by Discuz! Archiver|author=Discuz! Team and Comsenz UI Team|accessdate=29 June 2015|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922170122/http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Francis Wrigley Hirst]]: 1907\u20131916\n* Hartley Withers: 1916\u20131921\n*[[Walter Layton, 1st Baron Layton|Sir Walter Layton]]: 1922\u20131938\n*[[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]]: 1938\u20131956\n*[[Donald Tyerman]]: 1956\u20131965\n*[[Alastair Burnet|Sir Alastair Burnet]]: 1965\u20131974\n*[[Andrew Knight (journalist)|Andrew Knight]]: 1974\u20131986\n*[[Rupert Pennant-Rea]]: 1986\u20131993\n*[[Bill Emmott]]: 1993\u20132006\n*[[John Micklethwait]]: 2006\u20132014<ref>{{cite news|title=John Micklethwait leaving the Economist to join Bloomberg News|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/09/john-micklethwait-leaving-economist-joining-bloomberg|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 December 2014|last1=Sweney|first1=Mark}}</ref>\n*[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]: 2015\u2013present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/zanny-minton-beddoes/|title=Zanny Minton Beddoes|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Opinions==\n{{Main|The Economist editorial stance}}\nThe editorial stance of ''The Economist'' primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]] and [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring polices and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper favors [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/17732859|title=Globalisation: The redistribution of hope|date=16 December 2010|work=The Economist|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref> When the newspaper was founded, the term \"[[economism]]\" denoted what would today be termed \"[[economic liberalism]]\". The activist and journalist [[George Monbiot]] has described it as [[neoliberalism|neo-liberal]] while occasionally accepting the propositions of [[Keynesian economics]] where deemed more \"reasonable\".<ref name=\"Grauniad\">{{cite news|author=George Monbiot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/jan/11/economy.g8|title=George Monbiot, Punitive \u2013 and it works|work=The Guardian|date=11 January 2005|accessdate=25 May 2012|location=London}}</ref> The weekly favours a [[carbon tax]] to fight [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11543656|title=Buttonwood: Let them heat coke|journal=The Economist|date=14 June 2008|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> According to one former editor, Bill Emmott, \"the ''Economist''{{'}}s philosophy has always been liberal, not conservative\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/monarchy/story/0,2763,408484,00.html|title=Time for a referendum on the monarchy|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=Comment| date=8 December 2000| first=Bill|last=Emmot| location=London}}</ref> [[File:David Hume and Adam Smith statues.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[Adam Smith]] (''right'') and philosopher [[David Hume]] (''left'') represent the newspaper's foundational beliefs of ''[[laissez-faire]]'' [[Economic policy|policies]], [[self-sufficiency]], [[Protectionism|anti-protectionism]] and [[free trade]].|alt=]]Individual contributors take diverse views. ''The Economist'' favours the support, through [[central bank]]s, of banks and other important corporations. This principle can, in a much more limited form, be traced back to [[Walter Bagehot]], the third editor of ''The Economist'', who argued that the Bank of England should support major banks that got into difficulties. [[Karl Marx]] deemed ''The Economist'' the \"European organ\" of \"the aristocracy of finance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Marx|first=Karl|title=The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte|year=1852|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1852/18th-brumaire/ch06.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper has also supported liberal causes on social issues such as recognition of gay marriages,<ref>[https://www.economist.com/PrinterFriendly.cfm?story_id=2515389 Let them wed], cover article on 4 January 1996</ref> legalisation of drugs,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100602002643/http://www.drogasedemocracia.org/Arquivos/the-economist.pdf How to stop the drug wars], cover article on 7 March 2009.  The publication calls legalisation \"the least bad solution\".</ref> criticises the [[Taxation in the United States|US tax model]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21545981|title=Tax reform in America: A simple bare necessity|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=4 February 2012}}</ref> and seems to support some government regulation on health issues, such as smoking in public,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/16333351|title=Smoking and public health: Breathe easy|journal=The Economist|date=10 June 2010|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> as well as bans on spanking children.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11455006 \"Spare The Rod, Say Some\"], ''The Economist'', 31 May 2008.</ref> ''The Economist'' consistently favours guest worker programmes, parental choice of school, and amnesties<ref>[https://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=6744217 Sense, not Sensenbrenner], The Economist, 30 March 2006</ref> and once published an \"obituary\" of God.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/obituary/1999/12/23/god|title=Obituary: God|last=|first=|date=23 December 1999|work=The Economist|access-date=}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also has a long record of supporting gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/13447986|title=Lexington: Reflections on Virginia Tech|date=8 April 2009|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' has endorsed the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (in 2005), the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] (in 2010 and 2015),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/29/the-economist-backs-conservatives \"The Economist backs the Conservatives\"], ''The Guardian'' (PA report), 29 April 2010.</ref><ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite journal|title=Who should govern Britain?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21650113-despite-risk-europe-coalition-led-david-cameron-should-have-second-term-who|journal=The Economist|accessdate=11 May 2015|date=2 May 2015}}</ref> and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (in 2017 and 2019) at general election time in Britain, and both [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidates in the United States. ''Economist.com'' puts its stance this way:\n\n{{quotation|What, besides free trade and free markets, does ''The Economist'' believe in? \"It is to the Radicals that ''The Economist'' still likes to think of itself as belonging. The extreme centre is the paper's historical position\". That is as true today as when Crowther [Geoffrey, ''Economist'' editor 1938\u20131956] said it in 1955. ''The Economist'' considers itself the enemy of privilege, pomposity and predictability. It has backed conservatives such as [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]]. It has supported the Americans in [[Vietnam]]. But it has also endorsed [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Bill Clinton]], and espoused a variety of liberal causes: opposing capital punishment from its earliest days, while favouring penal reform and decolonisation, as well as\u2014more recently\u2014gun control and gay marriage.<ref name=\"About us\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/help/about-us#About_The_Economist|title=About us|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>}}\n''The Economist'' frequently accuses figures and countries of corruption or dishonesty. In recent years, for example, it criticised [[Paul Wolfowitz]], [[World Bank]] president; [[Silvio Berlusconi]], Italy's Prime Minister (who dubbed it ''The Ecommunist'');<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2005/09/324682.html|title=Report of Rome anti-war demo on Saturday 24th with photos|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=[[Independent Media Center]] }}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]], the late president of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]; [[Robert Mugabe]], the former head of government in [[Zimbabwe]]; and, recently, [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]], the president of Argentina.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Cristina in the land of make believe|work=The Economist|date=1 May 2008|url=https://www.economist.com/world/la/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11293743}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also called for [[impeachment of Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton's impeachment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/1998/09/17/just-go|title=Just go|date=1998-09-17|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> and, after the emergence of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=2647493|title=Resign Rumsfeld|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=6 May 2004}}</ref> for [[Donald Rumsfeld]]'s resignation. Though ''The Economist'' initially gave vigorous support for the [[Iraq War|US-led invasion of Iraq]], it later called the operation \"bungled from the start\" and criticised the \"almost criminal negligence\" of the Bush Administration's handling of the war, while maintaining, in 2007, that pulling out in the short term would be irresponsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RRRTGGP|title=Mugged by reality|accessdate=9 April 2007|work=The Economist|date=22 March 2007}}</ref> In the 2004 US election, the editors \"reluctantly\" backed John Kerry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_QTVPPQ|title=Crunch time in America|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=2 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=3329802|title=The incompetent or the incoherent?|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=28 October 2004}}</ref> In the 2008 US election ''The Economist'' endorsed [[Barack Obama]], while using the front cover of the issue published on the eve of the election to promote his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?source=most_commented&story_id=12511171| work=The Economist| title=It's time|date=30 October 2008}}</ref> In the 2012 US election, Barack Obama was again endorsed: the editorial said that they preferred Obama on the economy, foreign policy and health care, but criticised him for running a negative campaign against Romney and for a \"...poor appreciation of commerce.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Our American Endorsement. Which one? |url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21565623-america-could-do-better-barack-obama-sadly-mitt-romney-does-not-fit-bill-which-one?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709 |newspaper=The Economist |date=3 November 2012 |accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the Economist endorse [[Hillary Clinton]], and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] due \"[p]artly because she is not Mr Trump, but also in the hope she can show that ordinary politics works for ordinary people\u2014the sort of renewal that American democracy requires.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2016/11/05/americas-best-hope|title=America's best hope|date=2016-11-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nIn an editorial marking its 175th anniversary, ''The Economist'' criticised adherents to liberalism for becoming too inclined to protect the political status quo rather than pursue reform.<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/essay/2018/09/13/the-economist-at-175|title=The Economist at 175|accessdate=17 September 2018|work=The Economist|date=13 September 2018}}</ref>{{Non-primary source needed|date=May 2019}} The paper called on liberals to return to advocating for bold political, economic and social reforms: protecting [[free market]]s, land and tax reform in the tradition of [[Georgism]], [[open immigration]], a rethink of the [[social contract]] with more emphasis on education, and a revival of [[liberal internationalism]].<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\" />\n\n==Tone and voice==\nThough it has many individual columns, by tradition and current practice the newspaper ensures a uniform voice\u2014aided by the anonymity of writers\u2014throughout its pages,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/styleguide/introduction|title=Style Guide | accessdate=8 February 2013|work=The Economist|date=27 September 2011}}</ref> as if most articles were written by a single author, which may be perceived to display dry, understated wit, and precise use of language.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/research/styleGuide/index.cfm?page=673927|title=The Economist \u2013 Tone|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |title=Johnson |accessdate=27 December 2006 |work=The Economist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219221031/http://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |archivedate=19 December 2006 }}</ref> <!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->''The Economist'' has traditionally\u2014albeit not always consistently\u2014persisted in referring to itself as a \"[[newspaper]]\", rather than a \"[[news magazine]]\", due to [[Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|its legal classification as a newspaper]] in Britain, its transition from [[broadsheet]] to glossy colour format, and its general focus on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] as opposed to specialist subjects.<ref name=\"pgazette\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist''{{'}}s treatment of economics presumes a working familiarity with fundamental concepts of classical economics. For instance, it does not explain terms like [[invisible hand]], [[macroeconomics]], or [[demand curve]], and may take just six or seven words to explain the theory of [[comparative advantage]]. Articles involving economics do not presume any formal training on the part of the reader and aim to be accessible to the educated layman. It usually does not translate short French (and German) quotes or phrases. It does describe the business or nature of even well-known entities, writing, for example, \"[[Goldman Sachs]], an investment bank\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2008/02/21/a-bank-by-any-other-name|title=A bank by any other name|date=2008-02-21|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' is known for its extensive use of [[word play]], including puns, allusions, and metaphors, as well as alliteration and assonance, especially in its headlines and captions. This can make it difficult to understand for those who are not native English speakers.<ref>Richard J. Alexander, \"Article Headlines in ''The Economist'': An Analysis of Puns, Allusions and Metaphors\", ''Arbeiten aus Anglistik und Amerikanistik '''11''':2:159-177 (1986) {{jstor|43023400}}''</ref>\n\n===Editorial anonymity===\n[[File:The Economist Article.jpg|thumb|''Economist'' articles typically do not carry [[Byline|bylines]], anonymously publishing their work. |211x211px]]\nArticles often take a definite editorial stance and almost never carry a [[byline]]. Not even the name of the editor is printed in the issue. It is a long-standing tradition that an editor's only signed article during their tenure is written on the occasion of their departure from the position. The author of a piece is named in certain circumstances: when notable persons are invited to contribute opinion pieces; when journalists of ''The Economist'' compile special reports (previously known as surveys); for the Year in Review special edition; and to highlight a potential [[conflict of interest]] over a book review. The names of ''The Economist'' editors and correspondents can be located on the media directory pages of the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory|title=Media directory|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Online blog pieces are signed with the initials of the writer and authors of print stories are allowed to note their authorship from their personal web sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://andreaskluth.org/2008/11/20/why-the-economist-has-no-bylines/|title=Why The Economist has no bylines |work=Andreaskluth.org|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=20 November 2008 }}</ref> \"This approach is not without its faults (we have four staff members with the initials \"J.P.\", for example) but is the best compromise between total anonymity and full bylines, in our view\", wrote one anonymous writer of The Economist.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-1/|title=Why are The Economist's writers anonymous? |journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 September 2016|date=4 September 2013 }}</ref> There are three editorial and business areas in which the anonymous ethos of the weekly has contributed to strengthening its unique identity: collective and consistent voice, talent and newsroom management, and brand strength and clarity. <ref>{{cite journal |last=Arrese |first=\u00c1ngel |title=\"\u201cIt\u2019s Anonymous. It\u2019s The Economist\u201d. The Journalistic and Business Value of Anonymity\" |journal=Journalism Practice |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2020.1735489}}</ref>\n\nThe editors say this is necessary because \"collective voice and personality matter more than the identities of individual journalists\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/help/about-us|title=The Economist \u2013 About us|accessdate=11 June 2012|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> and reflects \"a collaborative effort\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|title=Economist Editor Micklethwait brings his global perspective to the Twin Cities|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=29 April 2008|publisher=MinnPost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705161308/http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|archive-date=5 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In most articles, authors refer to themselves as \"your correspondent\" or \"this reviewer\". The writers of the titled opinion columns tend to refer to themselves by the title (hence, a sentence in the \"Lexington\" column might read \"Lexington was informed...\").\n\nAmerican author and long-time reader [[Michael Lewis (author)|Michael Lewis]] criticised the paper's editorial anonymity in 1991, labelling it a means to hide the youth and inexperience of those writing articles.<ref name=\"fallows\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/1991/10/-quot-the-economics-of-the-colonial-cringe-quot-about-the-economist-magazine-washington-post-1991/7415/|title=The Economics of the Colonial Cringe: Pseudonomics and the Sneer on the Face of The Economist.|accessdate=27 April 2008|work=The Washington Post|date=16 October 1991}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2019/07/01/bestselling-author-michael-lewis-has-it-all-figured-out/|title=Bestselling Author Michael Lewis Has It All Figured Out|last=High|first=Peter|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Although individual articles are written anonymously, there is no secrecy over who the writers are as they are listed on ''The Economist''{{'s}} website, which also provides summaries of their careers and academic qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media directory|url=http://mediadirectory.economist.com/|work=The Economist|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Later, in 2009, Lewis included multiple ''Economist'' articles in his [[anthology]] about the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], ''[[Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lewis|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Panic.html?id=ZXUOASHVf_YC|title=Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity|date=2009|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-06514-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[John Ralston Saul]] describes ''The Economist'' as a \"...[newspaper] which hides the names of the journalists who write its articles in order to create the illusion that they dispense disinterested truth rather than opinion. This sales technique, reminiscent of pre-Reformation Catholicism, is not surprising in a publication named after the social science most given to wild guesses and imaginary facts presented in the guise of inevitability and exactitude. That it is the Bible of the corporate executive indicates to what extent received wisdom is the daily bread of a managerial civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Doubter's Companion: A Dictionary of Aggressive Common Sense |id={{ASIN|0743236602|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\n==Circulation==\n[[File:The Economist Display.jpg|thumb|A display of newspapers in [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]] supermarket, depicting the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\nEach of ''The Economist'' issue's official date range is from Saturday to the following Friday. ''The Economist'' posts each week's new content online at approximately 2100 Thursday evening UK time, ahead of the official publication date.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist launches on Android|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/08/service-announcement|accessdate=26 February 2018|work=The Economist|date=2 August 2011}}</ref> From July to December 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million.<ref name=\"pgazette\" /> However, on a weekly average basis, the paper can reach up to 5.1 million readers, across their print and digital runs.<ref name=\"pgazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/economist-boasts-15m-magazine-circulation-and-36m-social-media-followers/|title=The Economist boasts 1.5m magazine circulation and 36m social media followers|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date=March 8, 2016|website=Press Gazette|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1877, the publication's circulation was 3,700, and in 1920 it had risen to 6,000. Circulation increased rapidly after 1945, reaching 100,000 by 1970.<ref name=\"About us\" /> Circulation is audited by the [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]] (ABC). From around 30,000 in 1960 it has risen to near 1 million by 2000 and by 2016 to about 1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://digiday.com/publishers/economist-aims-double-circulation-profits-5-years/|title=The Economist Plans to Double Circulation Profits in 5 Years|magazine=[[Digiday]] |author=Lucinda Southern |date=17 February 2016 |access-date=7 July 2016}}</ref> Sales inside North America were in 2007 around 54 per cent of the total, with sales in the UK making up 14 per cent of the total and continental Europe 19 per cent. ''The Economist'' claims sales, both by subscription and at newsagents, in over 200 countries. Of its American readers, two out of three earn more than $100,000 a year.<ref name=\"gainsreaders\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5250996|title='Economist' Magazine Wins American Readers|date=8 March 2006|accessdate=27 December 2006|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] }}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' once boasted about its limited circulation. In the early 1990s it used the slogan \"''The Economist'' \u2013 not read by millions of people\". \"Never in the history of journalism has so much been read for so long by so few,\" wrote [[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]], a former editor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D3B56996BE43&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM\n| title=\"Economist\" aspires to influence, and many say it does.|accessdate=14 May 2008|format=pay archive|work=The Chicago Tribune|first=Ray|last=Moseley}}</ref>\n\nThe Economist Newspaper Limited is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[The Economist Group]]. The publications of the group include the ''CFO'' brand family as well as the annual ''The World in...'', and the bimonthly [[lifestyle magazine]], ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]].'' Sir [[Evelyn Robert de Rothschild]] was Chairman of the company from 1972 to 1989.\n\n==Letters==\n''The Economist'' frequently receives letters from senior businesspeople, politicians, ambassadors, and from spokespeople for various government departments, non-governmental organisations and lobbies. Well-written or witty responses from anyone are considered, and controversial issues frequently produce a torrent of letters. For example, the survey of [[corporate social responsibility]], published January 2005, produced largely critical letters from [[Oxfam]], the [[World Food Programme]], [[United Nations Global Compact]], the Chairman of [[BT Group]], an ex-Director of [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] and the UK [[Institute of Directors]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.business-humanrights.org/Links/Repository/542754 |title= Compilation: Full text of responses to Economist survey on Corporate Social Responsibility (January\u2013February 2005)|accessdate=3 February 2007|work=Business & Human Rights}}</ref>\n\nMany of the letters published are critical of its stance or commentary. After ''The Economist'' ran a critique of [[Amnesty International]] and human rights in general in its issue dated 24 March 2007, its letters page ran a reply from Amnesty, as well as several other letters in support of the organisation, including one from the head of the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=8954694|title=Letters: On Amnesty International and human rights, Iraq, tax breaks 4&nbsp;April 2007|accessdate=9 November 2007|work=The Economist|date=4 April 2007}}</ref> Rebuttals from officials within regimes such as the Singapore government are routinely printed, to comply with local [[right-of-reply]] laws without compromising editorial independence.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CnZjYJ3TduUC&pg=PA173 |title=The Media Enthralled: Singapore Revisited|author=Francis T. Seow|year=1998|pages=171\u2013175|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|accessdate=25 May 2012|isbn=9781555877798}}</ref>\n\nIt is extremely rare for any comment by ''The Economist'' to appear alongside any published letter. Letters published in the paper are typically between 150 and 200 words long (and began with the salutation \"Sir\" until the editorship of Zanny Minton Beddoes, the first female editor; they now have no salutation). Previous to a change in procedure, all responses to on-line articles were usually published in \"The Inbox\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/debate/theinbox/ |title=Latest blog posts |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> Comments can now be made directly under each article.\n\n==Features==\n[[File:A stack of Economist papers.jpg|thumb|A stack of ''Economist'' papers, ordered by publication date. ''Pictured'': the 14 October 2019 issue. ]]\n''The Economist''{{'}}s primary focus is world events, politics and business, but it also runs regular sections on science and technology as well as books and the arts. Approximately every two weeks, the publication includes an in-depth special report<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/printedition/specialreports |title=Special reports |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> (previously called [[survey article|surveys]]) on a given topic. The five main categories are Countries and Regions, Business, Finance and Economics, Science and Technology, and Other. Every three months, it publishes a technology report called ''Technology Quarterly''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/science/tq/ |title=Technology Quarterly |work=The Economist |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> or TQ, a special section focusing on recent trends and developments in science and technology.\n\nSince July 2007, there has also been a complete audio edition of the paper available 9&nbsp;pm London time on Thursdays.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Katie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/11/pressandpublishing.business1 |title=Economist launches audio magazine|work=The Guardian|location=London |date=11 July 2007 |accessdate=21 September 2016 }}</ref> The audio version of ''The Economist'' is produced by the production company ''Talking Issues''. The company records the full text of the newspaper in [[MP3]] format, including the extra pages in the UK edition. The weekly 130 MB download is free for subscribers and available for a fee for non-subscribers.\n\nThe publication's writers adopt a tight style that seeks to include the maximum amount of information in a limited space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/StyleGuide/|title=The Economist style guide|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist }}</ref> [[David G. Bradley]], publisher of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', described the formula as \"a consistent world view expressed, consistently, in tight and engaging prose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp|title=A Seven Year Ambition|work=mediabistro.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010200210/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp |archivedate=10 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThere is a section of [[economic statistics]]. Tables such as employment statistics are published each week and there are special statistical features too. It is unique among British weeklies in providing authoritative coverage of official statistics and its rankings of international statistics have been decisive.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3WVLKKSOcGYC&pg=PA88|page=88|title=Great expectations\u2014the social sciences in Great Britain|publisher=Commission on the Social Sciences|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7658-0849-3}}</ref> In addition, ''The Economist'' is known for its [[Big Mac Index]], which it first published in 1986, which uses the price of the hamburger in different countries as an informal measure of the [[purchasing power parity|purchasing power]] of currencies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NZnk5C2r8qEC&pg=PA396|page=396|title=International Economics|author=Paul R. Krugman, Maurice Obstfeld|publisher=Pearson Education|year=2009|isbn=978-0-321-55398-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Economist|title=On the Hamburger Standard|date=6\u201312 September 1986}}</ref>\n\n=== Columns ===\nThe publication runs several opinion columns whose names reflect their topic:<!--Bolded because these columns redirect here, per WP:BOLD.-->\n\n*[[File:Economist Cartoon.jpg|thumb|A [[political cartoon]] published by the newspaper in November 2010, depicting  the [[European debt crisis|2010 European sovereign debt crisis]].|alt=|253x253px]]'''''Babbage''''' (Technology): named for the inventor [[Charles Babbage]], this column was established in March 2010 and focuses on various technology related issues.\n*'''''Bagehot''''' (Britain): named for [[Walter Bagehot]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|t\n}}), 19th-century British constitutional expert and early editor of ''The Economist''. Since April 2017 it has been written by [[Adrian Wooldridge]], who succeeded [[David Rennie (columnist)|David Rennie]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Britain's cheering gloom|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21557752 |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlemagne moves town|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/charlemagne/2010/06/charlemagne_moves_town |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''Banyan''''' (Asia): named for the [[banyan]] tree, this column was established in April 2009 and focuses on various issues across the Asian continent, and is written by [[Dominic Ziegler]].\n*'''''Baobab''''' (Africa & Middle East): named for the [[baobab]] tree, this column was established in July 2010 and focuses on various issues across the African continent.\n* '''''Bartleby''''' (Work and management): named after [[Bartleby|the titular character]] of a [[Herman Melville]] short story, this column was established in May 2018. It is written by [[Philip Coggan]].\n* '''''Bello''''' (Latin America): named for [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], a Venezuelan diplomat, poet, legislator and philosopher, who lived and worked in Chile.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Bello column: Choosing a Name|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/01/bello-column|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 March 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref> The column was established in January 2014 and is written by [[Michael Reid (journalist and writer)|Michael Reid]].\n* '''''Buttonwood''''' (Finance): named for the [[Platanus occidentalis|buttonwood]] tree where early [[Wall Street]] traders gathered. Until September 2006 this was available only as an on-line column, but it is now included in the print edition. Since 2018, it is written by John O'Sullivan, succeeding Philip Coggan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/john-osullivan/|title=John O'Sullivan|website=Economist|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* '''''Chaguan''''' (China): named for Chaguan, the traditional Chinese Tea houses in [[Chengdu]], this column was established on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/09/13/the-economists-new-china-column-chaguan|publisher=The Economist website|title=The Economist's new China column: Chaguan|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A graphic detail of The Economist.jpg|thumb|The paper launched a large [[data journalism]] platform in 2015, tasked with creating and developing [[Graphical model|graphical models]] for ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] coverage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/turning-a-page-the-economists-data-journalism-gets-its-own-place-in-print-664c2e5bdfe9|title=Turning a page: The Economist\u2019s data journalism gets its own place in print|last=Economist|first=The|date=2018-10-22|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalismawards.org/projects/the-economist-data-teams-graphic-detail-portfolio/|title=The Economist Data Team's Graphic Detail Portfolio|website=Data Journalism Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>]]\n\n* '''''Charlemagne''''' (Europe): named for [[Charlemagne]], Emperor of the [[Francia|Frankish Empire]]. It is written by Jeremy Cliffe<ref>[http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ People: Jeremy Cliffe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075703/http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ |date=15 January 2019 }}{{snd}} Economist Media Directory. Retrieved 14/1/19</ref> and earlier it was written by David Rennie (2007\u20132010) and by Anton La Guardia<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Directory|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/anton-la-guardia|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 June 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> (2010\u20132014).\n\n*'''''Erasmus''''' (Religion and public policy) \u2013 named after the Dutch [[Christian humanist]] [[Erasmus]].\n*'''''Game Theory''''' (Sport): named after [[Game theory|the science of predicting outcomes]] in a certain situation, this column focuses on \"sports major and minor\" and \"the politics, economics, science and statistics of the games we play and watch\".\n*'''''Johnson''''' (language): named for [[Samuel Johnson]], this column returned to the publication in 2016 and covers language. It is written by [[Robert Lane Greene]].\n*'''''Lexington''''' (United States): named for [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the site of the beginning of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. From June 2010 until May 2012 it was written by [[Peter David (journalist)|Peter David]], until his death in a car accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/lexington/2012/05/lexington|publisher=The Economist website|title=Lexington: Peter David|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''''Prospero''''' (Books and arts): named after the character from [[William Shakespeare's]] play ''[[The Tempest]]'', this column reviews books and focuses on arts-related issues.\n*'''''Schumpeter''''' (Business): named for the economist [[Joseph Schumpeter]], this column was established in September 2009 and is written by Patrick Foulis.\n\n* '''''Free Exchange''''' (Economics): a general economics column, frequently based on academic research, replaced the column ''Economics Focus'' in January 2012\n*'''Obituary''' (recent death): Since 1997 it has been written by [[Ann Wroe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|title=An Interview with Ann Wroe, Obituaries Writer for The Economist|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223130322/http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|archive-date=23 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper goes to press on Thursdays, between 6&nbsp;pm and 7&nbsp;pm GMT, and is available at newsagents in many countries the next day. It is printed at seven sites around the world. Known on their website as \"This week's print edition\", it is available online, albeit with only the first five viewed articles being free (and available to subscribers only mid-October 2009 \u2013 2010).\n\n''The Economist'' published in 2015 its first US college rankings, focused on comparable economical advantages defined as 'the economic value of a university is equal to the gap between how much its students subsequently earn, and how much they might have made had they studied elsewhere'. Based on set of strict criteria sourced from US Department of Education (\"College Scorecard\") with relevant 'expected earnings' and multiple statistics applied in calculation of 'median earnings' conclusive evaluation method has been applied to run the scorecard's earnings data through a multiple regression analysis, a common method of measuring the relationships between variables.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2015/10/value-university |title= The Economist \"The value of university: Our first-ever college rankings\"  |journal=The Economist |accessdate=29 October 2015|date= 29 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' also produces the annual ''The World in'' [''Year''] publication. It also sponsors a writing award.\n\n==Awards==\n===Innovation Awards===\n[[File:Dimitris Droutsas at The Economist conference.jpg|thumb|293x293px|Greek Foreign Minister [[Dimitrios Droutsas|Dimitris Droutsas]] speaking at 2011 Economist Conference. ]]\n''The Economist'' sponsors the yearly \"Economist Innovation Awards\", in the categories of bioscience, computing and communications, energy and the environment, social and economic innovation, business-process innovation, consumer products, and a special \"no boundaries\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|title=Economist Innovation Awards Categories|publisher=The Economist Group|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117061347/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref> The awards have been held since 2002. Nominations are held between 2 and 30 April. The award ceremony is then hosted on 15 November. Choices are based on the following factors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|title=Economist Innovation Awards Nomination Process|publisher=Economistconferences.co.uk|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507204053/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n* How much revenue their innovation has made their company or its economic impact on a specific good cause or society in general\n* The effect their work has had on the marketplace (or if it's created a whole new marketplace altogether)\n* The impact their innovation has had on a new type of science or technology\n\n===Writing prize===\nIn 1999, ''The Economist'' organised a global futurist writing competition, [[The World in 2050]]. Co-sponsored by [[Royal Dutch/Shell]], the competition included a first prize of [[United States dollar|US$]]20,000 and publication in ''The Economist''{{'}}s annual flagship publication, ''The World In''.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=20000422&id=01ZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2003,2039685 | title=What is your vision of the future? | work=New Straights Times | date=22 April 2000}}</ref> Over 3,000 entries from around the world were submitted via a website set up for the purpose and at various Royal Dutch Shell offices worldwide.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/>\n\nThe judging panel included [[Bill Emmott]],<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/> [[Esther Dyson]],<ref>{{cite news |title= Angel Investor Esther Dyson Increases Dosage in Health Startups|url=http://go.bloomberg.com/tech-deals/2012-12-26-angel-investor-esther-dyson-increases-dosage-of-health-startups/ |work= Bloomberg News|date= 26 December 2012}}</ref> Sir [[Mark Moody-Stuart]] (then-chairman of [[Royal Dutch Shell]]),<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/> and [[Matt Ridley]] (a British scientist and member of the [[House of Lords]]).<ref>{{cite news |title=Getting better all the time |url=https://www.economist.com/node/16103826|work=The Economist |date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\n[[File:A page ripped out from The Economist by China's censorship department (cropped).jpg|thumb|232x232px|A page ripped out from ''The Economist'' by China's censorship department in [[Liaoning Provincial Museum|Liaoning Provincial Library]]. ]]\nSections of ''The Economist'' criticising authoritarian regimes are frequently removed from the paper by the authorities in those countries. ''The Economist'' regularly has difficulties with the ruling party of Singapore, the [[People's Action Party]], which had successfully sued it, in a Singaporean court, for [[Defamation|libel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/HL01Ae01.html|title=Inconvenient truths in Singapore|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[Asia Times]] }}</ref>\n\nLike many other publications, ''The Economist'' is subjected to censorship in [[India]] whenever it depicts a map of [[Kashmir]]. The maps are stamped by Indian Customs officials as being \"neither correct, nor authentic\". Issues are sometimes delayed, but not stopped or seized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/12/censorship_india|title=Censorship in India|work=The Economist | date=7 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, [[Iran]] banned the sale of ''The Economist'' when it published a map labelling the [[Persian Gulf]] simply as Gulf\u2014a choice that derives its political significance from the [[Persian Gulf naming dispute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1150191582529&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Iran bans ''The Economist'' over map|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, the government of [[Zimbabwe]] went further and imprisoned ''The Economist''{{'}}s correspondent there, [[Andrew Meldrum]]. The government charged him with violating a statute on \"publishing untruth\" for writing that a woman was decapitated by supporters of the ruling [[Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] party. The [[decapitation]] claim was retracted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |title=Guardian and RFI correspondent risks two years in jail |accessdate=2 April 2014 |work=[[Reporters Without Borders]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404211952/http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |archivedate=4 April 2009 }}</ref> and allegedly fabricated by the woman's husband. The correspondent was later acquitted, only to receive a [[deportation]] order.\n\nOn 19 August 2013, ''The Economist'' disclosed that the Missouri Department of Corrections had censored its issue of 29 June 2013. According to the letter sent by the department, prisoners were not allowed to receive the issue because \"1. it constitutes a threat to the security or discipline of the institution; 2. may facilitate or encourage criminal activity; or 3. may interfere with the rehabilitation of an offender\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist in prison: About that missing issue|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2013/08/economist-prison|work=The Economist|accessdate=2 April 2014|date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of business newspapers]]\n* [[List of newspapers in the United Kingdom]]\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Media|Business|News|United Kingdom|Europe}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Arrese, Angel (1995), ''La identidad de The Economist,'' Pamplona: Eunsa. {{ISBN|9788431313739}}. ([https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326415042_La_identidad_de_The_Economist preview])\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thebalancesmb.com/best-business-magazines-4176680|title=The 8 Best Business Magazines of 2020|last=Delbridge|first=Emily|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Balance Small Business|publisher=Dotdash|location=New York City|page=|pages=|at=Best Economics Reporting: The Economist|doi=|pmid=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 Feb 2020|magazine=}}\n* Edwards, Ruth Dudley (1993), ''The Pursuit of Reason: The Economist 1843\u20131993'', London: Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-12939-7}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Media Monoliths|author=Tungate|first=Mark|location=|pages=194\u2013206|chapter=''The Economist''|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7494-4108-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|The_Economist.ogg|12 July 2006}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.economist.com/}}\n* {{HathiTrust Catalog}}\n\n{{Rothschilds}}\n{{The Economist Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economist, The}}\n\n<!--Do not add any categories about newsmagazine or magazines, The Economist is a newspaper, printed in magazine-format.-->\n[[Category:The Economist]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International newspapers]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Websites utilizing paywalls]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the profession|Economist|6=other uses|7=The Economist (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|English weekly news and international affairs publication}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Economist\n| logo = The Economist Logo.svg\n| image = 'The Economist' cover (September 8, 2001).png\n| caption = Cover of the 8 September 2001 issue{{#tag:ref|The title and its design are references to the book ''[[No Logo]]'' (1999).|group=\"nb\"}}\n| type = [[Weekly newspaper]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n| format = <!--The Economist is a newspaper printed in magazine format. Leave as \"magazine\" for format, with no hyperlink.-->Magazine\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1843|09}}\n| founder = [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]\n| owners = [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]]\n| ISSN = 0013-0613\n| political = <!--This is not an indiscriminate list, only the big, umbrella political camps The Economist belongs to.-->\n[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eb87e2f4-ffc9-11e9-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Liberalism at Large \u2014 how The Economist gets it right and spectacularly wrong|last=Zevin|first=Alexander|date=December 20, 2019|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Social liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Radical centrism]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-0|work=The Economist|title=Is The Economist left- or right-wing?|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21564556|work=The Economist|title=True Progressivism|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Adelphi, London|1-11 John Adam Street]]<br>[[City of Westminster|Westminster]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| editor = [[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]\n| website = {{url|economist.com}}\n| circulation = 909,476 (print)<br>748,459 (digital)<br>1.6 million (combined)\n| circulation_date = July-December 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=The Economist - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/432 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| logo_size = 120px\n| depeditor = [[Tom Standage]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Economist''''' is an international [[weekly newspaper]] <!--It is a newspaper NOT a magazine. Please see discussion at Talk:The Economist/Archive 2. The latter is \"printing format\" NOT a publication. Do not change wording without another editorial consensus on the talk as per WP:TITLE it is still a newspaper no matter how it is printed.-->printed in [[Magazine|magazine-format]] that focuses on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]], [[world news]], international business, and politics. Based in [[London|London, England]], the newspaper is owned by the [[Economist Group]], with core  editorial offices in major cities in North America, Europe, Asia, and the [[Middle East]]. In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million). In 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million. Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016. The newspaper stresses [[data journalism]] and analysis over original reporting, to both criticism and acclaim.<!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Article uses British English, e.g. \"-ise\" over \"-ize\". See: WP:ISE.--><!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->\n\nFounded in 1843, ''The Economist'' was first circulated by Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] to muster support for abolishing the British [[Corn Laws]] (1815\u201346), a system of [[Tariff|import tariffs]]. Over time, the newspaper's coverage expanded further into [[political economy]] and eventually began running articles on current events, finance, commerce, and British politics. Throughout the mid- to late- 20th century, it greatly expanded its layout and format, adding [[Op-ed|opinion columns]], special reports, [[Political cartoon|political cartoons]], [[Letter to the editor|reader letters]], cover stories, art critique, book reviews, and technology features. The paper is often recognizable by its [[fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] nameplate and illustrated, topical covers. Individual articles are written anonymously, with [[Byline|no byline]], in order for the paper to speak as one collective voice. The paper is supplemented by its sister lifestyle magazine, ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]]'', and a variety of podcasts, films, and books.\n\nThe [[The Economist editorial stance|editorial stance of ''The Economist'']] primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]], [[Social liberalism|social]], and most notably, [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring policies and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper advocates for [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]]. Despite a pronounced editorial stance, it is seen as having little [[reporting bias]], rigorous [[Fact-checking|fact checking]] and strict [[copy editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/when-will-magazines-stop-trying-to-copy-the-economist|title=Why Time and Newsweek Will Never Be The Economist|last=Pressman|first=Matt|date=April 20, 2009|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/|title=10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts|last=Leadership|first=The Berlin School Of Creative|date=February 1, 2017|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Its extensive use of [[Word play|word play]], [[Subscription (finance)|subscription]] prices, and typical depth of coverage has linked the paper with a high-income and educated readership, drawing both positive and negative connotations in the [[Western world|Western World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/01/31/why-the-economist-swapped-its-famous-elitist-marketing-emotional-messaging|title=Why The Economist swapped its famous elitist marketing for emotional messaging|last=Burnell|first=Ian|date=31 January 2019|website=The Drum|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/09/business/media/09economist.html|title=The Economist Tends Its Sophisticate Garden|date=2010-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In line with this, it claims to have influential readership of prominent business leaders and [[Policy|policy-makers]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:James Wilson by Sir John Watson-Gordon.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] founded the newspaper to \"take part in a severe [[Debate|contest between intelligence]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reed.edu/reed-magazine/articles/2017/contest-letter-editor.html|title=The Contest|last=Lydgate|first=Chris|date=March 1, 2017|website=Reed Magazine|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2017}}</ref>|208x208px]]\n''The Economist'' was founded by the British businessman and banker [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] in 1843, to advance the repeal of the [[Corn Laws]], a system of import tariffs.<ref>[http://mitpress.typepad.com/mitpresslog/2007/01/from_corn_laws_.html From the Corn Laws to Your Mailbox], The MIT Press Log, 30 January 2007. Retrieved 11 June 2010.</ref> A [[prospectus (finance)|prospectus]] for the \"newspaper\" from 5 August 1843 enumerated thirteen areas of coverage that its editors wanted the publication to focus on:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=1873493|title=Prospectus|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=5 August 1843}}</ref>\n# Original [[editorial|leading articles]], in which free-trade principles will be most rigidly applied to all the important questions of the day.\n# Articles relating to some practical, commercial, agricultural, or foreign topic of passing interest, such as foreign treaties.\n# An article on the elementary principles of [[political economy]], applied to practical experience, covering the laws related to prices, wages, rent, exchange, revenue and taxes.\n# [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] reports, with particular focus on commerce, agriculture and free trade.\n# Reports and accounts of popular movements advocating free trade.\n# General news from the [[Court of St. James's]], the [[Greater London|Metropolis]], the [[Historic counties of England|Provinces]], Scotland, and Ireland.\n# Commercial topics such as changes in fiscal regulations, the state and prospects of the markets, imports and exports, foreign news, the state of the manufacturing districts, notices of important new mechanical improvements, shipping news, the money market, and the progress of railways and public companies.\n# Agricultural topics, including the application of geology and [[chemistry]]; notices of new and improved [[List of agricultural machinery|implements]], state of crops, markets, prices, foreign markets and prices converted into English money; from time to time, in some detail, the plans pursued in Belgium, Switzerland, and other well-cultivated countries.\n# [[British overseas territories|Colonial]] and foreign topics, including trade, produce, political and fiscal changes, and other matters, including [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9s]] on the evils of restriction and protection, and the advantages of free intercourse and trade.\n# Law reports, confined chiefly to areas important to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture.\n# Books, confined chiefly, but not so exclusively, to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture, and including all treatises on political economy, finance, or taxation.\n# A commercial [[gazette]], with prices and statistics of the week.\n# [[Letter to the editor|Correspondence and inquiries]] from the newspaper's readers.\n\nWilson described it as taking part in \"a severe contest between intelligence, which presses forward, and an unworthy, timid ignorance obstructing our progress\", a phrase which still appears on its masthead as the publication's mission.<ref name=\"opinion\">{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/ |title=Opinion: leaders and letters to the Editor |work=The Economist |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> It has long been respected as \"one of the most competent and subtle Western periodicals on public affairs\".<ref name=\"Leites\">{{cite journal|title=The Politburo Through Western Eyes|pages=159\u2013185|author=Nathan Leites|journal=[[World Politics]]|year=1952|volume=4|issue=2|jstor=2009044|doi=10.2307/2009044}}{{subscription required}}</ref> It was cited by [[Karl Marx]] in his formulation of socialist theory, because Marx felt the publication epitomised the interests of the bourgeoisie <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YauuCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA242&dq=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&pg=PA242#v=onepage&q=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&f=false|title=Karl Marx: His Life and Thought|last=McLellan|first=David|date=1 December 1973|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349155149|language=en}}</ref> He wrote: \"the London ''Economist'', the European organ of the aristocracy of finance, described most strikingly the attitude of this class.\"<ref>Karl Marx, ''The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte'', VI (1852)</ref> In 1915, revolutionary [[Vladimir Lenin]] referred to ''The Economist'' as a \"journal that speaks for British millionaires\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theeconomist/status/955168910852153344?lang=en|author=The Economist|website=twitter.com}}</ref> Additionally Lenin claimed that ''The Economist'' held a \"bourgeois-pacifist\" position and supported peace out of fear of [[revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1915/may/01c.htm|title=Bourgeois Philanthropists and Revolutionary Social-Democracy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:The Economist 2019 1 o.jpg|left|thumb|A panel of journalists and public policy leaders at ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s 2019 India Summit.<nowiki/>]]In 1920, the paper's circulation rose to 6,170.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} In 1934, it underwent its first major redesign. The current [[fire engine red]] nameplate was created by [[Reynolds Stone]] in 1959.<ref name=\"About us\" /> In January 2012, ''The Economist'' launched a new weekly section devoted exclusively to China, the first new country section since the introduction of one on the United States in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economist Launches New China Section|url=http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|work=Asian Media Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201210032/http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|archivedate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 1991, [[James Fallows]] argued in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that ''The Economist'' used editorial lines that contradicted the news stories they purported to highlight.<ref name=\"fallows\" /> In 1999, [[Andrew Sullivan]] complained in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that it uses \"marketing genius\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/london-fog|title=London Fog|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> to make up for deficiencies in original reporting, resulting in \"a kind of ''[[Reader's Digest]]''\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3874750,00.html|title=Not so groovy.|date=14 June 1999|work=The New Republic|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref> for America's corporate elite.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Finkel|first=Rebecca|date=July 1999|title=Nasty barbs fly between New Republic and Economist|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/news1999/july99/news4707.html|magazine=Media Life|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107024913/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news1999/july99/news4707.html|archivedate=7 November 2015|accessdate=27 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"its writers rarely see a political or economic problem that cannot be solved by the trusted three-card trick of privatisation, deregulation and liberalisation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Stern|first=Stefan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/aug/21/pressandpublishing.business1|title=Economist thrives on female intuition|date=21 August 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 January 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' named it the best English-language paper noting its strength in international reporting where it does not feel moved to cover a faraway land only at a time of unmitigated disaster\" and that it kept a wall between its reporting and its more conservative editorial policies.<ref>Entertainment: 50 Best Magazines, Chicago Tribune, 15 June 2006.</ref> In 2008, [[Jon Meacham]], former editor of ''Newsweek'' and a self-described \"fan\", criticised ''The Economist''{{'s}} focus on analysis over original reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/node/39374|title=Jon Meacham Wants Newsweek to Be More Like Hayes' Esquire|work=The New York Observer|accessdate=27 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522125448/http://www.observer.com/node/39374|archive-date=22 May 2008}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Economist'' was [[2012 ICT Skype controversy|accused]] of hacking into the computer of Justice [[Mohammed Nizamul Huq]] of the [[Bangladesh]] Supreme Court, leading to his resignation as the chairman of the [[International Crimes Tribunal (Bangladesh)|International Crimes Tribunal]].<ref name=\"ICTleaks\">{{cite magazine|date=8 December 2012|title=Discrepancy in Dhaka|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/12/bangladesh|magazine=The Economist}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/bangladesh-crimes-tribunal-accuses-the-economist-magazine-of-hacking-judges-computer/2012/12/09/8f248da2-421e-11e2-8c8f-fbebf7ccab4e_story.html|title=Economist accused of hacking ICT judge's computer|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks2\">{{cite news|last=Hossain|first=Farid|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121209/as-bangladesh-war-crimes|title=Economist magazine faces contempt in Bangladesh|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/bangladeshi-war-crimes-tribunal-issues-notice-to-the-economist/1041394|title=Bangladeshi war crimes tribunal issues notice to The Economist|date=6 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-economist-pearson_55cb31f0e4b0923c12beac28?ir=Business&section=business&kvcommref=mostpopular|title=Pearson Unloads $731 Million Stake in the Economist|date=12 August 2015|work=HuffPost|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Shareholders ===\n[[File:Economist building London1.jpg|thumb|The Economist Building, until 2017, in [[London]], England on [[St James's Street]].|alt=]][[Pearson plc]] held a 50% shareholding via [[Financial Times|The Financial Times Limited]] until August 2015. At that time, Pearson sold their share in the Economist. The [[Agnelli family]]'s [[Exor (company)|Exor]] paid \u00a3287m to raise their stake from 4.7% to 43.4% while the Economist paid \u00a3182m for the balance of 5.04m shares which will be distributed to current shareholders.<ref name=\"West\">{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref> Aside from the Agnelli family, smaller shareholders in the company include [[Cadbury family|Cadbury]], [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]] (21%), [[Schroders|Schroder]], [[Baron Layton|Layton]] and other family interests as well as a number of staff and former staff shareholders.<ref name=\"West\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/agnellis-rothschilds-close-in-on-economist-magazine-sale-pearson/|title=Agnellis, Rothschilds close in on Economist|date=11 August 2015|work=POLITICO|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Trustee|board of trustees]] formally appoints the editor, who cannot be removed without its permission. Although ''The Economist'' has a global emphasis and scope, about two-thirds of the 75 staff journalists are based in the London borough of [[City of Westminster|Westminster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/so-whats-the-secret-of-the-economist-347699.html|title=So what's the secret of 'The Economist'?|date=26 February 2006|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Editor ===\n[[File:Zanny Minton Beddoes World Economic Forum 2013 cropped.jpg|thumb|254x254px|[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]] was appointed editor in 2015, first joining as an [[emerging markets]] correspondent in 1994.]]\nThe [[editor-in-chief]], commonly known simply as \"the Editor\", of ''The Economist'' is charged with formulating the paper's editorial policies and overseeing corporate operations. Since its 1843 founding, the editors have been:\n\n*[[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]: 1843\u20131857\n*[[Richard Holt Hutton]]: 1857\u20131861<ref>The ''Concise Dictionary of National Biography'' makes him assistant editor 1858\u20131860</ref>\n*[[Walter Bagehot]]: 1861\u20131877<ref>He was Wilson's son-in-law</ref>\n*[[Daniel Conner Lathbury]]: 1877\u20131881<ref>[[s:The Times/1922/Obituary/Daniel Conner Lathbury|A journalist and biographer]]</ref> (''jointly'')\n*[[Robert Harry Inglis Palgrave]]: 1877\u20131883 (''jointly'')\n* Edward Johnstone: 1883\u20131907<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|title=economist150\u5468\u5e74\uff081993\uff09 \u2013 \u7ecf\u6d4e\u5b66\u4eba\u8d44\u6599\u5e93 \u2013 ECO\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51 \u2013 Powered by Discuz! Archiver|author=Discuz! Team and Comsenz UI Team|accessdate=29 June 2015|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922170122/http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Francis Wrigley Hirst]]: 1907\u20131916\n* Hartley Withers: 1916\u20131921\n*[[Walter Layton, 1st Baron Layton|Sir Walter Layton]]: 1922\u20131938\n*[[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]]: 1938\u20131956\n*[[Donald Tyerman]]: 1956\u20131965\n*[[Alastair Burnet|Sir Alastair Burnet]]: 1965\u20131974\n*[[Andrew Knight (journalist)|Andrew Knight]]: 1974\u20131986\n*[[Rupert Pennant-Rea]]: 1986\u20131993\n*[[Bill Emmott]]: 1993\u20132006\n*[[John Micklethwait]]: 2006\u20132014<ref>{{cite news|title=John Micklethwait leaving the Economist to join Bloomberg News|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/09/john-micklethwait-leaving-economist-joining-bloomberg|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 December 2014|last1=Sweney|first1=Mark}}</ref>\n*[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]: 2015\u2013present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/zanny-minton-beddoes/|title=Zanny Minton Beddoes|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Opinions==\n{{Main|The Economist editorial stance}}\nThe editorial stance of ''The Economist'' primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]] and [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring polices and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper favors [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/17732859|title=Globalisation: The redistribution of hope|date=16 December 2010|work=The Economist|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref> When the newspaper was founded, the term \"[[economism]]\" denoted what would today be termed \"[[economic liberalism]]\". The activist and journalist [[George Monbiot]] has described it as [[neoliberalism|neo-liberal]] while occasionally accepting the propositions of [[Keynesian economics]] where deemed more \"reasonable\".<ref name=\"Grauniad\">{{cite news|author=George Monbiot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/jan/11/economy.g8|title=George Monbiot, Punitive \u2013 and it works|work=The Guardian|date=11 January 2005|accessdate=25 May 2012|location=London}}</ref> The weekly favours a [[carbon tax]] to fight [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11543656|title=Buttonwood: Let them heat coke|journal=The Economist|date=14 June 2008|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> According to one former editor, Bill Emmott, \"the ''Economist''{{'}}s philosophy has always been liberal, not conservative\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/monarchy/story/0,2763,408484,00.html|title=Time for a referendum on the monarchy|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=Comment| date=8 December 2000| first=Bill|last=Emmot| location=London}}</ref> [[File:David Hume and Adam Smith statues.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[Adam Smith]] (''right'') and philosopher [[David Hume]] (''left'') represent the newspaper's foundational beliefs of ''[[laissez-faire]]'' [[Economic policy|policies]], [[self-sufficiency]], [[Protectionism|anti-protectionism]] and [[free trade]].|alt=]]Individual contributors take diverse views. ''The Economist'' favours the support, through [[central bank]]s, of banks and other important corporations. This principle can, in a much more limited form, be traced back to [[Walter Bagehot]], the third editor of ''The Economist'', who argued that the Bank of England should support major banks that got into difficulties. [[Karl Marx]] deemed ''The Economist'' the \"European organ\" of \"the aristocracy of finance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Marx|first=Karl|title=The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte|year=1852|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1852/18th-brumaire/ch06.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper has also supported liberal causes on social issues such as recognition of gay marriages,<ref>[https://www.economist.com/PrinterFriendly.cfm?story_id=2515389 Let them wed], cover article on 4 January 1996</ref> legalisation of drugs,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100602002643/http://www.drogasedemocracia.org/Arquivos/the-economist.pdf How to stop the drug wars], cover article on 7 March 2009.  The publication calls legalisation \"the least bad solution\".</ref> criticises the [[Taxation in the United States|US tax model]],<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21545981|title=Tax reform in America: A simple bare necessity|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=4 February 2012}}</ref> and seems to support some government regulation on health issues, such as smoking in public,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/16333351|title=Smoking and public health: Breathe easy|journal=The Economist|date=10 June 2010|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> as well as bans on spanking children.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11455006 \"Spare The Rod, Say Some\"], ''The Economist'', 31 May 2008.</ref> ''The Economist'' consistently favours guest worker programmes, parental choice of school, and amnesties<ref>[https://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=6744217 Sense, not Sensenbrenner], The Economist, 30 March 2006</ref> and once published an \"obituary\" of God.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/obituary/1999/12/23/god|title=Obituary: God|last=|first=|date=23 December 1999|work=The Economist|access-date=}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also has a long record of supporting gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/13447986|title=Lexington: Reflections on Virginia Tech|date=8 April 2009|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' has endorsed the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (in 2005), the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] (in 2010 and 2015),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/29/the-economist-backs-conservatives \"The Economist backs the Conservatives\"], ''The Guardian'' (PA report), 29 April 2010.</ref><ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite journal|title=Who should govern Britain?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21650113-despite-risk-europe-coalition-led-david-cameron-should-have-second-term-who|journal=The Economist|accessdate=11 May 2015|date=2 May 2015}}</ref> and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (in 2017 and 2019) at general election time in Britain, and both [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidates in the United States. ''Economist.com'' puts its stance this way:\n\n{{quotation|What, besides free trade and free markets, does ''The Economist'' believe in? \"It is to the Radicals that ''The Economist'' still likes to think of itself as belonging. The extreme centre is the paper's historical position\". That is as true today as when Crowther [Geoffrey, ''Economist'' editor 1938\u20131956] said it in 1955. ''The Economist'' considers itself the enemy of privilege, pomposity and predictability. It has backed conservatives such as [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]]. It has supported the Americans in [[Vietnam]]. But it has also endorsed [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Bill Clinton]], and espoused a variety of liberal causes: opposing capital punishment from its earliest days, while favouring penal reform and decolonisation, as well as\u2014more recently\u2014gun control and gay marriage.<ref name=\"About us\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/help/about-us#About_The_Economist|title=About us|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>}}\n''The Economist'' frequently accuses figures and countries of corruption or dishonesty. In recent years, for example, it criticised [[Paul Wolfowitz]], [[World Bank]] president; [[Silvio Berlusconi]], Italy's Prime Minister (who dubbed it ''The Ecommunist'');<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2005/09/324682.html|title=Report of Rome anti-war demo on Saturday 24th with photos|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=[[Independent Media Center]] }}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]], the late president of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]; [[Robert Mugabe]], the former head of government in [[Zimbabwe]]; and, recently, [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]], the president of Argentina.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Cristina in the land of make believe|work=The Economist|date=1 May 2008|url=https://www.economist.com/world/la/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11293743}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also called for [[impeachment of Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton's impeachment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/1998/09/17/just-go|title=Just go|date=1998-09-17|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> and, after the emergence of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=2647493|title=Resign Rumsfeld|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=6 May 2004}}</ref> for [[Donald Rumsfeld]]'s resignation. Though ''The Economist'' initially gave vigorous support for the [[Iraq War|US-led invasion of Iraq]], it later called the operation \"bungled from the start\" and criticised the \"almost criminal negligence\" of the Bush Administration's handling of the war, while maintaining, in 2007, that pulling out in the short term would be irresponsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RRRTGGP|title=Mugged by reality|accessdate=9 April 2007|work=The Economist|date=22 March 2007}}</ref> In the 2004 US election, the editors \"reluctantly\" backed John Kerry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_QTVPPQ|title=Crunch time in America|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=2 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=3329802|title=The incompetent or the incoherent?|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=28 October 2004}}</ref> In the 2008 US election ''The Economist'' endorsed [[Barack Obama]], while using the front cover of the issue published on the eve of the election to promote his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?source=most_commented&story_id=12511171| work=The Economist| title=It's time|date=30 October 2008}}</ref> In the 2012 US election, Barack Obama was again endorsed: the editorial said that they preferred Obama on the economy, foreign policy and health care, but criticised him for running a negative campaign against Romney and for a \"...poor appreciation of commerce.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Our American Endorsement. Which one? |url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21565623-america-could-do-better-barack-obama-sadly-mitt-romney-does-not-fit-bill-which-one?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709 |newspaper=The Economist |date=3 November 2012 |accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the Economist endorse [[Hillary Clinton]], and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] due \"[p]artly because she is not Mr Trump, but also in the hope she can show that ordinary politics works for ordinary people\u2014the sort of renewal that American democracy requires.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2016/11/05/americas-best-hope|title=America's best hope|date=2016-11-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nIn an editorial marking its 175th anniversary, ''The Economist'' criticised adherents to liberalism for becoming too inclined to protect the political status quo rather than pursue reform.<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/essay/2018/09/13/the-economist-at-175|title=The Economist at 175|accessdate=17 September 2018|work=The Economist|date=13 September 2018}}</ref>{{Non-primary source needed|date=May 2019}} The paper called on liberals to return to advocating for bold political, economic and social reforms: protecting [[free market]]s, land and tax reform in the tradition of [[Georgism]], [[open immigration]], a rethink of the [[social contract]] with more emphasis on education, and a revival of [[liberal internationalism]].<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\" />\n\n==Tone and voice==\nThough it has many individual columns, by tradition and current practice the newspaper ensures a uniform voice\u2014aided by the anonymity of writers\u2014throughout its pages,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/styleguide/introduction|title=Style Guide | accessdate=8 February 2013|work=The Economist|date=27 September 2011}}</ref> as if most articles were written by a single author, which may be perceived to display dry, understated wit, and precise use of language.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/research/styleGuide/index.cfm?page=673927|title=The Economist \u2013 Tone|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |title=Johnson |accessdate=27 December 2006 |work=The Economist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219221031/http://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |archivedate=19 December 2006 }}</ref> <!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->''The Economist'' has traditionally\u2014albeit not always consistently\u2014persisted in referring to itself as a \"[[newspaper]]\", rather than a \"[[news magazine]]\", due to [[Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|its legal classification as a newspaper]] in Britain, its transition from [[broadsheet]] to glossy colour format, and its general focus on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] as opposed to specialist subjects.<ref name=\"pgazette\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist''{{'}}s treatment of economics presumes a working familiarity with fundamental concepts of classical economics. For instance, it does not explain terms like [[invisible hand]], [[macroeconomics]], or [[demand curve]], and may take just six or seven words to explain the theory of [[comparative advantage]]. Articles involving economics do not presume any formal training on the part of the reader and aim to be accessible to the educated layman. It usually does not translate short French (and German) quotes or phrases. It does describe the business or nature of even well-known entities, writing, for example, \"[[Goldman Sachs]], an investment bank\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2008/02/21/a-bank-by-any-other-name|title=A bank by any other name|date=2008-02-21|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' is known for its extensive use of [[word play]], including puns, allusions, and metaphors, as well as alliteration and assonance, especially in its headlines and captions. This can make it difficult to understand for those who are not native English speakers.<ref>Richard J. Alexander, \"Article Headlines in ''The Economist'': An Analysis of Puns, Allusions and Metaphors\", ''Arbeiten aus Anglistik und Amerikanistik '''11''':2:159-177 (1986) {{jstor|43023400}}''</ref>\n\n===Editorial anonymity===\n[[File:The Economist Article.jpg|thumb|''Economist'' articles typically do not carry [[Byline|bylines]], anonymously publishing their work. |211x211px]]\nArticles often take a definite editorial stance and almost never carry a [[byline]]. Not even the name of the editor is printed in the issue. It is a long-standing tradition that an editor's only signed article during their tenure is written on the occasion of their departure from the position. The author of a piece is named in certain circumstances: when notable persons are invited to contribute opinion pieces; when journalists of ''The Economist'' compile special reports (previously known as surveys); for the Year in Review special edition; and to highlight a potential [[conflict of interest]] over a book review. The names of ''The Economist'' editors and correspondents can be located on the media directory pages of the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory|title=Media directory|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Online blog pieces are signed with the initials of the writer and authors of print stories are allowed to note their authorship from their personal web sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://andreaskluth.org/2008/11/20/why-the-economist-has-no-bylines/|title=Why The Economist has no bylines |work=Andreaskluth.org|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=20 November 2008 }}</ref> \"This approach is not without its faults (we have four staff members with the initials \"J.P.\", for example) but is the best compromise between total anonymity and full bylines, in our view\", wrote one anonymous writer of The Economist.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-1/|title=Why are The Economist's writers anonymous? |journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 September 2016|date=4 September 2013 }}</ref> There are three editorial and business areas in which the anonymous ethos of the weekly has contributed to strengthening its unique identity: collective and consistent voice, talent and newsroom management, and brand strength and clarity. <ref>{{cite journal |last=Arrese |first=\u00c1ngel |title=\"\u201cIt\u2019s Anonymous. It\u2019s The Economist\u201d. The Journalistic and Business Value of Anonymity\" |journal=Journalism Practice |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2020.1735489}}</ref>\n\nThe editors say this is necessary because \"collective voice and personality matter more than the identities of individual journalists\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/help/about-us|title=The Economist \u2013 About us|accessdate=11 June 2012|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> and reflects \"a collaborative effort\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|title=Economist Editor Micklethwait brings his global perspective to the Twin Cities|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=29 April 2008|publisher=MinnPost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705161308/http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|archive-date=5 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In most articles, authors refer to themselves as \"your correspondent\" or \"this reviewer\". The writers of the titled opinion columns tend to refer to themselves by the title (hence, a sentence in the \"Lexington\" column might read \"Lexington was informed...\").\n\nAmerican author and long-time reader [[Michael Lewis (author)|Michael Lewis]] criticised the paper's editorial anonymity in 1991, labelling it a means to hide the youth and inexperience of those writing articles.<ref name=\"fallows\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/1991/10/-quot-the-economics-of-the-colonial-cringe-quot-about-the-economist-magazine-washington-post-1991/7415/|title=The Economics of the Colonial Cringe: Pseudonomics and the Sneer on the Face of The Economist.|accessdate=27 April 2008|work=The Washington Post|date=16 October 1991}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2019/07/01/bestselling-author-michael-lewis-has-it-all-figured-out/|title=Bestselling Author Michael Lewis Has It All Figured Out|last=High|first=Peter|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Although individual articles are written anonymously, there is no secrecy over who the writers are as they are listed on ''The Economist''{{'s}} website, which also provides summaries of their careers and academic qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media directory|url=http://mediadirectory.economist.com/|work=The Economist|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Later, in 2009, Lewis included multiple ''Economist'' articles in his [[anthology]] about the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], ''[[Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lewis|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Panic.html?id=ZXUOASHVf_YC|title=Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity|date=2009|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-06514-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[John Ralston Saul]] describes ''The Economist'' as a \"...[newspaper] which hides the names of the journalists who write its articles in order to create the illusion that they dispense disinterested truth rather than opinion. This sales technique, reminiscent of pre-Reformation Catholicism, is not surprising in a publication named after the social science most given to wild guesses and imaginary facts presented in the guise of inevitability and exactitude. That it is the Bible of the corporate executive indicates to what extent received wisdom is the daily bread of a managerial civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Doubter's Companion: A Dictionary of Aggressive Common Sense |id={{ASIN|0743236602|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\n==Circulation==\n[[File:The Economist Display.jpg|thumb|A display of newspapers in [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]] supermarket, depicting the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\nEach of ''The Economist'' issue's official date range is from Saturday to the following Friday. ''The Economist'' posts each week's new content online at approximately 2100 Thursday evening UK time, ahead of the official publication date.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist launches on Android|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/08/service-announcement|accessdate=26 February 2018|work=The Economist|date=2 August 2011}}</ref> From July to December 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million.<ref name=\"pgazette\" /> However, on a weekly average basis, the paper can reach up to 5.1 million readers, across their print and digital runs.<ref name=\"pgazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/economist-boasts-15m-magazine-circulation-and-36m-social-media-followers/|title=The Economist boasts 1.5m magazine circulation and 36m social media followers|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date=March 8, 2016|website=Press Gazette|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1877, the publication's circulation was 3,700, and in 1920 it had risen to 6,000. Circulation increased rapidly after 1945, reaching 100,000 by 1970.<ref name=\"About us\" /> Circulation is audited by the [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]] (ABC). From around 30,000 in 1960 it has risen to near 1 million by 2000 and by 2016 to about 1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://digiday.com/publishers/economist-aims-double-circulation-profits-5-years/|title=The Economist Plans to Double Circulation Profits in 5 Years|magazine=[[Digiday]] |author=Lucinda Southern |date=17 February 2016 |access-date=7 July 2016}}</ref> Sales inside North America were in 2007 around 54 per cent of the total, with sales in the UK making up 14 per cent of the total and continental Europe 19 per cent. ''The Economist'' claims sales, both by subscription and at newsagents, in over 200 countries. Of its American readers, two out of three earn more than $100,000 a year.<ref name=\"gainsreaders\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5250996|title='Economist' Magazine Wins American Readers|date=8 March 2006|accessdate=27 December 2006|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] }}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' once boasted about its limited circulation. In the early 1990s it used the slogan \"''The Economist'' \u2013 not read by millions of people\". \"Never in the history of journalism has so much been read for so long by so few,\" wrote [[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]], a former editor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D3B56996BE43&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM\n| title=\"Economist\" aspires to influence, and many say it does.|accessdate=14 May 2008|format=pay archive|work=The Chicago Tribune|first=Ray|last=Moseley}}</ref>\n\nThe Economist Newspaper Limited is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[The Economist Group]]. The publications of the group include the ''CFO'' brand family as well as the annual ''The World in...'', and the bimonthly [[lifestyle magazine]], ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]].'' Sir [[Evelyn Robert de Rothschild]] was Chairman of the company from 1972 to 1989.\n\n==Letters==\n''The Economist'' frequently receives letters from senior businesspeople, politicians, ambassadors, and from spokespeople for various government departments, non-governmental organisations and lobbies. Well-written or witty responses from anyone are considered, and controversial issues frequently produce a torrent of letters. For example, the survey of [[corporate social responsibility]], published January 2005, produced largely critical letters from [[Oxfam]], the [[World Food Programme]], [[United Nations Global Compact]], the Chairman of [[BT Group]], an ex-Director of [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] and the UK [[Institute of Directors]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.business-humanrights.org/Links/Repository/542754 |title= Compilation: Full text of responses to Economist survey on Corporate Social Responsibility (January\u2013February 2005)|accessdate=3 February 2007|work=Business & Human Rights}}</ref>\n\nMany of the letters published are critical of its stance or commentary. After ''The Economist'' ran a critique of [[Amnesty International]] and human rights in general in its issue dated 24 March 2007, its letters page ran a reply from Amnesty, as well as several other letters in support of the organisation, including one from the head of the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=8954694|title=Letters: On Amnesty International and human rights, Iraq, tax breaks 4&nbsp;April 2007|accessdate=9 November 2007|work=The Economist|date=4 April 2007}}</ref> Rebuttals from officials within regimes such as the Singapore government are routinely printed, to comply with local [[right-of-reply]] laws without compromising editorial independence.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CnZjYJ3TduUC&pg=PA173 |title=The Media Enthralled: Singapore Revisited|author=Francis T. Seow|year=1998|pages=171\u2013175|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|accessdate=25 May 2012|isbn=9781555877798}}</ref>\n\nIt is extremely rare for any comment by ''The Economist'' to appear alongside any published letter. Letters published in the paper are typically between 150 and 200 words long (and began with the salutation \"Sir\" until the editorship of Zanny Minton Beddoes, the first female editor; they now have no salutation). Previous to a change in procedure, all responses to on-line articles were usually published in \"The Inbox\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/debate/theinbox/ |title=Latest blog posts |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> Comments can now be made directly under each article.\n\n==Features==\n[[File:A stack of Economist papers.jpg|thumb|A stack of ''Economist'' papers, ordered by publication date. ''Pictured'': the 14 October 2019 issue. ]]\n''The Economist''{{'}}s primary focus is world events, politics and business, but it also runs regular sections on science and technology as well as books and the arts. Approximately every two weeks, the publication includes an in-depth special report<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/printedition/specialreports |title=Special reports |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> (previously called [[survey article|surveys]]) on a given topic. The five main categories are Countries and Regions, Business, Finance and Economics, Science and Technology, and Other. Every three months, it publishes a technology report called ''Technology Quarterly''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/science/tq/ |title=Technology Quarterly |work=The Economist |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> or TQ, a special section focusing on recent trends and developments in science and technology.\n\nSince July 2007, there has also been a complete audio edition of the paper available 9&nbsp;pm London time on Thursdays.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Katie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/11/pressandpublishing.business1 |title=Economist launches audio magazine|work=The Guardian|location=London |date=11 July 2007 |accessdate=21 September 2016 }}</ref> The audio version of ''The Economist'' is produced by the production company ''Talking Issues''. The company records the full text of the newspaper in [[MP3]] format, including the extra pages in the UK edition. The weekly 130 MB download is free for subscribers and available for a fee for non-subscribers.\n\nThe publication's writers adopt a tight style that seeks to include the maximum amount of information in a limited space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/StyleGuide/|title=The Economist style guide|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist }}</ref> [[David G. Bradley]], publisher of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', described the formula as \"a consistent world view expressed, consistently, in tight and engaging prose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp|title=A Seven Year Ambition|work=mediabistro.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010200210/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp |archivedate=10 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThere is a section of [[economic statistics]]. Tables such as employment statistics are published each week and there are special statistical features too. It is unique among British weeklies in providing authoritative coverage of official statistics and its rankings of international statistics have been decisive.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3WVLKKSOcGYC&pg=PA88|page=88|title=Great expectations\u2014the social sciences in Great Britain|publisher=Commission on the Social Sciences|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7658-0849-3}}</ref> In addition, ''The Economist'' is known for its [[Big Mac Index]], which it first published in 1986, which uses the price of the hamburger in different countries as an informal measure of the [[purchasing power parity|purchasing power]] of currencies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NZnk5C2r8qEC&pg=PA396|page=396|title=International Economics|author=Paul R. Krugman, Maurice Obstfeld|publisher=Pearson Education|year=2009|isbn=978-0-321-55398-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Economist|title=On the Hamburger Standard|date=6\u201312 September 1986}}</ref>\n\n=== Columns ===\nThe publication runs several opinion columns whose names reflect their topic:<!--Bolded because these columns redirect here, per WP:BOLD.-->\n\n*[[File:Economist Cartoon.jpg|thumb|A [[political cartoon]] published by the newspaper in November 2010, depicting  the [[European debt crisis|2010 European sovereign debt crisis]].|alt=|253x253px]]'''''Babbage''''' (Technology): named for the inventor [[Charles Babbage]], this column was established in March 2010 and focuses on various technology related issues.\n*'''''Bagehot''''' (Britain): named for [[Walter Bagehot]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|t\n}}), 19th-century British constitutional expert and early editor of ''The Economist''. Since April 2017 it has been written by [[Adrian Wooldridge]], who succeeded [[David Rennie (columnist)|David Rennie]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Britain's cheering gloom|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21557752 |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlemagne moves town|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/charlemagne/2010/06/charlemagne_moves_town |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''Banyan''''' (Asia): named for the [[banyan]] tree, this column was established in April 2009 and focuses on various issues across the Asian continent, and is written by [[Dominic Ziegler]].\n*'''''Baobab''''' (Africa & Middle East): named for the [[baobab]] tree, this column was established in July 2010 and focuses on various issues across the African continent.\n* '''''Bartleby''''' (Work and management): named after [[Bartleby|the titular character]] of a [[Herman Melville]] short story, this column was established in May 2018. It is written by [[Philip Coggan]].\n* '''''Bello''''' (Latin America): named for [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], a Venezuelan diplomat, poet, legislator and philosopher, who lived and worked in Chile.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Bello column: Choosing a Name|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/01/bello-column|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 March 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref> The column was established in January 2014 and is written by [[Michael Reid (journalist and writer)|Michael Reid]].\n* '''''Buttonwood''''' (Finance): named for the [[Platanus occidentalis|buttonwood]] tree where early [[Wall Street]] traders gathered. Until September 2006 this was available only as an on-line column, but it is now included in the print edition. Since 2018, it is written by John O'Sullivan, succeeding Philip Coggan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/john-osullivan/|title=John O'Sullivan|website=Economist|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* '''''Chaguan''''' (China): named for Chaguan, the traditional Chinese Tea houses in [[Chengdu]], this column was established on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/09/13/the-economists-new-china-column-chaguan|publisher=The Economist website|title=The Economist's new China column: Chaguan|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A graphic detail of The Economist.jpg|thumb|The paper launched a large [[data journalism]] platform in 2015, tasked with creating and developing [[Graphical model|graphical models]] for ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] coverage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/turning-a-page-the-economists-data-journalism-gets-its-own-place-in-print-664c2e5bdfe9|title=Turning a page: The Economist\u2019s data journalism gets its own place in print|last=Economist|first=The|date=2018-10-22|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalismawards.org/projects/the-economist-data-teams-graphic-detail-portfolio/|title=The Economist Data Team's Graphic Detail Portfolio|website=Data Journalism Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>]]\n\n* '''''Charlemagne''''' (Europe): named for [[Charlemagne]], Emperor of the [[Francia|Frankish Empire]]. It is written by Jeremy Cliffe<ref>[http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ People: Jeremy Cliffe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075703/http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ |date=15 January 2019 }}{{snd}} Economist Media Directory. Retrieved 14/1/19</ref> and earlier it was written by David Rennie (2007\u20132010) and by Anton La Guardia<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Directory|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/anton-la-guardia|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 June 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> (2010\u20132014).\n\n*'''''Erasmus''''' (Religion and public policy) \u2013 named after the Dutch [[Christian humanist]] [[Erasmus]].\n*'''''Game Theory''''' (Sport): named after [[Game theory|the science of predicting outcomes]] in a certain situation, this column focuses on \"sports major and minor\" and \"the politics, economics, science and statistics of the games we play and watch\".\n*'''''Johnson''''' (language): named for [[Samuel Johnson]], this column returned to the publication in 2016 and covers language. It is written by [[Robert Lane Greene]].\n*'''''Lexington''''' (United States): named for [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the site of the beginning of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. From June 2010 until May 2012 it was written by [[Peter David (journalist)|Peter David]], until his death in a car accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/lexington/2012/05/lexington|publisher=The Economist website|title=Lexington: Peter David|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''''Prospero''''' (Books and arts): named after the character from [[William Shakespeare's]] play ''[[The Tempest]]'', this column reviews books and focuses on arts-related issues.\n*'''''Schumpeter''''' (Business): named for the economist [[Joseph Schumpeter]], this column was established in September 2009 and is written by Patrick Foulis.\n\n* '''''Free Exchange''''' (Economics): a general economics column, frequently based on academic research, replaced the column ''Economics Focus'' in January 2012\n*'''Obituary''' (recent death): Since 1997 it has been written by [[Ann Wroe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|title=An Interview with Ann Wroe, Obituaries Writer for The Economist|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223130322/http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|archive-date=23 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper goes to press on Thursdays, between 6&nbsp;pm and 7&nbsp;pm GMT, and is available at newsagents in many countries the next day. It is printed at seven sites around the world. Known on their website as \"This week's print edition\", it is available online, albeit with only the first five viewed articles being free (and available to subscribers only mid-October 2009 \u2013 2010).\n\n''The Economist'' published in 2015 its first US college rankings, focused on comparable economical advantages defined as 'the economic value of a university is equal to the gap between how much its students subsequently earn, and how much they might have made had they studied elsewhere'. Based on set of strict criteria sourced from US Department of Education (\"College Scorecard\") with relevant 'expected earnings' and multiple statistics applied in calculation of 'median earnings' conclusive evaluation method has been applied to run the scorecard's earnings data through a multiple regression analysis, a common method of measuring the relationships between variables.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2015/10/value-university |title= The Economist \"The value of university: Our first-ever college rankings\"  |journal=The Economist |accessdate=29 October 2015|date= 29 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' also produces the annual ''The World in'' [''Year''] publication. It also sponsors a writing award.\n\n==Awards==\n===Innovation Awards===\n[[File:Dimitris Droutsas at The Economist conference.jpg|thumb|293x293px|Greek Foreign Minister [[Dimitrios Droutsas|Dimitris Droutsas]] speaking at 2011 Economist Conference. ]]\n''The Economist'' sponsors the yearly \"Economist Innovation Awards\", in the categories of bioscience, computing and communications, energy and the environment, social and economic innovation, business-process innovation, consumer products, and a special \"no boundaries\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|title=Economist Innovation Awards Categories|publisher=The Economist Group|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117061347/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref> The awards have been held since 2002. Nominations are held between 2 and 30 April. The award ceremony is then hosted on 15 November. Choices are based on the following factors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|title=Economist Innovation Awards Nomination Process|publisher=Economistconferences.co.uk|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507204053/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n* How much revenue their innovation has made their company or its economic impact on a specific good cause or society in general\n* The effect their work has had on the marketplace (or if it's created a whole new marketplace altogether)\n* The impact their innovation has had on a new type of science or technology\n\n===Writing prize===\nIn 1999, ''The Economist'' organised a global futurist writing competition, [[The World in 2050]]. Co-sponsored by [[Royal Dutch/Shell]], the competition included a first prize of [[United States dollar|US$]]20,000 and publication in ''The Economist''{{'}}s annual flagship publication, ''The World In''.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=20000422&id=01ZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2003,2039685 | title=What is your vision of the future? | work=New Straights Times | date=22 April 2000}}</ref> Over 3,000 entries from around the world were submitted via a website set up for the purpose and at various Royal Dutch Shell offices worldwide.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/>\n\nThe judging panel included [[Bill Emmott]],<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/> [[Esther Dyson]],<ref>{{cite news |title= Angel Investor Esther Dyson Increases Dosage in Health Startups|url=http://go.bloomberg.com/tech-deals/2012-12-26-angel-investor-esther-dyson-increases-dosage-of-health-startups/ |work= Bloomberg News|date= 26 December 2012}}</ref> Sir [[Mark Moody-Stuart]] (then-chairman of [[Royal Dutch Shell]]),<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\"/> and [[Matt Ridley]] (a British scientist and member of the [[House of Lords]]).<ref>{{cite news |title=Getting better all the time |url=https://www.economist.com/node/16103826|work=The Economist |date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\n[[File:A page ripped out from The Economist by China's censorship department (cropped).jpg|thumb|232x232px|A page ripped out from ''The Economist'' by China's censorship department in [[Liaoning Provincial Museum|Liaoning Provincial Library]]. ]]\nSections of ''The Economist'' criticising authoritarian regimes are frequently removed from the paper by the authorities in those countries. ''The Economist'' regularly has difficulties with the ruling party of Singapore, the [[People's Action Party]], which had successfully sued it, in a Singaporean court, for [[Defamation|libel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/HL01Ae01.html|title=Inconvenient truths in Singapore|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[Asia Times]] }}</ref>\n\nLike many other publications, ''The Economist'' is subjected to censorship in [[India]] whenever it depicts a map of [[Kashmir]]. The maps are stamped by Indian Customs officials as being \"neither correct, nor authentic\". Issues are sometimes delayed, but not stopped or seized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/12/censorship_india|title=Censorship in India|work=The Economist | date=7 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, [[Iran]] banned the sale of ''The Economist'' when it published a map labelling the [[Persian Gulf]] simply as Gulf\u2014a choice that derives its political significance from the [[Persian Gulf naming dispute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1150191582529&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Iran bans ''The Economist'' over map|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, the government of [[Zimbabwe]] went further and imprisoned ''The Economist''{{'}}s correspondent there, [[Andrew Meldrum]]. The government charged him with violating a statute on \"publishing untruth\" for writing that a woman was decapitated by supporters of the ruling [[Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] party. The [[decapitation]] claim was retracted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |title=Guardian and RFI correspondent risks two years in jail |accessdate=2 April 2014 |work=[[Reporters Without Borders]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404211952/http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |archivedate=4 April 2009 }}</ref> and allegedly fabricated by the woman's husband. The correspondent was later acquitted, only to receive a [[deportation]] order.\n\nOn 19 August 2013, ''The Economist'' disclosed that the Missouri Department of Corrections had censored its issue of 29 June 2013. According to the letter sent by the department, prisoners were not allowed to receive the issue because \"1. it constitutes a threat to the security or discipline of the institution; 2. may facilitate or encourage criminal activity; or 3. may interfere with the rehabilitation of an offender\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist in prison: About that missing issue|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2013/08/economist-prison|work=The Economist|accessdate=2 April 2014|date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of business newspapers]]\n* [[List of newspapers in the United Kingdom]]\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Media|Business|News|United Kingdom|Europe}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Arrese, Angel (1995), ''La identidad de The Economist,'' Pamplona: Eunsa. {{ISBN|9788431313739}}. ([https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326415042_La_identidad_de_The_Economist preview])\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thebalancesmb.com/best-business-magazines-4176680|title=The 8 Best Business Magazines of 2020|last=Delbridge|first=Emily|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Balance Small Business|publisher=Dotdash|location=New York City|page=|pages=|at=Best Economics Reporting: The Economist|doi=|pmid=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 Feb 2020|magazine=}}\n* Edwards, Ruth Dudley (1993), ''The Pursuit of Reason: The Economist 1843\u20131993'', London: Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-12939-7}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Media Monoliths|author=Tungate|first=Mark|location=|pages=194\u2013206|chapter=''The Economist''|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7494-4108-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|The_Economist.ogg|12 July 2006}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.economist.com/}}\n* {{HathiTrust Catalog}}\n\n{{Rothschilds}}\n{{The Economist Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economist, The}}\n\n<!--Do not add any categories about newsmagazine or magazines, The Economist is a newspaper, printed in magazine-format.-->\n[[Category:The Economist]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International newspapers]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Websites utilizing paywalls]]\n", "name_user": "DonSpencer1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Economist"}
{"title_page": "S.L. Benfica in European football", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox continental football\n| continent    = Europe\n| title        = S.L. Benfica in European football\n| image        = [[File:Benfica European cups in Museu Cosme Dami\u00e3o (cropped).JPG|250px]]\n| caption      = The [[1961 European Cup Final|1961]] and [[1962 European Cup Final|'62]] European Cup trophies on display at [[Museu Cosme Dami\u00e3o]]\n| club         = [[S.L. Benfica]]\n| european cup = '''2''' ([[1961 European Cup Final|1961]], [[1962 European Cup Final|1962]])\n| first entry  = [[1957\u201358 European Cup]]\n| last entry   = [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League]]\n}}\n[[S.L. Benfica|Sport Lisboa e Benfica]] is a Portuguese professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Lisbon]], whose involvement in European competition dates back to the 1950s. As [[1954\u201355 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|champions of Portugal]], Benfica were supposed to participate in the [[1955\u201356 European Cup|inaugural edition]] of the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] in 1955, but they were not invited by the organizers. Two years later, they made their European debut against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the European Cup, on 19 September 1957.\n\nBenfica won their first European title in [[1961 European Cup Final|1961]], defeating [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] to win the European Cup, and successfully retained the title in [[1962 European Cup Final|the following year]] after defeating [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. After that, they appeared in five more finals \u2013 [[1962\u201363 European Cup|1963]], [[1965 European Cup Final|'65]], [[1968 European Cup Final|'68]], [[1988 European Cup Final|'88]] and [[1990 European Cup Final|'90]] \u2013 but failed to reconquer the title. These consecutive final losses have been attributed to a famous [[Sports-related curses|curse]] by Hungarian manager [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]] in 1962. Benfica have also played in three [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup/UEFA Europa League]] finals \u2013 [[1983 UEFA Cup Final|1983]], [[2013 UEFA Europa League Final|2013]] and [[2014 UEFA Europa League Final|'14]] \u2013 losing all three.\n\nWith 2 titles, Benfica are the second most decorated Portuguese team in [[UEFA competitions]], and hold the Portuguese record for most appearances in [[UEFA Competitions' finals|UEFA competitions' finals]], with 10 appearances. Additionally, the 39 participations in the Champions League (formerly the European Cup) are only surpassed by Real Madrid and they occupy, as of 11 March 2020, the eighh place at the [[European Cup and UEFA Champions League records and statistics#All-time top 25 European Champion Clubs' Cup and Champions League rankings|competition's all-time ranking]]. \n\nBenfica's biggest European win is 10\u20130, which came against [[Stade Dudelange]] of Luxembourg for the [[1965\u201366 European Cup]], and their 18\u20130 aggregate win constitutes a European Cup record. Brazilian defender [[Luis\u00e3o]] holds the club record for appearances in Europe, with 124 matches, while former Portuguese striker [[Eus\u00e9bio]] is the club's leading European goalscorer, with 56 goals. \n\n==Background==\n{{Further|UEFA competitions}}\nThe first continental competition organised by [[UEFA]] was the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] in 1955. Conceived by [[Gabriel Hanot]], the editor of ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'', as a competition for winners of the European national football leagues, it is considered the most prestigious European football competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/history/index.html|title=Football's premier club competition|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=25 December 2011}}</ref> That year, Benfica had won the [[1954\u201355 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|Primeira Divis\u00e3o]], but the competition organizers selected [[Sporting CP]] to take part in the first edition.<ref name=\"1st edition\">{{cite web|title=50 years of European Cup|url=https://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/240459.pdf#page=6|website=[[UEFA]]|date=October 2004|pages=6\u20137|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Another club competition, the [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]], was established in 1955 and contested in parallel with the European Cup. It eventually came under the auspices of UEFA in 1971, which rebranded it to [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]. Since the 2009\u201310 season, the competition has been known as the UEFA Europa League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7637600.stm |title=Uefa Cup given new name in revamp|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=26 September 2008|access-date=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957, Benfica won the [[1956\u201357 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|league title]] and assured their European debut in the [[1957\u201358 European Cup]]. In the following years, UEFA created additional club competitions. The first, the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]], was inaugurated in 1960 for the winners of domestic cup competitions. Established in 1973, the [[UEFA Super Cup]] was originally a match played between the winners of the European Cup and the Cup Winners' Cup. Since 2000, it has been contested by the winners of the Champions League (formerly the European Cup) and the Europa League (formerly the UEFA Cup).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/index.html|title=Club competition winners do battle|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] was a competition for the winners of the European Cup (the later UEFA Champions League) and its South American equivalent, the [[Copa Libertadores]]. Established in 1960, the Intercontinental Cup was jointly organised by UEFA and the [[CONMEBOL|Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol]] (CONMEBOL). It ran until 2004, when it was replaced by the [[FIFA Club World Cup]], which includes the winners of all [[FIFA#Structure|six continental confederations]]' premier club competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/format/index.html|title=Competition format|website=[[UEFA]]|date=13 July 2005|access-date=2 September 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708050711/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/format/index.html|archive-date=8 July 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n==European champions and Guttmann's curse (1950\u201379)==\nBenfica's first European silverware came in 1950 when, managed by [[Ted Smith (footballer, born 1914)|Ted Smith]], they beat French side [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] at the [[Est\u00e1dio Nacional]] in [[Oeiras, Portugal]], to win the [[Latin Cup]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=220}} Seven years later, the team reached their second and last Latin Cup final, but lost to [[Alfredo Di St\u00e9fano]]'s [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=261}} After an unsuccessful UEFA competition debut in the 1957\u201358 European Cup, where they lost to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the initial round,<ref>{{cite web|title=1957/58: Di St\u00e9fano shines for Madrid|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1957/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica hired Hungarian manager [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]], who led the team to their first European Cup final ever on 31 May 1961.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=287}} Having overcome [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]], [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest D\u00f3zsa]], [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|AGF Aarhus]] and [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]], Benfica faced [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the final, where goals from [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1guas]], [[M\u00e1rio Coluna]] and an own goal from [[Antoni Ramallets]] helped the club lift its first European Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=1960/61: Eagles soar to end Madrid monopoly|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1960/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=31 March 1961|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> In the following year, already with [[Eus\u00e9bio]] in the lineup, Guttmann guided the team to back-to-back European Cup successes. After defeating [[FK Austria Wien|Austria Wien]], [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]],{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=294}}<ref name=\"Spurs v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=Spurs V Benfica (1962)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30eDS8JQG4s|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=YouTube}}</ref> Benfica met Real Madrid in the final on 2 May 1962. A hat-trick from [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] put [[1960\u201361 La Liga|the Spanish champions]] ahead before half-time, but a double from Coluna and rising star Eus\u00e9bio overturned the score to 5\u20133.<ref name=\"Real Madrid v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=Real Madrid V Benfica - European Cup Final In Amsterdam (1962)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0xIzCg2IyY|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1961/62: Eus\u00e9bio strikes gold for Benfica|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1961/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=2 May 1962|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> {{Quote box|quote=Not in a hundred years from now will Benfica ever be European champions.|source=\u2014 [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldsoccer.com/blogs/bela-guttmann-curse-benfica-351924|title=B\u00e9la Guttmann and the curse of Benfica|website=[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]|date=18 May 2014|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> |align=right |quoted=1 |width=33%}}\n\nAfter consecutive European Cup wins, Guttmann approached the club's board of directors asking for a pay rise. As his demand was turned down, he left the club and professed his famous curse.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benfica 'curse': What is the Curse of Bela Guttman and where does it rank among sports greatest superstitions?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/europa-league-final--seville-0-benfica-0-what-is-the-curse-of-bela-guttman-and-where-does-it-rank-among-sports-greatest-superstitions-9373886.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=15 May 2014|access-date=7 May 2015}}</ref> Benfica replaced him with [[Fernando Riera]], and while the Chilean manager led the team to a third-straight European Cup final, he failed to emulate Guttmann's success. On 25 May 1963, against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], Benfica's chances were slim after a harsh tackle from [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] on Coluna severely debilitated him. In a time when substitutions did not exist, Benfica played the rest of the match crippled, and two second-half goals from [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]] sent the trophy to Italy.<ref name=\"Milan v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=1963 European Cup Final - Milan V Benfica (1963)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30eDS8JQG4s|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Final: Les\u00e3o de Coluna hipoteca \"tri\" do Benfica, em 1963|trans-title=Coluna's injury compromises Benfica's 'treble'|url=https://www.futebol365.pt/noticia/84644/|work=Futebol365.com|date=10 May 2013|access-date=7 May 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=1962/63: Altafini strikes for Milan|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1962/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=22 May 1963|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> After a poor performance in the [[1963\u201364 European Cup]], Benfica returned to the final in the [[1964\u201365 European Cup|following season]]. Led by Romanian manager [[Elek Schwartz]], Benfica eliminated Real Madrid 5\u20131 in the quarter-finals on their way to meet the holders [[Inter Milan]] in the final, which was played at Inter's home ground, [[San Siro]], in a muddy and waterlogged pitch.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=316}} A mistake from [[Alberto da Costa Pereira]], allowing a shot from [[Jair da Costa|Jair]] to pass between his legs, cost Benfica their second attempt at a European Cup treble.<ref>{{cite news|title=1964/65: Jair the difference for Inter|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1964/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=27 May 1965|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, Benfica defeated [[Stade Dudelange]] 18\u20130 on aggregate, establishing a European record for biggest win on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stokkermans|first1=Karel|title=Champions' Cup Records|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ecc.html#rec|website=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] (RSSSF)|access-date=12 June 2015}}</ref> However, at a later stage of the competition, they conceded a record home defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and were eliminated.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=323}} After one year competing in the Inter-Cities Fairs Cup,{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=334}} Benfica returned to the European Cup and reached their fifth final in 1968. After eliminating [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] 3\u20130 in the semi-finals, Benfica faced Manchester United at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] on 29 May 1968. [[Bobby Charlton]] opened the score, but [[Jaime Gra\u00e7a]] equalised on the 79th minute. Near the end of regular time, Eus\u00e9bio squandered a one-on-one chance against [[Alex Stepney]] and the match went to [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]], where three goals in eight minutes gave the English side their first European title.<ref>{{cite web|title=1967/68: Charlton leads United charge|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1967/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=29 May 1968|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\nThe [[1968\u201369 European Cup|following season]], Benfica were stopped in the quarter-finals by [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] after a replay in [[Paris]]. As in the previous season's final, Benfica conceded three goals during extra time and were eliminated.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=343}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1968/69: Prati rises to the occasion|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1968/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> In [[1969\u201370 European Cup|1969\u201370]], Benfica fell in the second round against Scottish team and eventual finalists [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in a [[Coin flipping|coin toss decision]].<ref>{{cite news|title=1969/70: Feyenoord establish new order|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1969/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=6 May 1970|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter a mildly successful period in the 1960s, where they stood among the top contenders, Southern European teams started to lose influence in the European stage during the 1970s, as Dutch and German teams appeared stronger. In the [[1971\u201372 European Cup]], Benfica lost in the semi-finals to a [[Johan Cruyff]]-led Ajax on their way to a second consecutive win.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=365}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1971/72: Cruyff double keeps Ajax in command|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1971/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=31 May 1972|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica reached the quarter-finals of the [[1974\u201375 European Cup Winners' Cup]] before being eliminated by another Dutch team, [[PSV Eindhoven]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=384}} Over the course of the late 1970s, as historic players like Eus\u00e9bio and [[Ant\u00f3nio Sim\u00f5es|Sim\u00f5es]] retired, Benfica could not maintain the same performance of the previous decade, and only secured two European Cup quarter-final presences. In [[1975\u201376 European Cup|1975\u201376]], they lost 5\u20131 to the holders [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]],<ref>{{cite web|title=1975/76: Roth completes Bayern hat-trick|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1975/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> and in [[1977\u201378 European Cup|1977\u201378]] they were knocked out by the defending champions [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a 6\u20132 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news|title=1977/78: Dalglish keeps Reds on top|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1977/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Competitive record ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Opponent\n! Home\n! Away\n! [[Two-legged tie|Agg.]]\n|-\n| [[1955\u201356 European Cup|1955\u201356]]\n| rowspan=7 align=\"left\"|[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]\n| colspan=5|Denied entry<ref name=\"1st edition\"/>\n|-\n| [[1957\u201358 European Cup|1957\u201358]]\n| {{Tooltip|PR|Preliminary round}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20133\n| 1\u20133\n|-\n| rowspan=5|[[1960\u201361 European Cup|1960\u201361]]\n| {{Tooltip|PR|Preliminary round}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Scotland}} [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|3\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2\u20131\n| 5\u20131\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Hungary}} [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest D\u00f3zsa]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|6\u20132\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20132\n| 7\u20134\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|QF|Quarter-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|AGF]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|4\u20131\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|3\u20131\n| 7\u20132\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|SF|Semi-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Austria}} [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|3\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|1\u20131\n| 4\u20131\n|-\n| [[1961 European Cup Final|F]]\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|3\u20132\n|-\n| [[1961 Intercontinental Cup|1961]]\n| align=\"left\"|[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Pe\u00f1arol]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20135\n| 2pts\u20132pts (1\u20132 [[R