]\n|-\n| [[1967\u201368 European Cup|1968]]\n| European Cup\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| 3\u20130\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]<br />{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n|-\n| [[1982\u201383 UEFA Cup|1983]]\n| UEFA Cup\n| {{flagicon|Romania}} [[CS Universitatea Craiova|Universitatea Craiova]]\n| 1\u20131 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n| {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]]<br />{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} [[Bohemians 1905|Bohemians \u010cKD Prague]]\n|-\n| [[1987\u201388 European Cup|1988]]\n| European Cup\n| {{flagicon|Romania}} [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]]\n| 2\u20130\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[PSV Eindhoven]]<br />{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n|-\n| [[1989\u201390 European Cup|1990]]\n| European Cup\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n| 2\u20132 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]<br />{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|-\n| [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League|2013]]\n| UEFA Europa League\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]]\n| 3\u20132\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]<br />{{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[FC Basel|Basel]]\n|-\n| [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|2014]]\n| UEFA Europa League\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| 2\u20131\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]<br />{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Semi-finals lost===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Competition\n! Opposing team\n! Score\n! Other semi-finalists\n|-\n| [[1971\u201372 European Cup|1972]]\n| European Cup\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| 0\u20131\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Inter Milan]]<br />{{flagicon|Scotland}} [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n|-\n| [[1980\u201381 European Cup Winners' Cup|1981]]\n| Cup Winners' Cup\n| {{flagicon|East Germany}} [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena|Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n| 1\u20132\n| {{flagicon|Soviet Union}} [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]]<br />{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Feyenoord]]\n|-\n| [[1993\u201394 European Cup Winners' Cup|1994]]\n| Cup Winners' Cup\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[S.S.D. Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n| 2\u20132 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]<br />{{flagicon|France}} [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]\n|-\n| [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|2011]]\n| UEFA Europa League\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[S.C. Braga|Braga]]\n| 2\u20132 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[FC Porto|Porto]]<br />{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book|last=Tovar|first=Rui Miguel|year=2012|title=Almanaque do Benfica|trans-title=Benfica Almanac|language=pt|others=Revised by Lu\u00eds Milheiro|edition=1st|location=Alfragide, Portugal|publisher=Lua de Papel|isbn=978-989-23-2087-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pereira|first=Lu\u00eds Miguel|date=December 2011|title=O Livro de Recordes do Benfica|trans-title=Benfica records book|language=pt|edition=1st|location=Portugal|publisher=Prime Books|isbn=978-989-655-109-4|ref=harv}}\n\n{{S.L. Benfica}}\n{{Portuguese clubs in European football}}\n\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica|Europe]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football clubs in European football|Benfica]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox continental football\n| continent    = Europe\n| title        = S.L. Benfica in European football\n| image        = [[File:Benfica European cups in Museu Cosme Dami\u00e3o (cropped).JPG|250px]]\n| caption      = The [[1961 European Cup Final|1961]] and [[1962 European Cup Final|'62]] European Cup trophies on display at [[Museu Cosme Dami\u00e3o]]\n| club         = [[S.L. Benfica]]\n| european cup = '''2''' ([[1961 European Cup Final|1961]], [[1962 European Cup Final|1962]])\n| first entry  = [[1957\u201358 European Cup]]\n| last entry   = [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League]]\n}}\n[[S.L. Benfica|Sport Lisboa e Benfica]] is a Portuguese professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Lisbon]], whose involvement in European competition dates back to the 1950s. As [[1954\u201355 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|champions of Portugal]], Benfica were supposed to participate in the [[1955\u201356 European Cup|inaugural edition]] of the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] in 1955, but they were not invited by the organizers. Two years later, they made their European debut against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the European Cup, on 19 September 1957.\n\nBenfica won their first European title in [[1961 European Cup Final|1961]], defeating [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] to win the European Cup, and successfully retained the title in [[1962 European Cup Final|the following year]] after defeating [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. After that, they appeared in five more finals \u2013 [[1962\u201363 European Cup|1963]], [[1965 European Cup Final|'65]], [[1968 European Cup Final|'68]], [[1988 European Cup Final|'88]] and [[1990 European Cup Final|'90]] \u2013 but failed to reconquer the title. These consecutive final losses have been attributed to a famous [[Sports-related curses|curse]] by Hungarian manager [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]] in 1962. Benfica have also played in three [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup/UEFA Europa League]] finals \u2013 [[1983 UEFA Cup Final|1983]], [[2013 UEFA Europa League Final|2013]] and [[2014 UEFA Europa League Final|'14]] \u2013 losing all three.\n\nWith 2 titles, Benfica are the second most decorated Portuguese team in [[UEFA competitions]], and hold the Portuguese record for most appearances in [[UEFA Competitions' finals|UEFA competitions' finals]], with 10 appearances. Additionally, the 39 participations in the Champions League (formerly the European Cup) are only surpassed by Real Madrid and they occupy, as of 11 March 2020, the eighh place at the [[European Cup and UEFA Champions League records and statistics#All-time top 25 European Champion Clubs' Cup and Champions League rankings|competition's all-time ranking]]. \n\nBenfica's biggest European win is 10\u20130, which came against [[Stade Dudelange]] of Luxembourg for the [[1965\u201366 European Cup]], and their 18\u20130 aggregate win constitutes a European Cup record. Brazilian defender [[Luis\u00e3o]] holds the club record for appearances in Europe, with 124 matches, while former Portuguese striker [[Eus\u00e9bio]] is the club's leading European goalscorer, with 56 goals. \n\n==Background==\n{{Further|UEFA competitions}}\nThe first continental competition organised by [[UEFA]] was the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] in 1955. Conceived by [[Gabriel Hanot]], the editor of ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'', as a competition for winners of the European national football leagues, it is considered the most prestigious European football competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/history/index.html|title=Football's premier club competition|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=25 December 2011}}</ref> That year, Benfica had won the [[1954\u201355 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|Primeira Divis\u00e3o]], but the competition organizers selected [[Sporting CP]] to take part in the first edition.<ref name=\"1st edition\">{{cite web|title=50 years of European Cup|url=https://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/240459.pdf#page=6|website=[[UEFA]]|date=October 2004|pages=6\u20137|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Another club competition, the [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]], was established in 1955 and contested in parallel with the European Cup. It eventually came under the auspices of UEFA in 1971, which rebranded it to [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]. Since the 2009\u201310 season, the competition has been known as the UEFA Europa League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7637600.stm |title=Uefa Cup given new name in revamp|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=26 September 2008|access-date=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957, Benfica won the [[1956\u201357 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|league title]] and assured their European debut in the [[1957\u201358 European Cup]]. In the following years, UEFA created additional club competitions. The first, the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]], was inaugurated in 1960 for the winners of domestic cup competitions. Established in 1973, the [[UEFA Super Cup]] was originally a match played between the winners of the European Cup and the Cup Winners' Cup. Since 2000, it has been contested by the winners of the Champions League (formerly the European Cup) and the Europa League (formerly the UEFA Cup).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/index.html|title=Club competition winners do battle|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] was a competition for the winners of the European Cup (the later UEFA Champions League) and its South American equivalent, the [[Copa Libertadores]]. Established in 1960, the Intercontinental Cup was jointly organised by UEFA and the [[CONMEBOL|Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol]] (CONMEBOL). It ran until 2004, when it was replaced by the [[FIFA Club World Cup]], which includes the winners of all [[FIFA#Structure|six continental confederations]]' premier club competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/format/index.html|title=Competition format|website=[[UEFA]]|date=13 July 2005|access-date=2 September 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708050711/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/format/index.html|archive-date=8 July 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n==European champions and Guttmann's curse (1950\u201379)==\nBenfica's first European silverware came in 1950 when, managed by [[Ted Smith (footballer, born 1914)|Ted Smith]], they beat French side [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] at the [[Est\u00e1dio Nacional]] in [[Oeiras, Portugal]], to win the [[Latin Cup]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=220}} Seven years later, the team reached their second and last Latin Cup final, but lost to [[Alfredo Di St\u00e9fano]]'s [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=261}} After an unsuccessful UEFA competition debut in the 1957\u201358 European Cup, where they lost to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the initial round,<ref>{{cite web|title=1957/58: Di St\u00e9fano shines for Madrid|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1957/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica hired Hungarian manager [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]], who led the team to their first European Cup final ever on 31 May 1961.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=287}} Having overcome [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]], [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest D\u00f3zsa]], [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|AGF Aarhus]] and [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]], Benfica faced [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the final, where goals from [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1guas]], [[M\u00e1rio Coluna]] and an own goal from [[Antoni Ramallets]] helped the club lift its first European Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=1960/61: Eagles soar to end Madrid monopoly|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1960/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=31 March 1961|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> In the following year, already with [[Eus\u00e9bio]] in the lineup, Guttmann guided the team to back-to-back European Cup successes. After defeating [[FK Austria Wien|Austria Wien]], [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]],{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=294}}<ref name=\"Spurs v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=Spurs V Benfica (1962)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30eDS8JQG4s|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=YouTube}}</ref> Benfica met Real Madrid in the final on 2 May 1962. A hat-trick from [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] put [[1960\u201361 La Liga|the Spanish champions]] ahead before half-time, but a double from Coluna and rising star Eus\u00e9bio overturned the score to 5\u20133.<ref name=\"Real Madrid v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=Real Madrid V Benfica - European Cup Final In Amsterdam (1962)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0xIzCg2IyY|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1961/62: Eus\u00e9bio strikes gold for Benfica|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1961/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=2 May 1962|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> {{Quote box|quote=Not in a hundred years from now will Benfica ever be European champions.|source=\u2014 [[B\u00e9la Guttmann]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldsoccer.com/blogs/bela-guttmann-curse-benfica-351924|title=B\u00e9la Guttmann and the curse of Benfica|website=[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]|date=18 May 2014|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> |align=right |quoted=1 |width=33%}}\n\nAfter consecutive European Cup wins, Guttmann approached the club's board of directors asking for a pay rise. As his demand was turned down, he left the club and professed his famous curse.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benfica 'curse': What is the Curse of Bela Guttman and where does it rank among sports greatest superstitions?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/europa-league-final--seville-0-benfica-0-what-is-the-curse-of-bela-guttman-and-where-does-it-rank-among-sports-greatest-superstitions-9373886.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=15 May 2014|access-date=7 May 2015}}</ref> Benfica replaced him with [[Fernando Riera]], and while the Chilean manager led the team to a third-straight European Cup final, he failed to emulate Guttmann's success. On 25 May 1963, against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], Benfica's chances were slim after a harsh tackle from [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] on Coluna severely debilitated him. In a time when substitutions did not exist, Benfica played the rest of the match crippled, and two second-half goals from [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]] sent the trophy to Italy.<ref name=\"Milan v Benfica\">{{cite AV media|date=13 April 2014|title=1963 European Cup Final - Milan V Benfica (1963)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30eDS8JQG4s|access-date=15 April 2019|publisher=[[Path\u00e9 News|British Path\u00e9]]|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Final: Les\u00e3o de Coluna hipoteca \"tri\" do Benfica, em 1963|trans-title=Coluna's injury compromises Benfica's 'treble'|url=https://www.futebol365.pt/noticia/84644/|work=Futebol365.com|date=10 May 2013|access-date=7 May 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=1962/63: Altafini strikes for Milan|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1962/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=22 May 1963|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> After a poor performance in the [[1963\u201364 European Cup]], Benfica returned to the final in the [[1964\u201365 European Cup|following season]]. Led by Romanian manager [[Elek Schwartz]], Benfica eliminated Real Madrid 5\u20131 in the quarter-finals on their way to meet the holders [[Inter Milan]] in the final, which was played at Inter's home ground, [[San Siro]], in a muddy and waterlogged pitch.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=316}} A mistake from [[Alberto da Costa Pereira]], allowing a shot from [[Jair da Costa|Jair]] to pass between his legs, cost Benfica their second attempt at a European Cup treble.<ref>{{cite news|title=1964/65: Jair the difference for Inter|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1964/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=27 May 1965|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, Benfica defeated [[Stade Dudelange]] 18\u20130 on aggregate, establishing a European record for biggest win on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stokkermans|first1=Karel|title=Champions' Cup Records|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ecc.html#rec|website=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] (RSSSF)|access-date=12 June 2015}}</ref> However, at a later stage of the competition, they conceded a record home defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and were eliminated.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=323}} After one year competing in the Inter-Cities Fairs Cup,{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=334}} Benfica returned to the European Cup and reached their fifth final in 1968. After eliminating [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] 3\u20130 in the semi-finals, Benfica faced Manchester United at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] on 29 May 1968. [[Bobby Charlton]] opened the score, but [[Jaime Gra\u00e7a]] equalised on the 79th minute. Near the end of regular time, Eus\u00e9bio squandered a one-on-one chance against [[Alex Stepney]] and the match went to [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]], where three goals in eight minutes gave the English side their first European title.<ref>{{cite web|title=1967/68: Charlton leads United charge|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1967/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=29 May 1968|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\nThe [[1968\u201369 European Cup|following season]], Benfica were stopped in the quarter-finals by [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] after a replay in [[Paris]]. As in the previous season's final, Benfica conceded three goals during extra time and were eliminated.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=343}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1968/69: Prati rises to the occasion|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1968/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> In [[1969\u201370 European Cup|1969\u201370]], Benfica fell in the second round against Scottish team and eventual finalists [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in a [[Coin flipping|coin toss decision]].<ref>{{cite news|title=1969/70: Feyenoord establish new order|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1969/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=6 May 1970|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter a mildly successful period in the 1960s, where they stood among the top contenders, Southern European teams started to lose influence in the European stage during the 1970s, as Dutch and German teams appeared stronger. In the [[1971\u201372 European Cup]], Benfica lost in the semi-finals to a [[Johan Cruyff]]-led Ajax on their way to a second consecutive win.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=365}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1971/72: Cruyff double keeps Ajax in command|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1971/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=31 May 1972|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica reached the quarter-finals of the [[1974\u201375 European Cup Winners' Cup]] before being eliminated by another Dutch team, [[PSV Eindhoven]].{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=384}} Over the course of the late 1970s, as historic players like Eus\u00e9bio and [[Ant\u00f3nio Sim\u00f5es|Sim\u00f5es]] retired, Benfica could not maintain the same performance of the previous decade, and only secured two European Cup quarter-final presences. In [[1975\u201376 European Cup|1975\u201376]], they lost 5\u20131 to the holders [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]],<ref>{{cite web|title=1975/76: Roth completes Bayern hat-trick|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1975/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> and in [[1977\u201378 European Cup|1977\u201378]] they were knocked out by the defending champions [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a 6\u20132 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news|title=1977/78: Dalglish keeps Reds on top|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1977/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Competitive record ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Opponent\n! Home\n! Away\n! [[Two-legged tie|Agg.]]\n|-\n| [[1955\u201356 European Cup|1955\u201356]]\n| rowspan=7 align=\"left\"|[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]\n| colspan=5|Denied entry<ref name=\"1st edition\"/>\n|-\n| [[1957\u201358 European Cup|1957\u201358]]\n| {{Tooltip|PR|Preliminary round}