=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| 2\u20130\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Hungary}} [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest D\u00f3zsa]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|1\u20131\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20132\n| 1\u20133\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[1974\u201375 European Cup Winners' Cup|1974\u201375]]\n| rowspan=3 align=\"left\"|Cup Winners' Cup\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Vanl\u00f8se IF|Vanl\u00f8se]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|4\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|4\u20131\n| 8\u20131\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|East Germany}} [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena|Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|1\u20131\n| 1\u20131 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|QF|Quarter-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20132\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| 1\u20132\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[1975\u201376 European Cup|1975\u201376]]\n| rowspan=7 align=\"left\"|European Cup\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|7\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20131\n| 7\u20131\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Hungary}} [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest D\u00f3zsa]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|5\u20132\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20133\n| 6\u20135\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|QF|Quarter-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20135\n| 1\u20135\n|-\n| [[1976\u201377 European Cup|1976\u201377]]\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|East Germany}} [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20132\n| 0\u20132\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[1977\u201378 European Cup|1977\u201378]]\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} [[FC Torpedo Moscow|Torpedo Moscow]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130 ([[Overtime (sports)#Association football|aet]])\n| 0\u20130 {{pso|4\u20131}}\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| 2\u20130\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|QF|Quarter-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|England}} [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20132\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20134\n| 2\u20136\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[1978\u201379 UEFA Cup|1978\u201379]]\n| rowspan=3 align=\"left\"|[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|France}} [[FC Nantes|Nantes]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2\u20130\n| 2\u20130\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20132\n| 0\u20132\n|-\n| [[1979\u201380 UEFA Cup|1979\u201380]]\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2\u20131\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|1\u20133\n| 3\u20134\n|}\n<small>Note: Benfica score is always listed first.</small>\n\n==Chasing the dream (1980\u201395)==\nIn the beginning of the 1980s, Benfica's domestic dominance had dwindled, leaving the team to play in second-level competitions, namely the Cup Winners' Cup and the UEFA Cup. In [[1980\u201381 European Cup Winners' Cup|1980\u201381]], the team reached the Cup Winners' Cup semi-finals but lost to [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena|Carl Zeiss Jena]] from East Germany.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=425}} This performance was bested two seasons later, as Benfica reached the [[1983 UEFA Cup Final]] after overcoming a quarter-final bout against a [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] side featuring [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]] and [[Bruno Conti]]. In the two-legged final, Benfica faced Belgium's [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]]. In the first leg, on 4 May 1983, Benfica lost in [[Brussels]] with a sole goal from [[Kenneth Brylle Larsen|Kenneth Brylle]]. In the second leg, fourteen days later, Benfica manager [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] chose not to start [[Zoran Filipovi\u0107]] and [[Jo\u00e3o Alves (footballer, born 1952)|Jo\u00e3o Alves]], both undisputed starters, and the team drew 1\u20131 and lost another European final.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=440}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1982/83: Anderlecht shine in Stadium of Light|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1982/overview/index.html#198283+anderlecht+shine+stadium+light|website=[[UEFA]]|date=1 June 1983|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica returned to the European Cup in the following two seasons, but defeats against Liverpool in both participations showed that the team was not yet ready to compete with Europe's best teams.<ref>{{cite web|title=1983/84: Kennedy spot on for Liverpool|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1983/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=30 May 1984|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n{{Multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| width     = 200\n| footer   = [[Mercedes-Benz Arena (Stuttgart)|Mercedes-Benz Arena]] (former Neckarstadion) and [[Ernst-Happel-Stadion]] (former Praterstadion)\n| image1    = Neckarstadion 2011 - 2.jpg\n| image2    = EHStadion040606w.jpg\n}}\nAfter four seasons, Benfica proved ready to challenge for the European Cup in [[1987\u201388 European Cup|1987\u201388]]. After eliminating teams like Anderlecht and [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]], they reached their sixth final in the competition, where they met PSV in a match played at [[Stuttgart]]'s [[Mercedes-Benz Arena (Stuttgart)|Neckarstadion]] on 25 May 1988.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=476}} Following a goalless draw at the end of extra time, the match was decided by a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]]. The Dutch side \u2013 fielding five [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]] players that would go on to conquer the [[UEFA Euro 1988]] a month later \u2013 converted all of their penalty kicks, whereas [[Ant\u00f3nio Veloso]] allowed goalkeeper [[Hans van Breukelen]] to defend his penalty kick, and secured Benfica's fourth consecutive European Cup final loss.<ref>{{cite web|title=1987/88: PSV prosper from Oranje boom|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1987/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=25 May 1988|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Benfica did not wait long to make another appearance in the European Cup's showpiece match, as two years later \u2013 and with Swedish manager Eriksson again in charge \u2013 a team including [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]'s starting centre-backs [[Ricardo Gomes]] and [[Aldair]], together with midfielders [[Valdo Filho|Valdo]] and [[Jonas Thern]], eliminated [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] with a controversial handled goal from [[Vata Matanu Garcia|Vata]] to reach their seventh European Cup final.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=492}} Before [[1990 European Cup Final|the final]], Eus\u00e9bio visited B\u00e9la Guttmann's grave, asking for forgiveness in hope of ending the curse.<ref name=\"curse daily mail\">{{cite news|title=Not even Jesus can break the Guttman curse! Benfica's 50-year European hoodoo continues with defeat by Chelsea|url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2325408/The-Bela-Guttman-curse-continues-haunt-Benfica-Europa-League-final.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=16 May 2013|access-date=13 June 2015}}</ref> On 23 May 1990, Benfica faced title-holders Milan at [[Vienna]]'s [[Ernst-Happel-Stadion|Praterstadion]] and were unable to prevent [[Frank Rijkaard]] to score the winning goal and give the Italian side its fourth and second consecutive European Cup title.<ref>{{cite news|title=1989/90: Rijkaard seals Milan triumph|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1989/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=23 May 1990|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, Benfica took part in the [[1991\u201392 European Cup|last edition of the European Cup]] before being reformulated and converted into the UEFA Champions League. They reached the tournament's group stage after a successful performance at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], with [[Isa\u00edas Marques Soares|Isa\u00edas]] and [[Vasili Kulkov]] scoring in extra time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arsenal outclassed in extra time|newspaper=[[The Times]]|page=40|location=London|first=Stuart|last=Jones|date=7 November 1991}}</ref> In the group stage, Benfica ended in third place, behind Barcelona and [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1991/92: Koeman ends Barcelona's wait|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1991/standings/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|access-date=8 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205073753/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1991/standings/index.html|archivedate=5 February 2018}}</ref> In [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|1992\u201393]], Benfica reached the quarter-finals of the UEFA Cup, beating eventual winners Juventus at home (their only loss in the competition), but losing 3\u20131 in [[Turin]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1992/93: Juventus claim record third success|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1992/overview/index.html#199293+juve+seal+trick|website=[[UEFA]]|date=1 June 1993|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> The following season, Benfica returned to the [[1993\u201394 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] and reached the semi-finals after a 5\u20135 aggregate draw against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in the quarter-finals was decided on [[away goals rule|away goals]]. In [[Lisbon]], Benfica beat [[S.S.D. Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] 2\u20131 for the first leg of the semi-finals, with [[V\u00edtor Paneira]] even missing a penalty. However, in the return leg, centre-back [[Carlos Mozer]] was sent off on the 20th minute and the team resisted for 55 minutes before [[Roberto Sensini]] scored the only goal of the match, which put the Italians through.{{sfn|Tovar|2012|p=524}} In their debut in the Champions League in [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League|1994\u201395]], Benfica won their group but succumbed to Milan in the knockout phase.<ref>{{cite web|title=1994/95: Kluivert strikes late for Ajax|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1994/overview/index.html|website=[[UEFA]]|date=24 May 1995|access-date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Competitive record ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Opponent\n! Home\n! Away\n! [[Two-legged tie|Agg.]]\n|-\n| rowspan=5|[[1980\u201381 European Cup Winners' Cup|1980\u201381]]\n| rowspan=5 align=\"left\"|[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| {{Tooltip|PR|Preliminary round}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Altay S.K.|Altay]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|4\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| 4\u20130\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|0\u20130\n| 2\u20130\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|R2|Round 2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20131\n| 2\u20131\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|QF|Quarter-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffffdd\"|2\u20132\n| 3\u20132\n|-\n| {{Tooltip|SF|Semi-finals}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|East Germany}} [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena|Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|1\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#ffdddd\"|0\u20132\n| 1\u20132\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[1981\u201382 European Cup|1981\u201382]]\n| rowspan=2 align=\"left\"|[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]\n| {{Tooltip|R1|Round 1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Cyprus}} [[AC Omonia|Omonia]]\n| bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|3\u20130\n| bgcolor=\"#dd