 =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Mrs H. Iles and Albert Iles whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He also played for Tauranga against Te Puke and despite recently joining the rugby code was named captain\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the Tauranga area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against Hamilton<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calfskins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in Te Puke, Whakatane, and Taneatua and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga Rugby\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =\n|ru_triesA           =0\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =0\n|ru_teamB            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = \n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Mrs H. Iles and Albert Iles whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He also played for Tauranga against Te Puke and despite recently joing the rugby code was named captain\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the Tauranga area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against Hamilton<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calfskins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in Te Puke, Whakatane, and Taneatua and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRugby Union Playing Career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "CID (Indian TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian television crime series}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = CID\n| image                    = CID (Indian TV series).png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{unbulleted list|[[Crime Fiction]]|[[Suspense]]|[[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]}}\n| creator                  = [[B. P. Singh]]\n| creative_director        = Christabelle D'souza\n| writer                   = \n| starring                 = [[#Cast|See below]]\n| country                  = [[India]]\n| language                 = [[Hindi]]\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 1,547\n| producer                 = {{unbulleted list|B.P. Singh,<br>[[Pradeep Uppoor]]}}\n| location                 = [[Mumbai]], <br>[[Maharashtra]], <br>[[India]]\n| runtime                  = 40\u201345 minutes\n| company                  = Fireworks Productions\n| distributor              = [[Sony Pictures Networks]]\n| network                  = [[Sony Entertainment Television]]\n| picture_format           = {{unbulleted list|[[480i]]|[[HDTV]] [[1080i]]}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=yes|1998|01|21}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=yes|2018|10|27}}\n| director                 = [[B. P. Singh]]\n}}\n\n'''CID''' is an Indian [[police procedural]] television series about [[Maharashtra]] and [[Mumbai]]'s [[Crime Investigation Department (India)|Crime Investigation Department]], created by [[B. P. Singh]] for [[Sony Entertainment Television India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/121686/of-iconic-status.html|title=Of iconic status|last=|first=|date=|website=Deccan Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The series starred [[Shivaji Satam]] as ACP Pradyuman, [[Aditya Srivastava]] and [[Dayanand Shetty]] as Senior Inspectors Abhijeet and Daya, [[Dinesh Phadnis]] as Inspector Fredricks and Narendra Gupta as forensic expert Dr. Salunkhe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/crime/news/report-crimes-through-cid-serial-says-shivaji-satam-3879.html|title=Report crimes through CID serial, says Shivaji Satam|last=|first=|date=|website=[[India TV News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-just-what-makes-cid-so-popular-tv/20120320.htm|title=What makes CID so popular ?|last=|first=|date=|website=Rediff|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe location of the series is set in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. The series premiered on 21 January 1998 and is the longest running television series in [[India]]. The last episode aired on 27 October 2018.<ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/sony-s-iconic-cid-to-air-final-episode-on-october-27-before-returned-in-all-new-avatar/story-3z8y8I90UOmlHkBmTr6keJ.html|title=Sony\u2019s iconic CID to air final episode on October 27 before returning in all-new avatar|last=|first=|date=|website=Hindustan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The series aired its 500th episode on 26 January 2008; 1,000th episode on 27 September 2013 and 1,500th episode on 25 February 2018. The show also re-runs on [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony]]'s sister channel [[Sony Pal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/CID-Shivaji-Satam-Aditya-Srivastava-Dayanand-Shetty-Narendra-Gupta/articleshow/23095468.cms?|title=CID completes 1000 episodes|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Uniyal|first1=Parmita|title=Exclusive: Currently off air, CID will be back next month, confirms ACP Pradyuman aka Shivaji Satam|url=https://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/cid-will-be-back-next-month-confirms-acp-pradyuman-aka-shivaji-satam/1/677354.html|accessdate=26 May 2016|work=India Today|date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Shivaji Satam]] as ACP Pradyuman (1998\u20132018)\n* [[Aditya Srivastava]] as Senior Inspector Abhijeet (1999\u20132018)\n* [[Dayanand Shetty]] as Senior Inspector Daya (1998\u20132018)\n* [[Dinesh Phadnis]] as Inspector Fredricks (Freddy) (1998\u20132018)\n* [[Ansha Sayed]] as Inspector Purvi (2011\u20132018)\n* [[Ajay Nagrath]] as Sub-Inspector Pankaj (2012\u20132018)\n* [[Narendra Gupta]] as Dr.Salunke  (1998-2002, 2007\u20132018)\n* [[Shraddha Musale]] as Assistant Dr.Tarika (2007\u20132018)\n\n===Recurring===\n* Dhananjay Mandrekar as Sub-Inspector Sudhakar (1998\u20132005)\n* [[Ashwini Kalsekar]] as Inspector Asha (1998\u20132004)\n* [[Ashutosh Gowariker]] as Senior Inspector Virendra (1998\u20131999)\n* Sanjay Shemkalyanee as Sub-Inspector Desai (1998)\n* Pranav Verma as Sub-Inspector Shinde (1998)\n* Afshan Khan as Sub-Inspector Mridula (1998)\n* [[Sanjeev Seth]] as Sub-Inspector (1998)\n* [[Tushar Dalvi]] as Inspector Jayant (1999)\n* [[Shweta Kawatra]] as Dr. Niyati Pradhan (2003, 2005\u20132007)\n* Mandeep Bhandar as Dr. Vrinda Wagle (2003\u20132004)\n* [[Mona Ambegaonkar]] as Dr. Anjalika Deshmukh (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Manav Gohil]] as Inspector Daksh (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Smita Bansal]] as Inspector Aditi (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Kavita Kaushik]] as Inspector Anushka (2005\u20132006)\n* [[Sai Deodhar]] as Inspector Priyanka (2005)\n* [[Rajeev Khandelwal]] as ACP Prithviraj (2005)\n* [[Vivek V. Mashru]] as Inspector Vivek (2006\u20132012)\n* [[Alka Verma]] as Inspector Muskaan (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Amar Upadhyay]] as Inspector Rishi (2006)\n* [[Priya Wal]] as Dr. Nyla Rajadhyaksha (2006\u20132007)\n* Parinita Seth as Inspector Kaveri (2008)\n* [[Jimmy Nanda]] as Inspector Lavanya (2008\u20132009)\n* [[Megha Gupta]] as Inspector Devyana (2007\u20132008)\n* [[Vaishnavi Dhanraj]] as Inspector Tasha Kumar (2009\u20132010)\n* [[Hrishikesh Pandey]] as Inspector Sachin (2010-2016)\n*[[Abhay Shukla]] as Sub-Inspector Nikhil (2010-2016)\n* [[Jasveer Kaur]] as Inspector Kajal (2010\u20132012)\n* [[Manini Mishra]] as Dr. Sonali Barwe (2010\u20132011)\n* [[Vikas Kumar]] as Senior Inspector Rajat (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Janvi Chheda]] as Inspector Shreya (2012-2016, 2018)\n* Vineet Kumar Chaudhary as Inspector Vineet (2012\u20132013)\n* Neha Gadoria as Trainee Inspector Roma (2012)\n* Tanya Abrol as Inspector Jaywanti Shinde (2014\u20132016)\n* Jagjit Athwal as Sub-Inspector Vansh (2014\u20132016)\n* Vikas Salgotra as Sub-Inspector Mayur (2014\u20132016)\n* Pooja Khatri as Sub-Inspector Ishita (2014\u20132016)\n* Amaani Satrala as Sub-Inspector Divya (2014\u20132015)\n* Ankur Sharma Kabir as Sub-Inspector Karan (2014\u20132015)\n* [[Maninder Singh (actor) | Maninder Singh]] as Senior Inspector Dushyant Hemraj (2014)\n* [[Gaurav Khanna]] as Senior Inspector Kavin (2014)\n* Abid Shaikh as Sub-Inspector Vikram (2014)\n* [[Vivana Singh]] as Cyber Inspector Ritu (2017\u20132018)\n* [[B. P. Singh]] as DCP Shamsher Singh Chitrole (2005\u20132016)\n* [[Rahil Azam]] as Nakul (2004\u20132005, 2015)\n* [[Mahesh Manjrekar]] as Harpeez Dongara (2010)\n* [[Tarun Khanna (actor) | Tarun Khanna]] as Inspector Suraj (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Deepak Shirke]] as ACP Digvijay (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Rahul Dev]] as Katori Damta (2016)\n* [[Karmveer Choudhary]] as Pratap Singh\n* Kuldeep Singh as Dr. Vaibhav (2014)\n* [[Tigmanshu Dhulia]] as Barbosa, Leader of the Eye Gang (2018)\n* [[KK Goswami]] as Dhenchu, DCP's informer (2013-2018)\n\n==CID: Special Bureau cast (2004\u20132006)==\n* [[Anup Soni]] as ACP Ajatshatru\n* [[Salil Ankola]] as Senior Inspector Akshay\n* [[Nimai Bali]] as Senior Inspector Pratap\n* [[Hrishikesh Pandey]] as Inspector Abhimanyu\n* Sushmita Daan as Inspector Jasmine Prakash\n* [[Manasi Varma]] as Inspector Tejali\n* [[Sharad Kelkar]] as Inspector Jehan\n* Mahi as Inspector Gargi\n* Mugdha Godbole as Inspector Akansha\n* Amita Chandekar as Inspector Ashwini\n* Sachin Sharma as Inspector Samar\n* [[Kushal Punjabi]] as Inspector Kushal\n\n==CID 111 \u2013 The Inheritance==\n''CID'' got into both the [[Limca Book of Records]] and the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]] on 7 November 2004 for its record-breaking single shot episode of 111 minutes (1 hour and 51 minutes), entitled \"''The Inheritance''\" without a cut which writer \u2013 director \u2013 producer [[B. P. Singh]] feels \"''every Indian should be proud of because no one has achieved this before''\". This special episode was shot between 6:30 \u2013 8:21 PM [[Indian Standard Time|IST]] on 8 October 2004 at [[Lonavala]] and was aired on 7 November 2004 (Sunday) without a break from 8 \u2013 10 PM IST.<ref>{{cite news|title='CID' enters Limca Book of Records|url=https://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/nov032004/n9.asp|newspaper=Deccan Herald|accessdate=3 November 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115746/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/nov032004/n9.asp|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Other sub-series==\n''CID'' introduced its following sub-series during its 21 years of run on Indian Television. These sub-series aired alongside the main series:-\n* ''CID \u2013 Files'' (1998\u20132003)\n* ''CID \u2013 Special Bureau'' (2004\u20132006)\n* ''10 Years Of Glory: CID \u2013 Most Wanted'' (2007)\n* ''CID \u2013 Water Crime Stories'' (2009)\n* ''CID \u2013 Serial Killer Cases'' (2009)\n* ''CID \u2013 Brides and Murders'' (2009)\n* ''CID \u2013 Aakhri Chunauti'' (English: ''Final Challenge'') (2010)\n* ''CID \u2013 Abhijeet Ke Ateet Ka Raaz'' (English: ''The Secret of Abhijeet's Past'') (2010\u20132011)\n* ''CID \u2013 Chase'' (2011)\n* ''CID \u2013 Dhoom'' (English: ''Blast'') (2011)\n* ''CID \u2013 Grahan'' (English: ''Eclipse'') (2012)\n* ''CID \u2013 Ganga'' (2013)\n* ''CID \u2013 Mission Mumbai'' (2014)\n* ''CID \u2013 Giraftaar'' (English: ''Arrest'') (2014)\n*''CID - Nakul Ki Vaapsi (English: Nakul's Returns) (2015)''\n* ''CID \u2013 Karo Ya Maro'' (English: ''Do or Die'') (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/dayanand-shetty-promises-more-action-thrills-in-c-i-d/|title=Dayanand Shetty promises more action, thrills in \u2018C.I.D.\u2019|last=|first=|date=|website=The Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''21 Years Of Bravery: CID vs The Eye'' (2017\u20132018)\n\n==Production==\nThe pilot episode was shot in 1992, but the series premiered five years after it in 1998.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/cid-trivia-quirks-facts-and-clichs-we-bet-you-didnt-know-about/listshow/48529032.cms|title=CID trivia, quirks, facts and clich\u00e9s we bet you didn\u2019t know|last=|first=|date=|website=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Marathi theatre]] veteran, [[Shivaji Satam]], who plays ACP Pradyuman, had worked with [[B. P. Singh]] on many projects before ''CID''. He said in an interview: \"''Having worked with [[B. P. Singh]] on so many projects (initially being the Marathi sitcom Ek Shunya Shunya), I had to be a part of CID''\". [[Aditya Srivastava|Aditya Shrivastav]], who portrays Senior Inspector Abhijeet, was introduced in the show as a criminal (in episode 39 & 40 - ''The Case of the Stolen Gun'') but was later added into the team (in episode 73 & 74 - ''The Case of the Stolen Dynamite'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/soaps/story/wahiyat-wednesday-how-cid-duped-indian-audiences-for-two-decades-1637066-2020-01-15|title=Wahiyat Wednesday: How CID duped Indian audiences for two decades|last=|first=|date=|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"''I had agreed to do only 26 episodes. In 1998, I was also doing some films, and [[B. P. Singh]] Sir gave me the flexibility to come and go as I felt like. But I began to enjoy the role of Abhijeet, and so stayed on''\", said Shrivastav.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/Abhijeet-has-overpowered-Aditya-thats-my-reward/articleshow/47308677.cms|title=Abhijeet has overpowered Aditya & that\u2019s my reward|last=|first=|date=|website=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Singh wanted Srivastav to be part of his team after seeing his work in [[Ram Gopal Varma]]\u2019s ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]''. [[Dayanand Shetty]], who portrays Senior Inspector Daya was spotted by Sanjay Shetty, a member of the ''CID'' production team in a community play in which he was adjudged best actor. Singh was so impressed with Shetty that he finalized him just 5 minutes into the audition.\n\n''CID'' is primarily shot in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. During the long course of the show, the series has been shot in various locations all over [[India]]. The series has also been shot in foreign countries. Some Foreign locations have included places like [[Uzbekistan]], a major shoot in [[Paris]], and [[Switzerland]] which included tourist attractions like [[Interlaken]] as well as cities such as [[Berne]] and [[Zurich]]. The major shoot in [[Paris]]-[[Switzerland]] was for the 2 hourly special episode \"''Aakhri Chunauti''\", and a part of the production team's 13th anniversary celebration plan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Unnikrishnan|first=Chaya|title=Cops in demand|url=https://archive.indianexpress.com/news/cops-in-demand/506937/|work=[[Indian Express]]|accessdate=28 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe show was decided to end suddenly by the channel and on October 27, 2018, the last episode was aired.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/watch/cid-case-is-closed/article25400869.ece|title=CID: Case is closed|last=|first=|date=|website=The Hindu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/telly-talk/gossip/article/exclusive-dayanand-shetty-on-cid-going-off-air-the-channel-should-have-informed-us-about-it-in-advance-tv-news/304911|title=Dayanand Shetty on CID going off-air: 'The channel should have informed us about it in advance|last=|first=|date=|website=Times Now News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Rumours of the show getting cancelled was going rounds while the official statement by the channel stated  the show will go off air for three months to give the producers enough time to reboot it. Further it was reported that \u201c''CID is not wrapping up. But it is going on a short break and that\u2019s only for a creative reason. The makers haven\u2019t received any closure letter from the channel that proves that they are still in contract with them. The break has been decided mutually by the makers and channel as they want to reboot the show.''\u201d<ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\"/> But no announcement of it returning was made since then. Actor [[Dayanand Shetty]] who played Daya quoted that the show would not return after this break saying, \"''No, I don\u2019t think it\u2019s coming back. I doubt it\u2019s coming back. There can\u2019t be a break. It\u2019s just a convenient way of killing the show.''\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Other initiatives==\nBeginning on 7 July 2006; a nationwide hunt called ''Operation Talaash'' was launched, in search of a new officer to join the ''CID'' team, which ended on 1 September 2006. [[Vivek V. Mashru]] who played Sub-Inspector Vivek, was selected to play the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_another-hero-enters-cid_1053164 |title=Another hero enters CID \u2013 Entertainment \u2013 DNA |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=15 September 2006 |accessdate=6 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Sony Entertainment Television (India)|Sony Entertainment Television]] had launched ''CID: Gallantry Awards'', an initiative to encourage and honour acts of bravery in society on 26 January 2010 [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\nHonour to ordinary|url=https://archive.indianexpress.com/news/honour-to-ordinary/681974/|newspaper=The Indian Express|accessdate= 17 September 2010}}</ref> The second edition of this initiative was aired on 23 January 2011. The third and fourth editions were aired on 1 April 2012 and 14 April 2013 respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title=An award night for valiants on TV|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/An-award-night-for-valiants-on-TV/articleshow/19527055.cms|newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 July 2015; [[Sony Entertainment Television|Sony TV]] announced the Shaatir Lekhak Contest, in which 3 incomplete stories and clues were presented. Contestants were required to complete any one story out of three. The contest ended on 26 July 2015. The winning story was appeared in episodes and prizes were also given to the winner. From the total entries, 3 winners were selected, one for each story. The result for the winners were declared during one of the episodes of ''CID'' prior to 1 September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/chance-to-give-a-twist-to-cid-episode/|title=Chance to give a twist to \u2018CID\u2019 episode|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=9 July 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Crossovers==\nThe series had many crossover episodes with many series. ''CID'' had three crossover episodes with the series ''[[Aahat]]'', once on 13 November 2009; second time on  12 February 2010 and third time on 25 June 2010. It also had crossover episodes with ''[[Adaalat]]'', once on 3\u20134 December 2010; second time on 15 July 2012 titled [[CID Viruddh Adaalat]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CID joins hands with KD Pathak from Adaalat!|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/CID-joins-hands-with-KD-Pathak-from-Adaalat/articleshow/14647583.cms|newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref> and third time on 20 December 2014 titled ''CID v Adaalat \u2013 Karmyudh''.<ref name=\"Sony to screen a telefilm with CID and Adaalat's cast\">{{cite news|url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/story/42807_Sony-to-screen-a-telefilm-with-CID-and-Adaalats-cast|title=Sony to screen a telefilm with CID and Adaalat's cast|newspaper=[[afaqs!]]|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> It also had a crossover with [[Sab TV]]'s comedy series [[Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah]] for 4 episodes. Titled as \"''Mahasangram''\", it started and ended on July 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/CID-Tarak-Mehta-Ka-Oolta-Chashma-to-have-a-Mahasangram-episode/articleshow/37645778.cms|title=CID & Tarak Mehta Ka Oolta Chashma to have a Mahasangram episode \u2013 Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIt entered in both [[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World records]] and [[Limca Book of Records]] for uncut shooting for 111 minutes for the episode named '''The Inheritance''<nowiki/>' during October 2004.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n[[Rediff]] stated, \"''Its actors, or at least the core of the cast who have been a part of the series since its inception are so popular they have become household names.''\"<ref name=\"The TV show with the highest ratings\">{{cite news|url=https://movies.rediff.com/report/2010/jul/27/tv-cid-a-hit-with-viewers.htm |title=The TV show with the highest ratings|newspaper=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Times of India]] stated, \"''CID which has constantly entertained its viewers with unique and challenging cases is also known for its different jokes in the world of internet''.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Most-popular-jokes-on-CID/photostory/33440197.cms|title=Most popular jokes on CID|newspaper=Times of India|accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n[[Rediff.com|Rediff]] gave the series 4.5 / 5 stars, and stated, \"''Much of the credit for CID's success should go to [[B. P. Singh|Singh]], and its cast, especially [[Shivaji Satam]] who plays ACP Pradyuman''\".<ref name=\"The TV show with the highest ratings\"/>\n\nRahul Hedge of [[Rediff.com|Rediff]] giving the same ratings stated, \"''The crime detective series is still going strong''\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Just What Makes CID So Popular?|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-just-what-makes-cid-so-popular-tv/20120320.htm|accessdate=20 March 2012|newspaper=Rediff|author=Rahul Hedge}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+[[Indian Telly Awards]]\n! Year !! Awards !! Category !! Nominee !! Status !! Ref\n|-\n| 2002 || rowspan=10| [[Indian Telly Awards]] || Best Continuing TV Programme || Fireworks Productions || {{won||align=|style=|color=}} || <ref name=\"The Winners of The Indian Telly Awards 2002\">{{cite web|url=https://tellyawards.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/winners.htm|title=The Winners of The Indian Telly Awards 2002|work=Indian Television|access-date=1 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128175311/http://tellyawards.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/winners.htm|archive-date=28 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2002 || rowspan=2| [[Indian Telly Award for Best Actor in a Lead Role|Best Actor in a lead role]] || rowspan=2| [[Shivaji Satam]] || rowspan=2 {{won||align=|style=|color=}} || <ref>{{citation|url=http://tellyawards.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/winners.htm|title=ITA Awards 2002 Winner list|work=Indian Telly Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2003 || <ref>{{citation|url=http://tellyawards.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/personality.htm|title=ITA Awards 2003 Winner list|work=Indian Telly Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004 || Best Thriller Programme || rowspan=7| [[B. P. Singh]], [[Pradeep Uppoor]] <br> (Fireworks Production) || rowspan=7 {{won||align=|style=|color=}} 